<DOCNO> AP880620-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 0047EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Notebook Bjt   06-20 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Notebook, Bjt,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Free Lunch, No Contamination and Almost No Smoking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, the
genial host of the seven-nation economic summit, declined to
partake in the food and drink pavilions set up for hungry reporters
and delegates at the gathering.
   Mulroney toured the ``tent city,'' called Toronto Summit Square,
where journalists can eat all they want, round-the-clock and free
of charge.
   Asked if he had come by for a free lunch, the prime minister
reflected and replied: ``Is there such a thing?''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The European Community, the dozen European nations that form a
trading bloc, apparently doesn't like being taken for granted.
   The community is the eighth, and often overlooked, delegation to
the annual economic summit of industrialized democracies.
   Willy De Clercq, the bloc's commissioner for external relations
and trade policy, bristled when told a spokesman for another
delegation had implied the EC worries, especially concerning
agricultural subsidies, were given less weight because their
leaders were not elected.
   De Clercq told a news conference that the remark was a ``a very,
very characteristic example of lack of understanding and
comprehension, not to say knowledge about what the European
Community is.''
   ``Elected or not elected, the only body who decides agriculture
policy is the community as such ...''
   ``The reality is the reality and you can believe me that is the
situation, if you like it or not, and I like it,'' said De Clerq.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Canadian reporters have drawn the word ``scrum'' from the rugby
glossary and added it to the journalism lingo.
   As Mulroney toured the press area at the Metropolitan Toronto
Convention Center, he was surrounded by a mob of reporters waving
microphones, snapping pictures and shouting questions.
   ``Mulroney is having a slowly moving scrum through the
convention center,'' observed Paul Gessell, a reporter for the
Ottawa Citizen.
   Scrum, Canadians explained, is sort of like a wedge in U.S.
football. The forward linemen lock arms and heads in a fearsome
drive to resume play.
   In journalism, it refers to an impromptu news conference.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   As he left a welcoming ceremony with Mulroney, President Reagan
was asked whether he was embarrassed by the banana yellow tie that
Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III was wearing.
   ``It's Father's Day. It's the season for wild ties,'' Reagan
replied.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   If the Reagans haven't had time to consult their astrologer,
they can read what the stars hold for him in a local newspaper, the
Toronto Sun.
   The daily's astrologer, Eugenia Last, is keeping track of the
charts of all seven summit leaders.
   On Monday, she said, the 77-year-old president's ``need to
portray stamina and strength will be his main concern.''
   The U.S. president ``will have a great deal to offer,'' she
said, adding that the ``the likelihood of his being able to set a
precedent remains to be seen.''
   She had more specific advice for Mulroney.
   He should, she advised, ``take immediate action moving toward
his objectives in essence, plant the seeds of the future through
suggestion, then sit back.''
   Former White House chief of staff Donald Regan wrote in a book
this spring that Mrs. Reagan regularly consulted an astrologer
about the president's schedule.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Reporters covering British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher were
intrigued and somewhat insulted to hear security agents refer to
some of them as being ``contaminated.''
   Some sought an explanation of the pollution problem.
   It turns out that after undergoing a rigorous security check,
the reporters were supposed to be ``quarantined'' until the end of
the event they were covering.
   If the reporters came in contact with someone who had not yet
been cleared, they were considered ``contaminated'' and in need of
yet another security check.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Mulroney complained to Japanese Premier Noboru Takeshita that
Japan refuses to allow direct commercial flights between Canada and
Japan.
   ``We have very little land space. We have no room in our
airports,'' Takeshita explained to the host of the 14th annual
economic summit.
   ``That's OK, we'll use small planes,'' quipped Mulroney.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Toronto prides itself on having the toughest anti-smoking law in
North America. Smoking is prohibited in all public buildings. Well,
almost all.
   The law has been eased this weekend to allow reporters,
delegates and others attending the economic summit to pursue their
habits in the Metropolitan Toronto Convention Center, normally
considered a public building.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
