<DOCNO> AP880620-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 0048EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Summit-Text     06-20 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Summit-Text,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of a statement issued Sunday by
Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney on behalf of the summit
leaders. It was read by Canadian Finance Minister Michael Wilson:
   The leaders have had an excellent and free-wheeling discussion,
led off by a far-ranging statement by Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher. This was followed by a vigorous and comprehensive review
of major concerns of President Reagan, Chancellor Kohl, President
Mitterrand, Prime Minister Takeshita, Prime Minister De Mita and
President Delors.
   The idea of holding an initial working session among leaders has
clearly proved its worth. There was a productive and spontaneous
discussion which lasted about three-quarters of an hour longer than
had been anticipated. The discussion has given a focus to the
agenda and an opportunity for each leader to indicate their
priority concerns.
   The leaders are all conscious that this is the end of the second
cycle of summits. Since the last summit in Canada, in 1981, great
progress has been made in restoring and sustaining growth, winding
down inflation and facilitating structural reforms.
   Cooperation through summits has facilitated these results. The
response to the Oct. 19 stock market crisis, and the
better-than-expected performance of the world economy since then
show just how far this cooperation has developed and succeeded. It
has generated renewed confidence in financial markets.
   The leaders agreed, though, that there is no room for
complacency. Difficult challenges remain.
   On macroeconomic policies, our countries must develop further
our economic coordination efforts. Sound policies must be continued.
   On trade, they all agreed to resist protectionism and insure the
midterm review in Montreal gives a strong signal of progress.
   The Canada-U.S.A. free trade agreement was strongly welcomed, as
was the European Community Internal Market Initiative.
   On agriculture, concern was expressed at the market distortions
and budget costs posed by agricultural subsidization, both for
ourselves and the LDCs (lesser developed countries). There is a
need for impetus to the continuing efforts of reform. On that, the
leaders recognized their joint responsibility with the LDCs to find
solutions.
   For the poorest countries, they agreed to focus on new debt
relief options.
   They've also touched on other issues such as the environment,
population growth and technology.
   In sum, this has been a most useful opening to the deliberations
of the leaders.
   Although we as leading industrialized nations still face
challenges, we all feel we've made real progress in recent years.
Our message is and should be one of confidence and optimism in
dealing with the challenges confronting us.
   All this has in large part stemmed from the cooperation among
us, as symbolized by this meeting in Toronto.
</TEXT>
