<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-RookiesandVeterans     06-20 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Rookies and Veterans,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De Mita Summit Rookie, Thatcher Breaks Attendance Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian Prime Minister Ciriaco De Mita is the
rookie at this year's economic summit, while Margaret Thatcher of
Britain is breaking attendance records at the annual seven-nation
gathering.
   Mrs. Thatcher, in office since 1979 and re-elected to an
unprecedented third term in 1987, is attending her 10th summit.
``There's no one else who's into double digits,'' said her
spokesman Bernard Ingham. The runner-up is President Reagan, who is
attending his eighth and final summit.
   In deference to Mrs. Thatcher, Canadian Prime Minister Brian
Mulroney _ the host of this year's gathering _ asked her to lead
off the discussions when the leaders gathered Sunday for the first
session. She outlined for her fellow leaders the previous 13
summits with a perspective few of the others can share.
   Noburo Takeshita of Japan is attending his seventh economic
summit, although it is his first as prime minister. He attended
other summits as the Japanese finance minister.
   ``He has a lot of experience,'' said Japanese Foreign Ministry
spokesman Koichi Haraguchi.
   Takeshita, who took office last Nov. 6, has held bilateral
meetings with Reagan and Mrs. Thatcher, as well as French President
Francois Mitterrand.
   De Mita, in office since April, has had no experience at the
annual economic meeting, but did serve as minister of foreign trade
in the 1970s.
   ``He's had one month of briefings'' on more recent foreign
economic developments and is ``very well prepared,'' said his
spokesman, Nazarro Pagani.
   In his two months in office, De Mita has met several of the
summit leaders. Last week he sat next to West German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl at a European Soccer Cup match between their two
countries, and then flew to Washington to call on Reagan.
   He met with Mrs. Thatcher for the first time Sunday morning,
``and found her a very sympathetic woman, even though she is a
Conservative,'' Pagani said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
