<2ND_LINE>BC-Airport List,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Air Safety Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the airport areas subject to new
requirements for altitude-tracking equipment aboard small, private
planes, according to the Federal Aviation Administration.
   At 23 terminal control areas, planes must have Mode-C
transponders after July 1, 1989 if flying within 30 miles of the
airport:
   Atlanta; Boston; Chicago (O'Hare); Cleveland, Dallas-Fort Worth;
Denver; Detroit; Honolulu; Houston; Kansas City, Mo.; Las Vegas,
Nev.; Los Angeles; Miami; Minneapolis-St. Paul; New Orleans; New
York (LaGuardia, JFK and Newark); Philadelphia; Pittsburgh; St.
Louis; San Diego; San Franciso; Seattle-Tacoma, and Washington
(National).
   Airports where planes must have Mode-C transponders after Dec.
30, 1990 when flying within an Airport Radar Service Area, or ARSA:
   ALABAMA: Birmingham, Huntsville, Mobile.
   ALASKA: Anchorage.
   ARIZONA: Davis-Monthan AFB, Phoenix, Tucson.
   ARKANSAS: Little Rock.
   CALIFORNIA: Beale AFB, Burbank, Castle AFB, McClellan AFB, March
AFB, Mather AFB, Norton AFB, Oakland, Ontario, Sacramento, Santa
Ana.
   CONNECTICUT: Windsor Locks (Bradly International)
   FLORIDA: Daytona Beach, Fort Lauderdale, Fort Myers,
Jacksonville, Orlando, Palm Beach, Pensacola Naval Air Station,
Pensacola (regional), Sarasota, Tallahassee, Tampa, Whiting AFB.
   GEORGIA: Columbus, Savannah.
   HAWAII: Kahului
   IDAHO: Boise
   ILLINOIS: Champaign, Chicago (Midway), Springfield.
   INDIANA: Evansville, Fort Wayne, Indianapolis, South Bend.
   IOWA: Cedar Rapids, Des Moines.
   KANSAS: Wichita.
   KENTUCKY: Covington, Lexington, Louisville.
   LOUISIANA: Barksdale AFB, Lafayette, Shreveport.
   MAINE: Portland.
   MARYLAND: Baltimore (BWI)
   MICHIGAN: Flint, Grand Rapids, Lansing.
   MISSISSIPPI: Columbus, Jackson.
   NEBRASKA: Omaha, Offutt AFB.
   NEVADA: Reno.
   NEW JERSEY: Atlantic City.
   NEW MEXICO: Albuquerque.
   NEW YORK: Albany, Buffalo, Islip, Rochester, Syracuse.
   NORTH CAROLINA: Charlotte, Fayetteville, Greensboro, Pope AFB,
Raleigh.
   OHIO: Columbus, Dayton, Toledo.
   OKLAHOMA: Oklahoma City, Tinker AFB, Tulsa.
   OREGON: Portland.
   PENNSYLVANIA: Allentown.
   PUERTO RICO: San Juan.
   RHODE ISLAND: Providence.
   SOUTH CAROLINA: Charleston, Columbia, Greer, Shaw.
   TENNESSEE: Chatanooga, Knoxville, Nashville, Memphis.
   TEXAS: Abilene, Amarillo, Austin, Corpus Christi, Dallas (Love
Field), Dyess AFB, El Paso, Houston (Hobby), Laughlin AFB, Lubbock,
Midland, San Antonio.
   UTAH: Salt Lake City.
   VERMONT: Burlington.
   VIRGINIA: Chantilly (Washington Dulles International), Richmond,
Norfolk, Roanoke.
   WASHINGTON: Fairchild AFB, Spokane
   WISCONSIN: Madison, Milwaukee
   (Note: There are no airports with ARSA airspace in Colorado,
Delaware, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Missouri, Montana, New
Hampshire, North Dakota, South Dakota, West Virginia and Wyoming.)
   Two airports have been specially ``designated'' as falling under
the regulation prohibting planes without Mode-C equipment within 10
miles after Dec. 30, 1990 even though they have no ARSA airspace:
Billings, Mont., and Fargo, N.D.
