<DOCNO> AP880620-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 0135EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Security Bjt   06-20 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Security, Bjt,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amid Extraordinary Security, Arrests, IRA Scare, Reagan Red Alert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police charged chanting protesters, a
suspected Irish Republican Army operative was detained and a ``red
alert'' delayed President Reagan's motorcade as the economic summit
began with a host of security problems.
   A 3,000-strong security team, comprised of eight police and
defense forces, has responsibility for protecting the world
leaders, 1,500 officials and 3,000 reporters at the seven-nation
meeting.
   In unprecedented scenes for this peaceful city, a special summit
tactical squad was deployed Sunday when about 1,500 protesters
defied police orders and tried to march to summit headquarters
after a song-filled rally.
   They wanted to deliver a citizen's warrant for the arrest of
Reagan and the six other summit leaders for alleged ``crimes
against humanity'' ranging from U.S. backing for the Nicaraguan
Contras to ignoring the world's poor.
   When armed police blockaded University Avenue, the broad
thoroughfare leading to the summit venue, about 60 protesters
hurled themselves over crowd control barriers and were grabbed by
the riot squad.
   Supporters chanted ``Arrest the G-7,'' referring to the summit
group, and ``Arrest the real terrorists.''
   One demonstrator burned an American flag while others ignited
cardboard caricatures of the leaders and set light to newspaper
boxes containing USA Today and the Wall Street Journal.
   After three hours, SWAT teams backed by six mounted policemen
linked arms and swept across the intersection, shouting ``Move,
move, move'' as they advanced. About 30 demonstrators sat in the
roadway and sang ``Give Peace a Chance'' before they were dragged
away.
   Police said 138 were arrested, one on assault charges and the
others on charges of breaching the peace.
   Security fears were underscored by the arrest in Toronto of
Michael Derrick Collins, 31, suspected of being a low-level IRA
operative, on charges of overstaying his visa. Collins is being
sought by police in British-run Northern Ireland, according to a
spokesman for Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   Mrs. Thatcher narrowly escaped injury in an IRA bombing in 1984.
   James McAllister, an elected official of Sinn Fein, the IRA's
political wing, addressed the anti-summit demonstration and later
told reporters he did not know Collins. He said it was unlikely the
IRA would plan any attack on the Toronto summit.
   ``When they get Maggie, they'd prefer to get her on her own
ground _ Ireland or Britain,'' said McAllister.
   Two smaller protest groups appeared outside the 15-foot-high
fence around the city's convention center, where the leaders meet.
About 100 Canadians of Croatian descent demonstrated against
alleged persecution of Croatians in Yugoslavia, and eight Japanese
Buddhist monks in saffron robes chanted for peace.
   A ``red alert'' was declared as Reagan's motorcade took him from
Toronto airport to downtown, causing his armored limousine to slow
down. White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater explained later that
security forces had spotted a man carrying a bag marked
``ammunition'' _ but it turned out to contain only his lunch.
   And there was a minor accident along the motorcade route as
Reagan left the Royal York Hotel to a town square to be greeted by
Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney.
   A white canvas tent that had been erected in front of the hotel
to shelter the president's limousine became snagged on a bumper of
one of the motorcade vehicles as the motorcade pulled out.
   The tent collapsed and was dragged into the street, but no one
was injured. The tent was quickly cleared away and the motorcade
continued on its way.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880620-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 0143EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     06-20 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAUGATUCK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam veterans held a conciliatory
meeting with actress Jane Fonda, then began taking down signs
promoting the sale of bumper stickers that read ``I'm not Fond'a
Hanoi Jane.''
   About 25 Connecticut and Massachusetts veterans met Saturday
night with Fonda, who angered U.S. soldiers in Vietnam when she
traveled to North Vietnam in 1972.
   The meeting followed protests by some veterans of her plans to
film part of a movie near here this summer.
   Fonda apologized on national television last week for hurting
veterans with some of her anti-war activities, including posing for
photos next to a North Vietnamese anti-aircraft gun during the trip
to Hanoi and saying prisoners of war were lying about having been
tortured.
   Brian Powell, who served in Vietnam in 1969-70, said Fonda told
the veterans that ``in her anti-war passion she did some things
that were very stupid and very hurtful to Vietnam veterans.''
   Powell, 37, said Fonda's message was ``she was not anti-veteran,
she was anti-war.''
   Fonda said in a statement Sunday that she had wanted to meet
with local veterans since January, when protests heated up over her
plans to film ``Union Street'' in nearby Waterbury and in Holyoke,
Mass.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: language in 4th graf, ``Then the ...'' may be offensive to</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   some readers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activist Abbie Hoffman says he was booted off a
Continental Airlines plane at O'Hare International Airport after a
stewardess wrongly accused him of smoking marijuana in the lavatory.
   Friday's incident occurred after Hoffman boarded a flight for
Newark, N.J., the 51-year-old former Yippie leader said in a
telephone interview Sunday from Northampton, Mass., where he was
attending an anti-nuclear rally.
   Hoffman said he went into the lavatory minutes before takeoff.
Suddenly, fire alarm bells started ringing.
   ``Then the stewardess pushes in the door with her knee like a
storm trooper, and starts shouting, `You've been smoking
marijuana!''' Hoffman said. ``I said, `Like hell, bring on the
dogs. I'm not smoking anything.'''
   Hoffman said he was ordered off the plane, was briefly
questioned by an official, then allowed to board Continental's next
flight to Newark.
   Ned Walker, a Continental spokesman, said it was company policy
not to release passenger names, but confirmed that a male passenger
was ordered off the flight.
   He said crew members and passengers ``smelled a burning odor
coming from the lavatory'' after smoke alarms went off while the
plane was refueling.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elvis Presley's maroon nylon underpants, Michael
Jackson's fedora and Bob Dylan's handwritten lyrics were among the
mound of rock 'n' roll memorabilia that fetched more than $500,000
on the auction block.
   The parcel of Presley's personal items, including the
underpants, an electric razor, hairbrush and black socks, went for
$605, said Laura Stewart, a spokeswoman for Sotheby's auction house.
   A Gibson model J-200 guitar Presley used in the late 1950s and
early 1960s sold for $27,500, the top price paid at Saturday's
auction, Ms. Stewart said.
   Jackson's autographed fedora sold for $4,125.
   Dylan's handwritten lyrics for ``I Want You'' went for $8,800, a
John Lennon gray wool suit fetched $3,300 and one of Lennon's
guitar straps sold for $8,250, she said.
   About 30 bidders and more than 300 spectators gathered to see
226 lots of memorabilia that sold for $533,477, Ms. Stewart said.
The T.J. Martell Foundation for Leukemia, Cancer and AIDS Research
received $127,600 of the proceeds, she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Humorist Erma Bombeck said she could sense many of
the students attending Northeastern University's commencement were
worried venturing out into the world for the first time.
   ``I tend to agree with ... Woody Allen who, when he was asked if
he wanted to live forever in the hearts of his contemporaries,
said, `I just want to go on living in my own apartment,''' Bombeck,
51, told a near-capacity crowd Sunday at Boston Garden.
   The newspaper columnist and author encouraged the nearly 2,460
undergraduates to relish life's commonplace events during their
pursuit of success.
   ``Success isn't some large plateau of champagne wishes and
caviar dreams. Success is a condition that dwells inside of every
one of you and surfaces in your life when you least expect it.''
</TEXT>
