<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Cambodia     06-20 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Cambodia,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Message From Cambodia Resistance Leader Seeks `Peacekeeping' Force</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita brought
to the seven-nation economic summit a message from Cambodian
resistance leader Norodom Sihanouk calling for an international
peacekeeping force to secure ``the freedom, sovereignty and safety
of Cambodia.''
   The message also called for an end to all forms of assistance to
Vietnam, Japanese delegation press officer Koichi Haraguchi said in
a briefing early today.
   Haraguchi said Takeshita briefly mentioned Sihanouk's message at
a dinner meeting of presidents and prime ministers attending the
summit Sunday night. He said Japanese Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno
spelled out the details in a separate meeting with his counterparts.
   Haraguchi said Japan might make a non-military contribution to a
United Nations peacekeeping force. He said the Japanese would also
consider a financial contribution toward the resettling of
Cambodian refugees.
   Among the foreign ministers, he said, ``I would say there was
basic support for Prince Sihanouk and basically the atmosphere was
to support his message.''
   Haraguchi said that Sihanouk's message, as outlined by Uno, said
free elections were not feasible under either the Cambodian
government installed by Vietnam after its 1978 invasion or under
the Khmer Rouge, the strongest rebel force.
   ``Even if Vietnamese forces make a concrete withdrawal,
Sihanouk's forces will not be able to secure the freedom,
sovereignty and safety of Cambodia unless strong international
peacekeeping forces are introduced,'' the message as reported by
Haraguchi said.
   ``It is high time for the international community to put an end
to the situation of the invasion of Cambodia and the violation of
human rights,'' Sihanouk was quoted as saying.
   ``To secure withdrawal, the mst effective and peaceful means is
to stop all forms of economic assistance to Vietnam,'' Haraguchi
quoted Sihanouk as telling the foreign ministers.
   The government of Cambodian Premier Hun Sen, the three guerrilla
factions, Vietnam, and other nations are preparing to attend peace
talks in Jakarta, Indonesia, in July.
   The makeup of a new government was a key point of contention
that led to the break-off in previous talks between Hun Sen and
Sihanouk.
</TEXT>
