<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Singleton-Tampa Bjt   06-20 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Singleton-Tampa, Bjt,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worried Neighbors Call Meeting, Collect Signatures To Oust Rapist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Word that rapist-mutilator Lawrence Singleton
has moved to a quiet neighborhood here has triggered fear and
outrage mirroring the reaction in six California towns he was
forced to flee after his parole last year.
   People are collecting petition signatures, and have called a
meeting for tonight in hopes of getting Singleton to leave. A radio
station and a car dealership have offered the Tampa native $10,000
and a one-way ticket to clear out.
   ``A lot of people around here are angry, hostile and afraid. We
want to avoid vigilante behavior and mistakes,'' said Art Lawrence,
a parole officer and father of two teen-agers in the Forest Hills
neighborhood.
   Singleton, 60, gave authorities a Forest Hills address last week
in complying with state law requiring felons moving to Florida to
register a residence. The address belongs to Singleton's brother,
Walter.
   Walter Singleton says his brother isn't living with him and
won't reveal where he is. However, some residents are convinced
Lawrence Singleton is living in their quiet, middle-class
neighborhood.
   Singleton was convicted of raping a 15-year-old hitchhiker,
chopping her arms off with an ax and leaving her for dead near San
Francisco in 1978. The gray-bearded former merchant seaman spent
eight years of a 14-year sentence in a California prison.
   ``We have somebody with a record of brutality and perversion who
has not surfaced,'' Lawrence said Saturday. ``Mothers are telling
their kids to beware of men with beards. How disruptive this is to
a community!''
   ``He's going to have a hard time living anywhere,'' added Forest
Hills retiree Robert Hosack. ``He might as well be in jail.''
   Hillsborough County sheriff's Col. Cal Henderson said
authorities cannot force Singleton out.
   California residents protested when their communities were
mentioned as potential homes for Singleton during his year on
parole. He was forced to flee six towns, and eventually wound up in
a mobile home on the grounds of San Quentin prison.
   When his parole ended in April, he was a free man.
   At tonight's meeting, residents plan to discuss what legal
recourse, if any, they have in order to force Singleton to leave.
They have invited police and elected officials.
   Hundreds of signatures seeking Singleton's ouster have been
collected on petitions circulated by Forest Hills residents, said
Lawrence. The petitions will eventually be presented to officials,
he said.
   ``Legally, he has a right to be where he wants to be,'' said
resident Lester Heitlinger. ``And I want him to have his rights,
but I don't want him to have his rights in my neighborhood. I don't
want to have to worry about an ogre living near.
   ``My wife and I saw him out walking at 8:10 the other morning,''
said Heitlinger, who lives a half mile from Walter Singleton. ``I'm
absolutely positive it was the same face I saw in the newspaper.''
   However, Winston Whittle, who lives across the street from
Walter Singleton, said he hasn't seen Lawrence Singleton.
   ``He's got no reason to lie,'' Whittle said of Walter Singleton.
``He couldn't be hiding his brother inside forever.''
   Whittle said he's had two mailboxes destroyed in recent days,
presumably by vandals who mistook his home for Singleton's.
   Singleton has been constant fodder on Tampa Bay area talk shows,
with listeners suggesting he be shipped far from Florida.
   In a full-page newspaper ad Thursday, Bradenton car dealer Tom
Stimus said Singleton was ``not fit to live among decent human
beings.'' He offered Singleton $5,000, a one-way ticket anywhere
and rent and utilities for six months at Singleton's new address.
   Stimus previously offered rewards for the assassination of
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi and Iran's Ayatollah Khomeini.
   St. Petersburg radio station WQYK-FM matched Stimus' $5,000
offer after hundreds of people responding to an on-air poll said
they wanted Singleton to leave, according to spokeswoman Diana
Thomas.
</TEXT>
