<HEAD>Quiet Talks Over Delegate Numbers in New Jersey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of Jesse Jackson and Michael
Dukakis are negotiating over Jackson's claim that he should have
more than nine New Jersey delegates at the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta next month.
   Jackson won nine of the 71 delegates up for grabs in the New
Jersey primary on June 7, but his backers say he deserved more
because he got 33 percent of the popular vote.
   State party officials said talks are going on over whether
Dukakis should relinquish some of his New Jersey delegates to
Jackson.
   Officials are hoping to resolve the issue before Tuesday night,
when 38 at-large and other delegates are to be chosen at the state
Democratic convention.
   ``It's the Dukakis campaign's goal to have a unified party
before Atlanta, at Atlanta, and after the convention,'' said Harold
Hodes, a New Jersey lobbyist and a leader in Dukakis' New Jersey
campaign.
   Hodes said the issue will be resolved before Tuesday night. He
said he has talked with Newark Mayor Sharpe James, who directed
state campaign, and will meet with him again.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kitty Dukakis Recovering Quickly From Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis, who celebrates her 25th
wedding anniversary today with her husband, Democratic presidential
nominee-to-be Michael S. Dukakis, said she is fast recovering from
recent neck surgery.
   Mrs. Dukakis, 51, who underwent surgery at Massachusetts General
Hospital on June 3, said she is not taking any medication for pain.
   ``I have a little bit of hip pain, but nothing compared to what
I thought it would be like,'' said Mrs. Dukakis. ``And no
discomfort in my neck at all, except for having to wear the
collar.''
   Her operation was on two herniated spinal disks, which caused
numbness in her arms and legs.
   Mrs. Dukakis said she has recently taken walks around the
Brookline neighborhood where she lives.
   ``She's really on her way, (and is) physically and emotionally
in very good shape,'' said Sandy Bakalar, a close friend of Mrs.
Dukakis and the person who introduced her to the Massachusetts
governor. ``She can't wait to get to the (Democratic national)
convention.''
