<DOCNO> AP880620-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 0321EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KerouacMemorial Bjt   06-20 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kerouac Memorial, Bjt,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beat Author Kerouac Honored In Native City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For nearly two decades the only memorial to
``beat generation'' author Jack Kerouac in his hometown was his
grave, where fans left offerings like a bottle of burgundy wine,
two cigarettes and a wilted rose.
   This week, the first official Kerouac memorial in Lowell will be
dedicated with a gathering of boyhood friends and writers like
Allen Ginsberg who, with Kerouac, expressed disillusionment with
mainstream America in the 1950s.
   ``Kerouac is to Lowell, as Thoreau is to Concord or Steinbeck is
to Salinas (Calif.),'' said Paul Marion, cultural affairs directors
for the Lowell Historic Preservation Commission, which coordinated
construction of the memorial. ``It will be a focal point for the
pilgrims.''
   In his early novels, Kerouac nostalgically portrayed this
northeastern Massachusetts city of mills and ethnic neighborhoods.
It became a brief sanctuary in his last years, when he was bloated
from booze and unable to write. He died in St. Petersburg, Fla., at
age 47 of a hemorrhage.
   The $100,000 memorial is an arrangement of 3-by-8-foot granite
panels bearing 15 passages from some of Kerouac's 20 books and
essays, including the so-called Lowell novels ``Doctor Sax,'' ``The
Town and the City'' and the classic ``On the Road.''
   Houston sculptor Ben Woitena said he arranged the panels in a
cross and circle pattern to represent the strong Roman Catholic
values of Kerouac's youth and his later exploration of Buddhism.
The polished reddish-brown stone reflects the red-brick mills and
canals that symbolized working-class Lowell to Kerouac.
   The site is less than a mile from the French-Canadian
neighborhood where Kerouac was raised and a block from The Sun
newspaper, which fired him after a brief stint as a young
sportswriter.
   Saturday's dedication will highlight a week of Kerouac-related
events, including poetry readings by Kerouac friends Ginsberg and
Lawrence Ferlinghetti.
   Two of Kerouac's three wives, Edith Parker Kerouac of Detroit
and Lowell-born Stella Sampas Kerouac, are expected to meet for the
first time since Kerouac's funeral. Kerouac's 36-year-old daughter,
Janet, also is to attend.
   The memorial's focus on literature, rather than Kerouac's
lifestyle, won over a contingent of residents who were opposed to a
large tribute to Kerouac, whom they saw as a symbol or decadence
and irreverence.
   ``It's good that they are finally remembering him for his
works,'' said the Rev. Armand Morrissette, who was Kerouac's
boyhood confidant and eulogized him at his funeral. ``He was a man
of great compassion and sincerity. He was much more than just a
drunk.''
   ``Kerouac saw all the world through Lowell. It was his reference
point for all the people and places he wrote about in his life,''
Ginsberg said in a telephone interview. ``To Jack, Lowell was a
sacred place. It's fitting that Lowell, in turn, makes Jack
sacred.''
   Kerouac, born Jean-Louis Lebris de Kerouac in 1922, spoke only
the French-Canadian ``patois'' until grade school.
   Although he often recalled his Lowell boyhood, Kerouac rarely
returned after leaving in 1939 for Columbia University in New York
City, where he was adopted into a circle of friends that included
Ginsberg and William Burroughs. He did, however, make his home in
Lowell for about a year during the mid-1960s before moving to
Florida.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
