<HEAD>Shares Dip, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS style of time element thruout</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell for
the first time in six days today, while the dollar closed slightly
higher against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the market's
main index, dipped 203.43 points, or 0.71 percent, from Friday's
close to finish the day's session at 28,139.03.
   The Nikkei index closed at 28,342.46 on Friday, the fifth
consecutive day it posted record highs. Trading was sluggish today
with 1.2 billion shares changing hands, compared with 1.7 billion
Friday.
   An official of Nomura Securities Co., who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said investors were restrained because there were no
fresh incentives following active trading last week.
   He said some investors wanted to monitor the development of the
Toronto summit of seven industrialized nations because a new world
monetary policy might be discussed.
   In the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at
126.09 yen, up 0.36 yen from Friday's close. The dollar opened at
125.84 yen and ranged between 125.82 yen and 126.14 yen.
   Volume totaled $4.1 billion, compared with nearly $5 billion
Friday.
