<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RampMurders     06-20 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ramp Murders,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fear, Anger Grip City After Killings Of Women In Parking Ramps</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: `Deane' cq in 20th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BAENEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The daytime murders of two women in parking
ramps and a series of other attacks have brought fear and anger to
this city, which prides itself on its small-town values and low
crime rate.
   ``We're being infected by America's values,'' Police Chief Tony
Bouza said.
   In response, many women are enrolling in self-defense classes,
businesses are beefing up security and sales of Mace and whistles
have been brisk.
   ``We talk about our quality of life. We say we're above this,
these things don't happen (here). They happen in Chicago or L.A. or
New York,'' said City Councilwoman Barbara Carlson. ``And all of
sudden murders like this occur and you realize they can happen.
They are happening. What do we do?''
   Carrie Coonrod, a 19-year-old student on her way to a job
interview, was stabbed to death May 27 in a downtown parking
garage. A suspect, who was released from a Nebraska prison in March
after serving time for a sex offense, was arrested three hours
later.
   Sixteen days later, Mary Catherine Foley, 34, a manager at
Honeywell Inc., was strangled in the company's parking ramp. No
arrests have been made.
   Other events have heightened the tension:
   _A 44-year-old drifter, Billy Glaze, was indicted Tuesday on
first-degree murder charges in the 1986-1987 deaths and sexual
mutilation of three women.
   _On June 3, a man assaulted a 26-year-old woman in an isolated
part of the skyway pedestrian system linking downtown businesses.
The man fled after the woman screamed, alerting passers-by.
   _An attorney was abducted from her downtown office the evening
of May 22 and repeatedly raped in a 13-hour ordeal. A building
security guard has been charged in the assault.
   Gov. Rudy Perpich has scheduled a meeting Wednesday with
representatives of Twin Cities businesses and government to
determine what help the state can give.
   In the last couple of weeks, 48 self-defense workshops have been
scheduled and more are pending, said Lucy Gerold, director of
community crime prevention for the city. Normally, about 12
workshops are provided a year.
   ``I think it's fear,'' Ms. Gerold explained.
   Some businesses are buying employees Mace or providing escorts
to cars.
   The law firm of Robins, Zelle, Larson and Kaplan bought about
200 aerosol cans of Mace for employees, said managing partner Tom
Kayser. Within 1{ hours, the cans were gone, Kayser said.
   Abbott Northwestern Hospital bought about 4,500 ``shriek
alarms,'' pressurized canisters that emit a piercing whistle, for
employees, said spokeswoman Megan O'Hara. A radio station announced
plans to give away 5,000 police whistles.
   A store that sells Mace, a chemical irritant used to disable an
attacker, had sold out its supply and was awaiting a new shipment.
   ``We have orders for over 1,000 in the last two days and
normally we would sell a gross (144),'' said Deane Rusinko, a
salesman at Uniforms Unlimited.
   ``The last few days the majority of our time has been spent
answering the phone and filling orders. I've never seen anything
like it, ever,'' Rusinko said.
   In this city of 360,000 people, there have been 27 killings this
year, compared with 23 at the same time in 1987 when there were a
record 48 slayings for the year, Deputy Police Chief Bob Lutz said.
   Chief Bouza called the parking ramp killings ``isolated,
aberrational acts,'' and said reports of other violent crimes
actually declined this year.
   Susan Hanstead, who works at a downtown law firm, said she feels
Minneapolis is safer than her hometown of Chicago.
   ``Notwithstanding what just happened, I feel OK here,'' said Ms.
Hanstead, whose law firm ordered Mace and organized a self-defense
class. ``I think I'm more angry than I am afraid right now.''
</TEXT>
