<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SwedishWedding     06-20 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swedish Wedding,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Wins Elaborate Wedding After 12-Year Transcontinental
Courtship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARREN MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wait has ended for Lena Sofia
Bergstrand and Frank Young, who met nearly a dozen years ago in
Sweden and carried on a transatlantic courtship before a fairy-tale
wedding won through patience.
   Forty fiddlers, the 80-voice Orphei Drangar men's chorus and
musicians from the Gothenburg Symphony _ all from Sweden _ helped
create the elaborate traditional Swedish wedding Sunday.
   Bergstrand and Young said goodbye almost 12 years ago when he
returned to the United States after a nine-month courtship during
his exchange student days in Sweden. Both thought then their
romance was over.
   But they couldn't forget each other. They exchanged hundreds of
telephone calls and letters between Albany, N.Y., and Johanneshov,
Sweden, and got together about twice each year.
   So when the minister read from the Bible that ``Love is patient,
love is kind,'' the passage had special meaning for the 27-year-old
bride, an insurance company secretary in Sweden, and 28-year-old
groom, a commercial pilot.
   The ceremony, part of the 10-day ``Midsummer, a Minnesota
Festival of Music'' at Highland Lake Park Reserve, was ``the kind
of wedding celebration little girls dream about _ filled with
dancers, sweet music, pageantry, flowers and poetry,'' said Jan
Strand, co-director of New Sweden Minnesota, part of the yearlong
national celebration commemorating the 350th anniversary of Swedish
immigration to the United States.
   Celebration organizers chose Young and Bergstrand as winners of
the wedding from among hundreds of applicants in the international
competition, Strand said.
   ``Their story of young love kept alive across a dozen years and
thousands of miles is a truly classic story of romance and
commitment,'' Strand said.
   The wedding festivities began with a procession led by
standard-bearers carrying four U.S. and four Swedish flags.
Horse-drawn Swedish hay wagons, colorful ethnic dancers, strolling
musicians and folk fiddlers followed, and a carriage drawn by white
horses held the bride and groom, who wore traditional Swedish
wedding attire.
   After the procession, a 1,500-pound, 60-foot Swedish Maypole
topped with a rooster and the blue-and-yellow Swedish flag was
raised by hand by about 24 men using crossed wood beams.
   Then came the ceremony, attended by about 2,000 people of
Scandinavian descent and other onlookers who covered the hillside
overlooking the stage.
   Organizers, who had invited the public and expected a crowd of
10,000, said the 98-degree heat kept many away. Nonetheless, some
came in party dresses and Swedish folk costumes.
   The groom and his two attendants wore moosehide knicker-type
britches with wool socks, wool vests and heavy wool-lined jackets _
and must have sweltered.
   Bergstrand's wedding dress, and those of her two attendants,
were made from fabric, materials and patterns sent from Leksand,
Sweden, according to the folk-costume tradition of that area.
   The wedding dress had a red silk brocade bodice, white linen
damask scarf and blouse and black wool skirt, topped by a blue wool
apron with a special glazed finish.
   ``We're very happy that we're finally going to be together,''
Bergstrand told a news conference before the wedding. ``It's like a
dream come true.''
   Following a honeymoon in Denmark, Sweden and Norway, the couple
will make their home in Albany.
   Strand said the cost of the wedding was unknown because several
corporate sponsors helped pay expenses and most of the labor was
volunteered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
