<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Waha     06-20 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Waha,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former AP Vienna Bureau Chief Dies In Car Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eric Waha, an Associated Press newsman
for 31 years and former Vienna chief of bureau for the news agency,
has died in a single-vehicle car crash. He was 63.
   A police report said Waha was alone in his car Sunday when it
went off a country highway about 12 miles from Vienna and smashed
into a tree.
   Waha, a native of Vienna, joined the AP in 1953 and became
Vienna bureau chief in 1965. He left Vienna in 1979 to become a
representative of AP Dow Jones in Hong Kong.
   He later returned to Europe where he served as AP correspondent
in East Berlin for 2{ years before his retirement in 1984.
   In 1956, he was among the Western correspondents covering the
Hungarian uprising and was arrested. He was released several days
later and expelled from Hungary.
   Waha also covered the 1968 Soviet-led invasion of
Czechoslovakia, directing coverage both in Vienna and in the
Czechoslovak capital of Prague.
   He organized coverage of the 1964 winter Olympics in Innsbruck,
Austria, and again played a key role in the AP report on the 1976
Olympics there.
   Among other major sport events he covered was the 1972 winter
Olympics in Sapporo, Japan. His last assignmant was the 1984 Winter
Olympics in Sarajevo, Yugoslavia.
   Waha's favorite sport was soccer. He was an amateur soccer
player and covered international matches in Austria and Eastern
Europe.
   As a bureau chief, he managed the AP's business and
administrative affairs in Austria, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia,
Hungary, Romania and Yugoslavia.
   He also served for many years as secretary of the Austrian
foreign press club.
   Waha, who was unmarried, is survived by a brother, Norbert.
</TEXT>
