<HEAD>Lingering Clouds, Showers And Thunderstorms Over Much Of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cloudy skies, isolated showers and thunderstorms lingered over
much of the nation today after wracking parts of the central and
southeastern United States with fierce winds and hail the size of
softballs.
   The storm systems produced severe weather Sunday afternoon and
early evening but then dissipated.
   In Georgia, strong thunderstorm winds blew trees onto power
lines at Moran and downed several trees at Bolingbroke. The high
winds also blew over a tin shed near Holly Ridge, La. In Minnesota,
strong gusts brought down trees, a small garage and a barn.
   Large hail hammered parts of Wisconsin. Martel reported hail the
size of ping pong balls, Baldwin had golf ball-sized hail, and an
area north of River Falls was blasted by hail as big as softballs.
   Record highs were recorded Sunday in the Midwest and Plains,
including 104 degrees at Lincoln, Neb., breaking a record of 103
for the date set in 1974; 95 degrees in Alpena, Mich., topping the
92-degree mark of 1964; and 103 in Sioux City, Iowa, beating the
99-degree record set in 1933 and 1953.
   A tornado touched down briefly Sunday at McCook, Neb., but no
damage or injuries were reported.
   Skies were clear over Minnesota, much of Wisconsin and the
central Plains early today; a few showers and thunderstorms
persisted over northeastern Colorado and northwest Kansas. Isolated
showers and thunderstorms lingered in the Southeast.
   Today's forecast called for thunderstorms scattered from Maine
across Vermont to New York; and showers and thunderstorms from
Florida and Alabama into southeastern Texas, as well as from
southern Idaho to northern Arizona and Southern California.
   High temperatures were forecast for the upper 60s and the 70s
along the California coast; in the 70s and 80s in northern Oregon
and Washington; in the 80s over the Great Lakes and northern Maine;
near 90 from the Carolinas across Georgia and Alabama, as well as
in the Rockies; in the upper 90s to 100 and hotter in the central
Plains and the Missouri Valley, and from the valleys of central
California through the desert Southwest; and in the 90s in the rest
of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 51
degrees at North Bend, Ore., to 94 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 fair; Boston 68 fair; Buffalo 71 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 71 fair; Cincinnati 67 fair; Cleveland 70
fair; Detroit 68 fair; Miami 76 cloudy; New York 64 fair;
Philadelphia 68 foggy; Pittsburgh 63 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine
62 foggy; Washington 72 hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 61 fair; Chicago 77 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 75 fair; Denver 71 fair; Des Moines 76 fair;
Indianapolis 72 fair; Kansas City 83 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 72
fair; Nashville 75 fair; New Orleans 70 fair; St. Louis 82 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 79 fair; Anchorage 51 rain; Las Vegas 85
fair; Los Angeles 62 cloudy; Phoenix 94 fair; Salt Lake City 79
partly cloudy; San Diego 63 cloudy; San Francisco 58 partly cloudy;
Seattle 57 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 77 partly cloudy; Toronto 73 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
