<HEAD>Dollar Stable as Market Waits for Summit News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar turned in mixed results today in calm
early European trading as the market waited for news from an
economic summit meeting in Toronto. Gold prices were higher also in
slack trading.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar rose in East Asia as
dealers anticipated positive comments on the currency by leaders of
the seven major industrialized nations attending the summit, which
began on Sunday.
   ``They will probably make some remarks on the foreign exchange
market, and everything that has been said in recent weeks has been
positive,'' a senior dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt said.
   But dealers said many market participants were waiting for an
official statement, leaving the dollar little changed in a narrow
trading range.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar rose 0.36 yen to a closing 126.09 yen. Later, in London, it
was quoted fractionally higher at 126.15 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday's
rates:
   _1.7537 West German marks, up from 1.7530
   _1.4565 Swiss francs, down from 1.4575
   _5.9135 French francs, up from 5.9120
   _1.9706 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9695
   _1,301.10 Italian lire, down from 1,301.35
   _1.2103 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2130
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7870 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7827 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $454.20 a troy ounce and
at mid-morning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $453.90. Both were up from late Friday's bid
of $450.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $454.00, up from $450.40 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.15 to close at a bid $455.30.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $7.24 a troy
ounce, up from late Friday's $7.08.
