<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Yellowtail     06-20 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Yellowtail,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patriarch Of Crow Indians Dies At 98</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LODGE GRASS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A patriarch of the Crow Indian Tribe
who once turned down the post of commissioner of the Bureau of
Indian Affairs has died at age 98.
   Robert Summers Yellowtail Sr. died Saturday in his sleep at his
cattle ranch near this southeastern Montana reservation town.
   For 75 years, Yellowtail was known as a modern-day warrior who
fought the tribe's battles with words.
   His rejection of the BIA post came in the 1950s during the
Eisenhower administration.
   ``I never did get along with the Indian bureau, even when I
worked for it,'' he said in explaining his decision to turn down
the federal position.
   Born near Lodge Grass, Yellowtail graduated from Riverside High
School in California, studied law and planned to become a lawyer,
but instead became involved in tribal affairs and politics.
   The University of Montana School of Law eventually awarded him
an honorary degree.
   He served several times as tribal chairman, and the BIA
appointed him superintendent of his reservation _ the first Indian
to hold the post. He held the job 11 years.
   Yellowtail said his most memorable experience was a war of words
in the U.S. Capitol on April 6, 1917.
   All the great chiefs of the Crow Tribe had gathered in
Washington to fight homesteading on their reservation, site of
Custer's Last Stand on the Little Bighorn. Montana Sen. Thomas J.
Walsh, one of the most powerful men in Congress, wanted to open
their reservation to white settlement.
   The old chiefs did not speak English, and the task of arguing
their case before the Senate Indian Affairs Committee fell to
Yellowtail, a 28-year-old law student.
   ``The gallery was jammed full of spectators,'' Yellowtail
recalled years later. ``They said I would have 18 minutes to answer
Senator Walsh, but I took 4{ hours.''
   World War I interrupted his off-the-cuff speech: A bell summoned
the committee to join a special assembly in which President Woodrow
Wilson asked Congress to declare war on Germany.
   But the committee reconvened to hear Yellowtail's remarks, and
when he finished, Walsh eyed the comittee members and withdrew his
proposal.
   Funeral services were tentatively scheduled for Wednesday in
Lodge Grass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
