<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0508 06-20 0874</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0508,0898</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Rebels Seize Western Border Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede MEHRAN</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to update with rebels reporting more
fighting. Picks up 7th graf pvs ``Mehran, largely...''. Changes
byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian rebels today reported fierce
fighting with Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's forces around the
captured western border town of Mehran.
   Hassan Abdin, a senior official of the Iraqi-based National
Liberation Army, said in a communique telexed to Nicosia that the
rebels plan to withdraw ``to new defensive positions.''
   He did not elaborate. However, the National Liberation Army
force that stormed Mehran on Sunday was expected to follow the
rebels' usual pattern of withdrawing from Iranian territory after
inflicting as much damage as possible on Khomeini's troops.
   In previous operations, the rebel force has rarely stayed inside
Iran for more than 48 hours before pulling back to bases inside
Iraq.
   The National Liberation Army claimed a force of 22 brigades
seized Mehran and high ground to the north and south in an
offensive launched Saturday night along a 30-mile front.
   However, Iran denied Mehran was seized and said the offensive
was mounted by Iraqi soldiers backed by chemical weapons. Iraq said
none of its soldiers were involved in fighting at Mehran.
   The rebels said they had no exact figures on enemy casualties
but estimated that hundreds were killed or wounded at least 1,400
were taken prisoner. The rebels reported at least 48 dead among
their own troops.
   Earlier today, the National Liberation Army said it planned
bigger offensives aimed at toppling the Tehran regime.
   Mahmoud Attai, the rebel force's chief of staff, said in a
communique: ``We are contemplating much larger offensives for which
the capture of the city of Mehran is considered only a prelude.''
   The communique was telexed to The Associated Press bureau in
Nicosia from the Baghdad headquarters of the Mujahedeen Khalq, or
People's Holy Warriors, the main component in the National
Liberation Army.
   Rebel officials refused to say how many of National Liberation
Army troops were involved in the offensive, but claimed it was
their largest operation since the group's founding a year ago.
   The rebels said their 30-mile-wide offensive had punched as many
as 12 miles into Iran and engaged about 14,000 government soldiers.
   In a communique telexed today to Nicosia from Baghdad, the
rebels said they had blown up hundreds of bunkers and captured
large amounts of heavy weapons and armored vehicles worth $1
billion.
   Mehran, largely destroyed in earlier battles between Iranian and
Iraqi armies, was filled Sunday with cheering, smiling, flag-waving
rebel troops, including many women. It has changed hands four times
since the outbreak of the Iran-Iraq war in September 1980.
   An Associated Press reporter found no evidence in the town
itself of a major battle: no bodies, no wounded, no destroyed
vehicles, no fires. The rebels said most of the fighting occurred
in the foothills of mountains to the north and south, where
artillery had controlled the town. The guerrillas said they
captured this high ground too.
   The rebels exulted over the victory, calling the battle a major
political and psychological blow to Khomeini's fundamentalist
regime.
   The rebel group is built around activists who helped Khomeini
overthrow Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlevi. It later was outlawed by
Khomeini's Islamic fundamentalists and created a base in Baghdad.
The group describes itself as Islamic socialists seeking a secular
regime in Iran.
   Supported by Iraq, the National Liberation Army has been playing
a small but growing role in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war. Western
diplomats in Baghdad put the number of the group's fighters at
about 15,000.
   A report Sunday by Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency,
monitored in Nicosia, said ``a large number of Iranian Moslem
combatants were martyred and injured when Iraqi warplanes
chemically bombed the Changuleh region east of Mehran.''
   Earlier Sunday, IRNA said Iraqi warplanes bombed Mehran with
chemicals.
   The agency said Iranian units were dispatched to ``neutralize
the chemical weapons'' and that hundreds of Iraqis were killed in
fighting near the town. It also reported Iranian warplanes bombed
Iraqi positions in the Mehran area.
   IRNA also said an attack on Mehran was repulsed and Iranian
troops were mopping up enemy positions.
   Iraq denied its forces were involved in the attack on Mehran or
that chemical weapons were used. The rebels said no Iraqi troops or
artillery support was involved.
   It was not known how many Iranian government troops had held
Mehran, but it was clear the number was small.
   ``There was very little fighting,'' said Horie Aboi, 25, one of
dozens of women combatants in the town. Like most of the occupiers,
she looked fresh and her uniform was unsoiled Sunday. ``Because the
town was surrounded, they quickly gave up,''
   Fatima Tahouri, deputy commander of the forces occupying Mehran,
said there was stiff resistance when Iranian opposition forces
crossed the border and moved the few miles to the town.
   Asked why there was no evidence of fighting from a battle that
ended six hours earlier, she said: ``We've picked up a few things
since the morning.''
   With no civilian population and useful buildings, Mehran was
mainly a symbolic victory. Crumbled, blown-away mud structures are
nestled in a grove of battered palms.
</TEXT>
