<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PriceyParking     06-20 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pricey Parking,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>6-Year Court Battle Waged Over Parking Place</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten lawyers have run up $35,000 in bills
to settle Natalie Maciborka's claim to a parking place at her
condominium, but she still can't park where she wants.
   The six-year tiff has alienated residents of the 10-story pink
stucco Ashleigh House.
   ``They've ganged up on me,'' said Mrs. Maciborka, 55, who drives
a 1982 white Pontiac Phoenix. ``They deprived me of my rights. They
scratched my car. They ostracized me.''
   Other residents see it differently.
   ``The whole thing is ridiculous,'' said resident Sam Miller, 75.
   ``We're just sick of it,'' said Virginia Tuck, 55. As president
of the condominium association, she has posted flyers in the
building elevators to keep residents up to date.
   The problem began in 1981 when Mrs. Maciborka sold her covered
parking space, No. 8, to residents Clarence A. Snyder and Robert J.
Zuttermeister. Mrs. Maciborka got their old space, uncovered and 70
yards away.
   A new condo board discovered a few years later that state law
and the building's bylaws prohibited the sale of parking places.
   Mrs. Maciborka tried to give Snyder back his $4,000, but he
refused it.
   Snyder then sued Mrs. Maciborka for $100,000, citing emotional
distress. She countersued Snyder and the homeowners association for
$200,000 and her old parking place.
   Broward Circuit Judge Daniel M. Futch ruled in March 1987 that
Snyder could keep No. 8. No damages were granted.
   Mrs. Maciborka wanted a clarification, and Circuit Judge Richard
D. Eade last week confirmed the final judgment and assigned space
No. 92 to Mrs. Maciborka.
   ``A guest space,'' she fumed. ``They've segregated me. There are
90 spaces for 90 residents, and they've punished me by putting me
in space No. 92 _ a guest space.''
   But other residents are unhappy about the condo association's
$11,000 legal bill.
   ``Why does the rest of the building have to pay for something
that was between her and someone else?'' Miller asked.
   Mrs. Maciborka has paid her $53.10 share of the condo's latest
legal bill.
</TEXT>
