<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Amerasians     06-20 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Amerasians,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Parents Search for Children in Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Americans returned to Vietnam
today to try to bring out children they left behind during the war
years.
   The group flew from Bangkok to Ho Chi Minh City, formerly
Saigon. They hoped to return in a week with their children and then
fly together to the United States.
   The four Americans have written their children letters and
telegrams telling them of their arrival in Ho Chi Minh City,
according to Bruce Burns, director of the California-based
Amerasian Registry. His group helps reunite Americans with
half-Vietnamese children they left behind.
   Burns said Sunday the Vietnamese government has cooperated with
the four cases.
   Vietnam has said that all of the country's Amerasians should
resettle in the United States and allowed an organized departure
program for regular resettlement. Vietnam also has cooperated with
resettling smaller groups on a more informal basis.
   The Americans were Joseph Crotty of Redding, Calif.; West
Anderson of Poulsbo, Wash.; and Verdun Andrus from San Diego,
Calif. The fourth is Mrs. Nam Small, the Vietnamese-American wife
of John Small of Westbrook, Maine.
   Crotty, 62, who was a Navy officer in Vietnam, left behind a
pregnant girlfriend, Pham Thi Tam, in August 1969, Burns said.
Their son, Khuc Thua Si, 18, was granted U.S. citizenship a few
years ago. Crotty retired from the Navy and the California Highway
Patrol.
   Anderson, 38, spent two years in the Army in Vietnam. He brought
his wife to the United States but left behind their daughter Nguyen
Thi Lang, now 16. Anderson works in a munitions factory, Burns said.
   Andrus, 59, a retired accountant, spent eight years in Vietnam
with an architectural and engineering firm. He has not seen his
wife, Hoang Son Andrus, since the communist victory in April 1975.
She lives with their 14-year-old son, Vo Thi Tham.
   Mrs. Small has not seen her son, Nguyen Ngoc Linh, 16, since
1974. At that time, she left to join her husband, but their son had
to stay for medical examinations. John Small, 45, a postmaster,
spent two years in the Army in Vietnam.
</TEXT>
