<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JailbreakKilling     06-20 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jailbreak Killing,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search Continues for Gunman, Two Escapees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK GROVE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman who freed two prisoners after
killing a sheriff's deputy apparently plotted the breakout with his
fellow inmates before his release from the jail five days earlier,
authorities said.
   Authorities believe the man who killed Deputy Jeff Gathings was
19-year-old Frank Bancroft, who had been released from the jail
Tuesday after a sentence for theft, said West Carroll Parish
Sheriff Gary Bennett.
   Brothers Sonny and Frank Caston were set free by the gunman
early Sunday, Bennett said. Both men had criminal records and were
in the parish jail awaiting trial on burglary and arson charges.
   A deputy in the West Carroll Parish Sheriff's office said Sunday
night that the search for the men had been expanded from northeast
Louisiana into Mississippi and Arkansas.
   Road blocks were erected at Oak Grove, about 10 miles south of
the Arkansas state line, after the escape. Authorities found a
black pickup truck that may have been used by the men Sunday
afternoon near the Castons' hometown of Lake Providence, on the
Mississippi River about 10 miles east of Oak Grove.
   Bennett said Gathings was alone in the radio room, next to the
jail, when the gunman entered 2:30 a.m. Sunday.
   Inmates heard the blast of the 12-gauge shotgun and saw Bancroft
let the Castons out of jail, Bennett said. ``All of them (the
inmates) know him.''
</TEXT>
