<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1008EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Britain     06-20 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Britain,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Parliamentarians Arrive On Mission to Improve Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four British lawmakers arrived in Tehran
today on a private mission to improve Britain's relations with
Iran, the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
   The Iranian agency, monitored in Nicosia, said officials of
Iran's Foreign Ministry and parliament met the British
parliamentarians at Tehran's airport.
   ``Relations between Tehran and London and issues of mutual
interest'' will be among topics discussed, IRNA said. It said the
British government ``has expressed interest in solving financial
disputes between the two countries and later ... improving
Tehran-London ties.''
   IRNA said the Britons were scheduled to hold talks with senior
Iranian officials during their three-day visit. It gave no details.
   The British legislators said before leaving London that they
hoped to meet with Iran's parliament speaker, Hashemi Rafsanjani.
He is the most powerful figure in the country after Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini.
   IRNA indicated that Britain's release last month of Abdullah
Nouripour, an Iranian who had been held on charges of trying to
cause an explosion, had spurred efforts to improve relations. It
said Nouripour returned to Tehran on May 19.
   The British lawmakers are Cyril Townsend and Robert Hicks of
Britain's governing Conservative Party; Thomas Clarke of the
opposition Labor Party; and Lord Tordoff of the liberal Social
Democrats. Their trip was arranged by Archbishop of Canterbury
Robert Runcie.
   Townsend said before leaving London, ``We think the climate has
been improving in recent weeks and we like to think that four
members of Parliament going to Tehran ... can nudge that progress
along.''
   The lawmakers cautioned against raising hopes that their visit
could lead to the release of British hostages held in Lebanon by
pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems.
   Clarke said the group was not taking any messages from the
hostages' families. ``We are fully aware of how strongly they feel
and that's one of the reasons it would be quite improper for us to
build up people's hopes.''
   Three Britons are among the 18 foreigners, including nine
Americans, missing after being kidnapped in Lebanon. The hostage
held longest is American Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Britain's relations with Tehran have been strained since
Khomeini's 1979 Islamic revolution toppled Shah Mohammad Reza
Pahlavi. The Iranians have long considered Britain the second-most
hostile Western nation next to the United States.
   Relations deteriorated last year when a British diplomat was
kidnapped in Tehran and an Iranian diplomat was arrested in England
for shoplifting. Both countries later expelled diplomats.
   Hopes that relations could improve increased June 10 when
Britain and Iran agreed to compensate each other for damage
inflicted on their embassies in violence several years ago in
Tehran and London.
   The Iranians, alarmed at their growing isolation during their
nearly 8-year-old war with Iraq, have been making clear efforts to
patch up ties with Western European nations, apparently hoping to
draw them away from alignment with the United States.
   France restored relations with Iran last week after an 11-month
break, and West Germany has been discussing bolstering its
relations with Tehran.
   The French move came after French hostages held in Lebanon were
freed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
