<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Promotions     06-20 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Promotions,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Study Dispute Over Birmingham Plan for Promoting Black
Firefighters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in an important new test of
affirmative action, today agreed to study a dispute over a
Birmingham, Ala., plan for promoting more black firefighters.
   The justices said they will study efforts by city officials and
others to kill a challenge by white firefighters who say the plan
makes them victims of reverse discrimination.
   The case is likely to provide one of the first indications of
how the court's newest member, Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, will
vote on affirmative action disputes. He succeeded retired Justice
Lewis F. Powell, for years a pivotal figure in the court's
consideration of programs giving preferential treatment to
minorities and women.
   A decision in the Birmingham case is expected sometime in 1989.
   At issue is whether, and under what conditions, a court-approved
agreement between public officials and minority groups may be
challenged by employees who say the plan victimizes them.
   The case began in 1974 when Birmingham officials and the
Jefferson County Personnel Board were sued by the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People and individuals
who charged them with discriminating against blacks in hiring and
promotion.
   Eventually, both sides reached agreement on an extensive plan
that includes long-term and interim annual goals for hiring blacks
as firefighters and promoting blacks to higher ranks.
   The Birmingham Firefighters Association, representing most of
the city's firefighters, objected that the agreement would hurt its
members. But the association's opposition to the plan was rejected
by a federal judge who in 1981 issued consent drecrees approving
the plan.
   There were 453 city firefighters at the time, including 42
blacks. None of the city fire department's 140 lieutenants,
captains or battalion chiefs were black. But nearly half the
workers in Birmingham's civilian labor force were black.
   After the firefighters association challenge was rejected, seven
white male firefighters sued the city and the county personnel
board, charging reverse discrimination. They said less qualified
blacks would be given promotions over them.
   A federal judge ruled that the white firefighters were bound by
the court consent decrees authorizing the affirmative action plan.
The judge dismissed the white firefighters' suit.
   But the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last December
reinstated it. ``The policy of encouraging voluntary affirmative
action plans must yield to the policy against requiring third
parties to submit to bargains in which their interests were either
ignored or sacrificed,'' the appeals court said.
   It noted that the plan did not place a great burden on the city,
since it was called upon only to reallocate promotions and not
create new jobs.
   ``In real terms, the relief contemplated by the decrees was to
come not from the hands of the city, but from the hands of the
employees who would have otherwise received the promotions,'' the
appeals court said.
   It ordered a trial judge to decide whether the white
firefighters were discriminated against unlawfully, saying that the
earlier consent decrees authorizing the affirmative action plan do
not insulate it from their lawsuit.
   The consent decrees give the plan no more legitimacy than any
other voluntary program of racial preferences would have , the
appeals court said.
   It added that the affirmative action plan must be analyzed with
``heightened scrutiny'' _ meaning city officials must have a
``compelling reason'' to impose a policy that disadvantages whites.
   The appeals court said such analysis is required by a recent
Supreme Court ruling that upheld the promotion of a woman over a
marginally more qualified man. Generally, the high court has
required ``heightened scrutiny'' only when courts study government
programs that allegedly disadvantage minorities.
   The Supreme Court last January split, 4-4, in upholding a New
York City affirmative action plan for promoting more blacks and
Hispanics in the city police department. That plan was challenged
unsuccessfully by white officers.
   Because of the tie vote, the justices were unable to decide
issues similar to those raised in the Birmingham case.
   The Reagan administration supports the 11th Circuit court ruling
that permits the white firefighters to challenge the Birmingham
plan. Nonetheless, administration lawyers urged the Supreme Court
to study the case to settle the issue of whether whites should be
allowed to sue in such instances.
   Birmingham city officials led by Mayor Richard Arrington, who is
black, were joined by the Jefferson County Personnel Board and
black firefighters in urging the high court to overturn the 11th
Circuit court ruling.
   City officials said the appeals court ruling threatens to reopen
old wounds.
   ``The reverse discrimination litigation has cost the city
substantial time and expense and has re-awakened racial division
and animosity that the city has worked to put behind it,'' the
officials said.
   The cases are Martin vs. Wilks, 87-1614; Personnel Board of
Jefferson County vs. Wilks, 87-1639; and Arrington vs. Wilks,
87-1668.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
