<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1058EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-NashvilleDeseg     06-20 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Nashville Deseg,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justices Say State Need Not Pay School Desegregation Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to order
Tennessee to help pay for continuing efforts to racially
desegregate Nashville area public schools.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that sheilded the
state from making such expenditures.
   The controversy has its roots in a 1955 lawsuit over racial
segregation in Nashville schools.
   Until the Supreme Court's landmark 1954 decision outlawing
racial segregation in public schools, Tennessee law barred black
and white children from attending the same schools.
   In 1960, the Metropolitan County Board of Education of Nashville
and Davidson County was substituted as a defendant in the case.
   In 1981, the local school board asked a federal judge to require
Tennessee to pay the full cost of implementing court-ordered
desegregation remedies, which include extensive busing.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas A. Wiseman Jr. ruled in 1985 that
forcing Tennessee to pay for ``costs already sustained'' before the
school board filed its complaint in 1981 would violate the
Constitution's 11th Amendment giving states broad protections
against being sued.
   But Wiseman ruled that the 11th Amendment does not shield the
state from helping pay for continuing desegregation efforts.
   He ordered Tennessee officials ``to assume 60 percent of the
costs directly attributable to Metro's desegregation program from
and after ... March 16, 1981.''
   Tennessee appealed, arguing that it should not have to pay
anything. The local school district also appealed, contending that
the state should have to pay all desegregation costs.
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled for the state last
Dec. 30.
   ``The federal courts would not be justified in shifting any of
the costs in question from Metro (the local school district) to the
state of Tennessee,'' the appeals court said.
   The Supreme Court in 1977 ruled that Michigan could be forced to
help pay the costs of desegregating Detroit's public schools.
   But the 6th Circuit court said there is a difference between the
Detroit case and the Nashville case.
   ``The monetary relief granted in (the Detroit case) was merely
ancilliary to other affirmative relief,'' the appeals court said,
``and the monetary relief granted here is not.''
   It noted that Michigan officials had been ordered to help put
some desegregation programs into effect, not merely pay for
programs undertaken by the Detroit school authorities.
   The appeals court said Tennessee's duty to eliminate the
vestiges of past segregation in education ``was discharged long
before Metro filed its ... complaint against the state.''
   The case is Metropolitan County Board vs. Tennessee, 87-1774.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
