<DOCNO> AP880620-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1101EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Indians     06-20 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Indians,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court To Decide Whether Indian Tribes May Control Some Non-Indians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether Indian tribes may control, through tribal zoning laws, the
use of land owned by non-Indians within a reservation's boundaries.
   The justices, in a case of significance to any state in which a
reservation is located, said they will resolve a dispute involving
the Yakima Indian Reservation in Washington state.
   A federal appeals court ruled last Sept. 21 that the
Confederated Tribes and Bands of the Yakima Indian Nation has a
legitimate interest in regulating _ and may zone _ so-called ``fee
land'' located on its reservation but owned by individuals, most of
them not tribal members.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said the tribe's interest
in regulating that land must be balanced against the interests of
Yakima County and the federal government.
   The Yakima reservation encompasses 1.3 million acres of land,
most of it within Yakima County. About 5,000 tribal members and
about 20,000 non-members live within the reservation's boundaries.
   About 800,000 acres, including some 740,000 in Yakima County,
fall within the reservation's ``closed area'' in which the tribe's
zoning ordinance allows no permanent structures.
   Philip Brendale, who owns 160 acres of land within the
reservation's closed area, was barred by the ordinance from selling
his land for residential development.
   And Stanley Wilkinson, who owns about 100 acres just within the
reservation's northern boundary, was barred by the ordinance from
subdividing a portion of his land.
   Neither man is a member of the Yakima tribe. They, along with
Yakima County officials, contend that the tribe lacks the legal
authority to control the use of their land.
   Brendale, Wilkinson and Yakima County filed separate appeals
from the 9th Circuit court's ruling.
   The county's lawyers argued that the appeals court ruling, at
least in its effect on the reservation's ``open area,'' conflicts
with past Supreme Court rulings limiting tribal authority over
non-Indians.
   The county's appeal cited a 1978 decision in which the justices
ruled that Indian tribes do not have the authority to prosecute
non-Indians for crimes committed on reservations.
   The appeal also relied on a 1981 decision in which the high
court ruled that Montana, and not an Indian tribe, had the
authority to regulate the fishing and hunting of non-Indians on the
tribe's reservation.
   The appeals acted on today, seeking to limit tribal control of
land use, were supported in ``friend-of-the-court'' briefs
submitted by the National Association of Counties and seven states.
   The states are Washington Arizona, Nevada, New Mexico, South
Dakota, Utah and Wyoming.
   The case cases are Brendale vs. Confederated Tribes, 87-1622;
Wilkinson vs. Confederated Tribes, 87-1697; and Yakima County vs.
Confederated Tribes, 87-1711.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880620-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1102EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-IRA     06-20 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-IRA,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Given Long Sentences For Plotting IRA Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Northern Ireland men were sentenced today to
17 and 20 years in prison for plotting an Irish Republican Army
terror campaign in Britain. The prisoners raised their fists to
supporters as they were led away.
   Patrick McLaughlin, 40, received a 20-year sentence for
conspiring to cause explosions in England. Liam McCotter, 25, was
sentenced to 17 years on the same charge. Both are from Belfast.
   ``You contemplated explosions which were likely to endanger
human life,'' High Court Justice John Owen. ``I bear in mind there
was sufficient explosive material to cause 25 such explosions.''
   He gave the longer sentence to McLaughlin because of
McLaughlin's two previous convictions, for riotous behavior in 1971
and for possession of a gun and ammunition in 1974.
   After the sentences were read, a man in the public gallery
shouted in Gaelic, ``Our day will come!''
   McLaughlin and McCotter raised their fists, and McCotter chanted
IRA slogans as the men were taken away. They were driven from the
courthouse in an armed convoy with a helicopter hovering above.
   Scotland Yard's anti-terrorist squad arrested the pair Feb. 19,
1987 after following them to two weapons caches containing almost
200 pounds of high explosives, detonators, timing devices, three
automatic rifles, two handguns, and ammunition.
   The weapons were hidden in plastic garbage cans buried in
Macclesfield and Delamere forests south of Manchester, in northern
England.
   Court testimony did not reveal what the targets may have been,
but anti-terrorist sources mentioned as a possibility last June's
general election campaign. Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher won a
third term in the election.
   Police said the weapons were smuggled into England through
northern Wales.
   McLaughlin and McCotter were kept under surveillance for four
days as they brought the materials into the forests and hid them.
They made cuts in tree bark to mark the hiding places.
   Police also followed the pair to a nighttime rendezvous with a
trawler at Camaes Bay in north Wales, where arms reportedly changed
hands. Police feared exposing their operation and allowed the
vessel to leave.
   Scotland Yard's anti-terrorist squad is still searching for two
people in the case. One is a man known only as Alan Robinson, who
rented the apartment used by McLaughlin and McCotter. Maps of
London and Manchester were found in the apartment. The other
suspect has not been identified.
   The IRA is outlawed in Britain. It is fighting to drive the
British from Northern Ireland and unite the province with the Irish
Republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
