<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Expulsions     06-20 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia-Expulsions,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Daily Blasts Deported Western Activists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party daily today
charged that 32 Western activists expelled from Czechoslovakia
abused their rights as tourists by pursuing political goals.
   The foreign activists arrived in Czechoslovakia on tourist
visas, but ``the aim of their trip was not the beauties of
Prague,'' Rude Pravo said. They were from 16 countries and were
attending an unofficial East-West seminar on human rights and peace.
   Seminar participants said the expulsions came after police
disrupted meetings Friday and Saturday, detained Czechoslovak
participants, confiscated materials prepared for the seminar and
warned Westerners not to continue the seminar.
   The seminar had been organized by the Czechoslovak human rights
group Charter 77 and the newly established Czechoslovak Independent
Peace Association.
   ``We gladly open our home to all honest tourists coming to us
with sincere tourist interests, but we can show the door to
provocateurs abusing international tourism for political aims,''
Rude Pravo said.
   ``As facts told by the uninvited `tourists' show, both emigre
centers in Western Europe and other international reactionary
circles which ... aim mainly at slanders ... were interested in
holding the gathering,'' the article said. It appeared under the
headline, ``Visitors with Codes.''
   A protest statement drafted by Western participants and signed
also by Czechoslovak activists said the activities of the
Czechoslovak government ``fly in the face of recent East bloc
promises for democratic reform.''
   At a news conference in Vienna on Sunday, four Americans who
attended the seminar said police arrested 20 Eastern European
conference participants.
   ``We are dismayed and deeply concerned at the arrest of 19
Czechoslovakians and one Hungarian, and the police state tactics of
the Czechoslovakian government,'' the protest statement said.
   Judith Hempfling from Amherst, Mass., told reporters in Vienna
after returning from Prague that the statement was read to about 30
people who had gathered at the Czech dissident Saturday morning.
   She said the petition was circulated for signatures as police
came upstairs.
   Rob Leavitt of the Massachusetts-based Institute for Defense and
Disarmament Studies said police put the foreigners in police vans
and drove them to Prague's central police station.
   He said the foreigners were kept for about five hours in a
waiting room and were then told they had five hours to leave the
country.
   The other Americans at the news conference were Joanne Landy, of
the New York-based Campaign for Peace and Democracy _ East-West,
and Brad Knott, a peace activist from Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
