<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-AlabamaDeseg     06-20 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Alabama Deseg,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justices Affirm Ruling That Judge Shoult Not Have Presided</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling
that unraveled years of litigation in a still-pending lawsuit to
racially desegregate Alabama's colleges and universities.
   The court, without comment, refused to disturb a ruling that the
federal judge who found ``vestiges of segregation'' in the state's
schools of higher education should not have presided over the case.
   U.S. District Judge U.W. Clemon, the first black federal trial
judge in Alabama, ruled in 1985 that authorities would have to take
steps to racially integrate such state-run schools as Auburn
University, the University of Alabama and Troy State.
   The Reagan administration had sued the state's higher education
system for racial discrimination in 1983, the first such claim by
the administration against a state college system.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last Oct. 6 that
Clemon should have disqualified himself from the case. The appeals
court said that Clemon, as a former state legislator, ``actively
participated in the very events and shaped the very facts that are
at issue in this suit.''
   Clemon once served as chairman of the state Senate Rules
Committee. In that role, the appeals court said, he ``played a
critical role in the confirmation of those individuals nominated
for positions on the board of trustees of the defendant
institutions.''
   The appeals court, however, rejected arguments that Clemon
should have disqualified himself because of his past civil rights
activity and because his children may some day attend some of the
schools involved.
   ``To disqualify minority judges from major civil rights
lititgation solely because of their minority status is
intolerable,'' the 11th Circuit court said.
   Clemon's 1985 ruling against the state school officials followed
15 months of pretrial proceedings and a 22-day trial over which he
presided.
   The 11th Circuit's ruling in October sent the case back for a
new trial before another federal judge.
   The appeal acted on today was filed by Alabama State University
and Alabama A&M University, two predominantly black schools whose
officials say have had their integration attempts thwarted by
official state policies, and individuals.
   Justice Department lawyers, although contending that Clemon's
disqualification by the 11th Circuit court was wrong, urged the
high court to reject the appeal.
   ``The question is inherently fact-bound and non-recurring,''
they said, adding that the government ``will continue adequately to
represent the students and faculty of the Alabama schools _ the
persons who would truly benefit from the desegregation of the
Alabama system of higher education.''
   The case is Board of Trustees vs. Auburn University, 87-1200.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
