<2ND_LINE>PM-Skinhead Abduction,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl Now Says `Skinheads' Abducted Her In Seattle, Not Portland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old girl says five young women with
shaved heads tied her up, cut off her hair, kicked her, burned her
with cigarette lighters and dumped her by a highway, then fled with
her car and pet snake.
   The abductors were described as ``Skinheads,'' members of a
white supremacist youth gang.
   Three teen-age girls were in a British Columbia jail for
investigation of possessing stolen property, abduction and assault
in the incident, said Constable David Wilks of the Royal Canadian
Mounted Police. They were arrested for speeding in the stolen car
Saturday in Golden, British Columbia, about 250 miles east of
Vancouver, police said.
   Police were searching for two other suspects.
   The victim, from Portland, Ore., suffered scratches and burns.
She also said her abductors cut her long hair to within a half-inch
of her scalp.
   ``She had a distinct lack of hair,'' said Snohomish County
sheriff's Sgt. Sam Goss.
   Her pet boa constrictor was recovered in its cage in the car.
   The abducted girl told The Oregonian on Sunday that she was
kidnapped early Saturday in Seattle by five Skinhead girls, then
dumped about 20 miles north of Everett, which is north of Seattle.
   ``They were drunk, and trying to prove that they were tough,''
she said.
   She initially had told police she was abducted in Portland, but
said Sunday that she had been trying to keep her father from
finding out she had been in Seattle, about 170 miles from Portland,
with his car.
   The teen-ager told The Oregonian that her abductors forced a rag
into her mouth, tied her hands with a rope and bound her feet and
hands with a chain.
   ``They threw me into the back of my car and covered me with
jackets,'' she said.
   ``They started kicking me and I thought I was going to die,''
she said. ``They used cigarette lighters to burn me on my legs and
arms, to see if I was dead. I played dead.''
   Police said the five eventually dumped her along Interstate 5.
She said she freed herself from the ropes and crawled to the
freeway, where a motorist stopped and took her to a hospital.
   Authorities in Everett were pressing for immediate return of two
of the jailed teen-agers who are U.S. citizens and illegal aliens
in Canada, said Snohomish County sheriff's Deputy Rhonda Pince. The
third, a resident of Calgary, Alberta, would be brought back after
extradition hearings, she said.
