<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Escape, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0585,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search Expands to Tennessee</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd, 4th grafs to CORRECT to Banister, sted Bannister.
Subs 9th graf, `An aerial...' with 1 graf to update with Hicks
saying he believed no inmates in Tenn.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EDDYVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The search for five inmates who escaped a
state prison expanded into Tennessee after authorities discovered
the fingerprints of a convicted murderer in a garage where a car
was stolen, officials said.
   The car was taken Sunday morning in Dover, Tenn., and
fingerprints left behind indicate that Joseph Montgomery had been
there, said Barry Banister, a spokesman for the Kentucky State
Penitentiary.
   Montgomery, 27, of Louisville, was serving 31 years for murder,
burglary, assault and other charges. He was among eight inmates,
including four convicted murderers, who escaped Thursday from the
prison. One inmate was captured Friday and two on Saturday, all
near the prison.
   Within two hours of the escape, a pickup truck was stolen a few
miles from the penitenitary, Banister said. Authorities are
investigating whether Montgomery, and perhaps some of the other
escapees, drove to Dover, about 50 miles south of the penitenitary.
   The truck has not been found, he said.
   Sheriff David Hicks of Stewart County, Tenn., said his
department received a complaint Saturday night about three people
trying to flag down cars on Tennessee 232 in a sparsely populated
area 15 miles from Dover.
   ``The officer confronted them and they ran from him and dropped
a cooler and shirt,'' Hicks said.
   Eddyville officials were go to Tennessee with comparison
fingerprints from the five escapees to see if they matched prints
from the cooler and shirt, Hicks said.
   Hicks said he believed any escapees who were in Tennessee left
after the car theft.
   Among the inmates still at large were two convicted murderers.
The others were serving terms for various crimes.
   The eight sawed their way to freedom from an upper level of
Cellhouse 3, which is reserved for the penitentiary's worst
disciplinary cases. The breakout was apparently planned well in
advance, with inmates on the cellhouse's lower level setting small
fires to distract guards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
