<2ND_LINE>PM-Woman Abducted, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0580,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged In Death Of Banker's Wife</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `Farmer Richard...' to CORRECT to Greenfield,
sted Greenville.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CORRY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A book store operator was charged today with
kidnapping a bank manager's wife who was found shot to death after
her husband received a vague ransom note, authorities said.
   David C. Copenhefer, 40, of Corry, appeared before Magistrate
Patsy Nichols today on charges of kidnapping, attempted robbery and
attempted extortion in the disappearance of Sally Weiner, 37, of
Corry.
   He was not charged in Mrs. Weiner's death. Ms. Nichols, who set
bond at $100,000, said the investigation is continuing.
   Copenhefer was arrested at his home today after police seized
weapons, including high-powered automatic rifles, from his home and
took other evidence from Corry Books & Cards, which Copenhefer
operated. The book store is within sight of a Pennbank branch,
where Mrs. Weiner's husband, Harry, is manager.
   Farmer Richard Stutzman was checking cattle fence on his farm
Sunday morning when he found Mrs. Weiner's body in a clearing five
miles northwest of here, said state police Capt. Douglas Greenfield.
   Dozens of police officers and FBI agents had been combing Erie
County in northwestern Pennsylvania for Mrs. Weiner since Friday
afternoon, when she told her husband in a phone call she would be
killed if he didn't meet a ransom demand, said Pennbank President
Thomas Doolin.
   Mrs. Weiner died of a single gunshot wound to the head, said
Erie County Coroner Merle Wood. ``I would say she died instantly,''
Wood said.
   He said it wasn't known when Mrs. Weiner died or what type of
gun killed her.
   When Mrs. Weiner talked to her husband, she seemed to be reading
from a statement, Doolin said.
   ``She said they were holding a gun to her and that there was a
death threat,'' Doolin said Saturday. ``She said ... he would find
instructions on what to do in a paper bag in the parking lot
outside the bank.''
   Weiner was told to buy a walkie-talkie, set it at a certain
frequency, and go to an isolated, wooded area outside Corry Friday
night, Doolin said.
   Weiner followed the instructions but left after two hours when
no one contacted him, Doolin said. No further contact was made.
   The note, which directed Weiner alone to bring money from the
bank, did not specify an amount, ``which is kind of unusual,''
Doolin said.
   Weiner's mother, Susan Weiner of Erie, said her daughter-in-law
was lured to a restaurant near the Corry Plaza Shopping Center by a
caller who said he wanted her to help plan a surprise civic honor
for her husband.
   She said her son and daughter-in-law had been married 13 years
and were the parents of a boy and girl. A former music teacher,
Mrs. Weiner played piano at several churches and was active in
church groups, Susan Weiner said.
   ``She was a beautiful musician,'' Susan Weiner said. ``She was
hoping to begin teaching again in the fall because she loved her
work and she loved music.''
</TEXT>
