<2ND_LINE>PM-Sharpton-Taxes,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sharpton Reportedly Has Not Filed Tax Returns For Several Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black activist who is at the center of the
Tawana Brawley dispute has not filed income tax returns for several
years and is under investigation for possible tax evasion, New York
Newsday reported today.
   The newspaper said that four sources familiar with the
investigation said the Rev. Al Sharpton has not filed a return for
at least three years. Sharpton acknowledged Sunday that he had not
filed returns in recent years, but said he had not intended to
defraud the government.
   Government investigators believe that though Sharpton has no
visible source of income or regular-paying job, he must be
supported by sources of reportable income, Newsday reported.
   Sharpton said his income comes from speaking engagements,
although he also has a record promotion company. He refused to say
how much he earns.
   Newsday said its sources noted that the tax case is in a
preliminary stage and that no decision has been made to charge
Sharpton. Failure to file an income tax return for a single year is
punishable by up to six years in prison.
   Sharpton said he recently directed his accountant to petition
for a late filing for last year's and previous years' taxes.
   Sharpton is a key adviser to the family of Miss Brawley, a black
Wappingers Falls teen-ager who says she was abducted and sexually
assaulted by at least six white men in November.
   But she and her advisers, who also include two lawyers, have
refused to cooperate with police. Sharpton and others involved in
the case have claimed black people cannot get justice through the
normal channels of investigation.
   Miss Brawley's mother has been in a church since last week,
after an arrest warrant was issued over her refusal to testify
before a grand jury. Officials have so far declined to go into the
church to take her into custody.
</TEXT>
