<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CaptiveWomen     06-20 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Captive Women,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Attorney: Heidnik Case `Not A Whodunit'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Michael Heidnik raped and tortured six
women, killing two of them, but the jury should look beyond those
acts, his attorney said today in opening arguments at Heidnik's
murder trial.
   ``My client is not innocent. We are not relying on that
presumption. He is very, very guilty. This is not a case of
whodunit. This is a case of why it was done,'' A. Charles Peruto
Jr. said. ``He is relying on a defense of mental infirmity. His
criminal acts will show him to be insane.''
   Heidnik, 44, is charged with keeping the women chained in a
basement torture chamber in his Philadelphia home, which officials
say he used as a ``church'' where he installed himself as bishop.
   Assistant District Attorney Charles Gallagher told the jury,
chosen last week in Pittsburgh, that Heidnik ``methodically and
systematically committed repeated sadistic and malicious acts''
against his victims in the basement.
   ``He kept them there chained and repeatedly assaulted them,
repeatedly raped them and eventually killed two of them,''
Gallagher said. ``The evidence will come from the four survivors.
You will see how Heidnik took advantage of underprivileged people.''
   Heidnik is charged with murdering two women _ one by
strangulation while she was hanging chained to a pipe and the other
by electrocution while she was standing in a water-filled pit.
   Peruto has insisted that Heidnik was treated with the chemical
LSD while a hospital patient during Army service in West Germany in
1962, but has been unable to get any records.
   Common Pleas Judge Lynne Abraham warned that without documents,
the alleged evidence on the LSD incident would be excluded from
testimony.
   Peruto said that shortly after the alleged experiments Heidnik
was discharged from the Army and eventually given 100 percent
disability benefits for service-related mental problems.
   Heidnik used some of his disability funds to found a church in
which he proclaimed himself bishop and then allegedly used
contributions to play the stock market, eventually amassing more
than $500,000 before he was arrested in March 1987.
   Jury selection was moved out of Philadelphia because the defense
claimed excessive publicity prevented a fair trial.
</TEXT>
