<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush     06-20 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Honors Drugs Agents Slain in Line of Duty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush honored three slain
drug agents in a memorial ceremony on Monday and said ``it burns me
up'' that federal drug enforcement officers are given so little
credit by politicians of either party.
   Bush was the featured speaker at a Drug Enforcement
Administration service paying tribute to three officers killed in
the line of duty during the past year: Paul S. Seema and George M.
Montoya of Los Angeles and Arthur L. Cash of Tucson, Ariz.
   The vice president presented the families of the three officers
framed certificates signed by President Reagan and told an audience
of about 150 agency employees, ``We remember their unselfish
behavior and mourn them as heroes.''
   ``I hope what I'm about to say isn't accused of being too
political. But in this political season I hear comments from people
of both parties giving no credit at all to the job the men and
women in this room and across the country are doing,'' Bush said.
``It burns me up. It's not fair. It's not accurate.''
   ``By design, you don't get your pictures in the paper or sit at
the head table at testimonial dinners. But everywhere I've gone in
this country, I take time talking about the contribution you
make,'' Bush said.
   At the same time, Bush said, ``As we honor your fallen
colleagues, I want to challenge you to do even better.''
   The vice president has called for the death penalty for major
drug dealers and for those convicted of drug-related murders.
   ``I really do believe the death penalty is the answer,'' Bush
told the audience, which gave him a standing ovation.
   He repeated his call for ``increasing the certainty and the
severity of punishment.''
   The nearly certain Republican nominee shared the stage with
Attorney General Edwin L. Meese III, who told the DEA employees
that ``the quality of the work you do is virtually unmatched.''
   Meese, whose legal difficulties have at times been a political
embarrassment to the vice president, praised Bush as ``the leader
in the administration...in speaking out on behalf of the
(anti-drug) law enforcement effort.''
   During the brief ceremony, the names of 40 drug enforcement
employees killed since the 1920s were read.
   Montoya and Seema were killed last February while conducting an
undercover investigation in Los Angeles. Cash was killed while
transporting prisoners in Arizona in August 1987.
</TEXT>
