<HEAD>Precede TEL AVIV</HEAD>
<HEAD>Explosion In Pizzeria Injures 22</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with 22 injured, quotes and description
from scene. CORRECTS name of town. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HERZLIYA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion in a pizzeria injured 22
Israelis and overturned cars and trucks today in this coastal
resort, hospital officials and witnesses said.
   Police said the blast was caused by a gas leak. They were
investigating whether it was accidental.
   ``Apparently this was not a terrorist act, but one can always
ask why the gas leaked,'' Tel Aviv Police Chief Yigal Marcus said
on Israel army radio. ``Did someone leave the tap open on purpose?
Did someone forget? ... This we can't determine for sure.''
   Police said the gas leaked from 15 canisters stored in the
Rimini Pizzeria, on the ground floor of a three-story building in
Herzliya. The Mediterranean resort is six miles north of Tel Aviv.
   The blast gutted the restaurant, blew away its rear wall and
damaged the second floor, where a home for the elderly is located,
said Associated Press photographer Max Nash.
   Two trucks and at least one car were overturned by the explosion.
   ``We sat down and were served when all of a sudden the whole
building exploded,'' one pizzeria customer, Levy Sudi, told Israel
radio. ``The whole building collapsed on us. Glass, bricks, blocks.
I don't remember what happened afterwards.''
   Herzilia Mayor Eli Landau told the radio: ``Cars are overturned,
metal is ripped. The first and second stories of the building are
completely destroyed.''
   A crane was used to evacuate residents of the retirement home. A
bloodied blanket hung out of one of the shattered second-floor
windows.
   Some of the elderly residents, including a man and a woman with
blood on their arms and legs, appeared to be in shock.
   ``Take it easy, Mummy, take it easy,'' one woman told her
mother, who was walking amid the rubble in a daze.
   One of the injured was in serious condition with a chest injury
and two suffered moderate injuries. The others were slightly
injured, said Dr. Avinoam Eliashiv, a doctor at Meir Hospital.
</TEXT>
