<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1357EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-US     06-20 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-US,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Businessmen Participate in Biggest Chinese Trade Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 American businessmen Monday attended
the opening session of China's largest trade conference, seeking to
exchange economic know-how with their Chinese counterparts.
   The four-day U.S.-China Joint Session on Industry, Trade and
Economic Development in Beijing's Great Hall of the People includes
1,000 Chinese from 22 provinces, who are looking for U.S. capital
and technology to fuel their drive for economic modernization.
   The Americans are mostly businessmen from small or medium-sized
companies on their first trip to China to meet representatives of
Chinese industries.
   The opening session began with a noisy welcome from a Chinese
children's drum and cymbal band, as well as greetings from
President Reagan, Vice President George Bush and Chinese Premier Li
Peng.
   ``Between our two countries there is enormous potential for
development,'' Li said.
   Reagan, in his message read by U.S. Ambassador Winston Lord,
noted that bilateral trade reached $10.4 billion last year and was
up 19 percent in the first quarter of this year, while U.S.
businessmen had invested $3 billion in China, more than in any
other country except Hong Kong.
   Speakers offered frank criticisms of American and Chinese trade
and economic policies, but agreed that U.S. restrictions on high
technology sales to China are counterproductive.
   The State Department last fall temporarily froze liberalization
of high tech sales to China to protest alleged sales of Chinese
Silkworm missiles to Iran, but lifted the freeze in March.
   Vice Minister Li Lanqing of the Foreign Economic Relations and
Trade Ministry criticized the United States for failing to grant
China the favored-nation trade status, which would curb the
restrictions on high tech sales and ease other trade barriers.
   These, he said, damage ``U.S. businessmen's interests and
competitiveness in China.''
   ``Under current procedures, the State Department uses trade
restrictions to advance diplomatic interests or to express its
frustrations with the behavior of other nations,'' said Roger
Sullivan, chairman of the National Council for U.S.-China Trade.
   Former U.S. Chamber of Commerce Chairman Edwin D. Dodd said
China needs to emulate Asian countries like Singapore and South
Korea by promoting private enterprise.
   But Sullivan advised China to develop its domestic economy
rather than copying the Singapore or Hong Kong model of
export-oriented growth, which is dependent on cheap labor and
protectionism.
   Liu Hongru, deputy governor of the central People's Bank of
China, admitted that China's financial system remains plagued by
inefficient use of funds, badly trained staff and rigid currency
exchange controls.
   Chinese law expert Jerome Cohen said there are still ``frequent
overlaps and even contradictions between national and local
legislation'' and that China still lacks copyright, mortgage,
insurance, banking and other laws.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880620-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1330EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Puzzle Bjt   06-20 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Puzzle, Bjt,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Briefings Provide the Pieces, But in a Jumble</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although the leaders of the world's most powerful
democracies meet in a summit cocoon of strict privacy, their
statements and the gist of negotiations are relayed in a
near-torrent of briefings by official spokesmen and senior advisers.
   But the picture that emerges can be as hard to fit together as a
pile of jumbled jigsaw pieces. Sometimes it's hard to believe that
all the briefers were even describing the same puzzle.
   Part of the problem is that the officials with the job of
carrying the news to some 3,000 anxious journalists are working
with second-hand information themselves. With rare exceptions, they
were not present at the discussions. The briefers had to be briefed
themselves.
   Then there's the impulse by each country to emphasize its own
role, interpret developments from its point of view _ impart what
is known as its ``spin'' on the news.
   This suits the reporters, as well, who naturally want to focus
on the performance of their own country's leaders in the world
arena.
   The official declarations of the leaders of the seven
industrialized democracies are issued as carefully prepared
communiques, after every word has been weighed.
   But there also are more than 20 briefings each day, from early
in the morning until past midnight.
   With the exception of Japan, which conducts separate briefings
in Japanese and English, each delegation reports exclusively in its
own language _ or in the case of bilingual Canada, two languages _
without simultanous translation.
   To be sure of getting every point of view, a reporter would have
to be fluent in five languages _ and capable of being in several
places at once.
   Instead, news organizations cover as many briefings as they can,
and struggle to resolve the apparent contradictions that come up.
   One key issue at the Toronto summit is what to do about the debt
load on the world's poorest nations. Each participating country has
its own ideas, and several are eager to be seen as the one which
showed the way.
   After Monday's opening summit session, the British delegation
announced that agreement had been reached on how to deal with the
Third World debt, in an accord based on Britain's proposals.
   French officials have been pushing President Francois
Mitterrand's proposal on the debt crisis _ similar in many ways to
Britain's _ and they said Sunday and again Monday that the
agreement was not yet final.
   ``Nothing is settled before the final communique,'' a Mitterrand
aide told a briefing.
   President Reagan's spokesman, Marlin Fitzwater, left the
impression at his briefing Sunday that the debt question had
scarcely been raised.
   The Canadians, meanwhile, who like to think they have a genius
for bringing about compromise, said Monday that they were working
actively to bring the different positions together.
   One delegation official, speaking on condition of anonymity
about the apparent conflicts, said there was rarely any intention
to distort the issues.
   ``We will see consensus on debt, but each country will perceive
the discussions in a selective way _ not negatively, in a humanly
selective way,'' the official said.
   Paul Frazer, spokesman for Canadian Foreign Minister Joe Clark,
said an accurate briefing is a difficult art, in part because
reporters ``would like an impression, they'd like an assessment,''
rather than a dry recitation of events.
   ``One of the toughest things to do in giving a briefing is to
stick to the facts,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Campbell, the news editor in the
Associated Press' Paris bureau, is on assignment in Toronto
covering the economic summit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
