<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Notebook Bjt   06-20 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Notebook, Bjt,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Names, Civilized Americans, Souvenir Pins and Other Summit
Tidbits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLE FELDMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just call him Ron.
   President Reagan invoked an air of informality at his first
summit seven years ago, and is trying to keep it up at his last.
   At the outset of the Toronto meeting, Reagan told the newcomers,
Prime Ministers Noboru Takeshita of Japan and Ciriaco De Mita of
Italy, that the leaders were on a first-name basis.
   ``My name is Ron,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
quoted the president as saying.
   Fitzwater didn't say whether they took him up on it.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Many of the eight delegations to the economic summit held
late-night briefings for the media that stretched into the early
hours Monday _ but not the United States.
   Fitzwater was asked why he wasn't following the lead set by the
French, who conducted a briefing at 1 a.m.
   ``We're so civilized in the United States,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The 14th annual economic meeting among the industrialized
democracies might be remembered as the summit of pins.
   There were circle pins and triangle pins, rectangular pins and
freeform pins promoting the summit and various products and locales.
   When supplies dried up, metropolitan Toronto was quick to take
action.
   A ``Pin-Free Zone'' was established in the city's tent in Summit
Square, the watering hole for delegates and journalists.
   But by Monday morning the pin supply had been replenished, and
the pin-free zone lifted.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Economic summitry can't interfere with true love.
   Summit organizers had tried to postpone a wedding at the
exclusive Hunt Club, also the site of the leaders' first dinner.
But club officials turned them down flat.
   ``We would certainly have been upset'' had the reception been
postponed, the father of the bride, Logan Brown, told the Toronto
Star.
   The wedding between his daughter, Sandra, and Roman Bandi went
off as scheduled Saturday.
   And the leaders dined the next night.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Security is so tight at the economic summit that even the food
undergoes scrutiny.
   Mary D'Alton, project coordinator of Kitchener Caterers, said,
``The security level is much, much higher (than previous catered
gatherings). It adds an extra concern.''
   ``Everything is swept by security, everything, everything,'' she
said, referring to the metal-detecting wands wielded by security
agents.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Speaking of food, summit organizers hoped to donate Summit
Square leftovers to the city's poor and homeless _ if the 3,000
journalists and 1,500 delegates didn't consume it all first.
   There was nothing left Saturday and Sunday.
   Barb Richardson, dispatcher for Second Harvest, said Monday that
she hoped the glutonous appetites would ease during the final two
days of the summit.
   She said the group, which distributes food to various
organizations assisting the poor and homeless, wasn't picky. ``As
long as its edible, we'll take it,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
