<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DroughtDreams Bjt   06-20 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Dreams, Bjt,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tennessee Farmer's Dreams Ruined by Drought</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This is one in an ongoing series of stories about the effects
of the 1988 drought on the nation.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARYVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Clemmer has begun dreaming that his
drought-stricken fields are being drenched by a soft, gentle rain.
But this happy reverie turns to dust each morning, when the sun
comes streaming over the nearby Smoky Mountains.
   ``What I see when I look out my window in the morning makes me
sick to my stomach,'' says the 50-year-old Clemmer, who has been
raising cattle and crops in Blount County for the past quarter
century.
   What he sees is a rolling expanse of wilted, yellowish grass
that has been cropped to the nub by hungry cattle.
   And, lately, Clemmer has been seeing something else happening in
those seared fields, something he can hardly believe.
   ``Just look out there,'' he said Sunday afternoon while he and
some neighbors sat in the shade. ``It looks like a winter sight,
don't it? Here it is June and I'm feeding hay to my cattle.''
   Out in the field about 30 cows and calves were gathered around a
roll of hay that Clemmer had put out that morning.
   ``I've been putting out hay for two weeks now because there's
simply no grass left in my fields,'' he said. ``If this was a
normal year I wouldn't have to put out any hay until Thanksgiving,
and maybe even a little later than that.''
   But this is hardly a normal year in eastern Tennessee, one of
the hardest-hit drought areas in the Southeast.
   ``Our rainfall level for the year already is 10 inches below
average,'' said Ralph Lovely, the University of Tennessee
Agricultural Extension Service agent in Blount County, just east of
Knoxville.
   Lovely added, ``This drought cycle is killing us. We're down 40
inches over the past four years; that's a year's rainfall we've
lost.''
   As a result, he said, trees are dying and hay and row crops,
such as corn and soybeans, are withering. He predicted many
cattlemen in the county, one of the state's biggest
cattle-producing areas, will be forced to dump their herds this
fall for lack of feed.
   Clemmer said he probably will be among them.
   ``At the rate I'm going I won't have any hay left for winter,''
he said. ``By fall, the price of hay will be out of sight; besides,
nobody can afford hay and feed on a year-round basis.''
   Adding to his problems, he said, is the fact that the yield of
his first hay crop, which he cut two weeks ago, was more than 50
percent below normal.
   ``And, on top of that, I've got 75 acres in corn that isn't
going to make it, either, unless we get a lot of rain the next two
weeks,'' he said. ``I've already decided not to plant soy beans
this year. It would just be a waste of time and money.''
   Clemmer said money has become a major concern while he has
watched his crops dry up along with his dreams.
   ``This is the fourth straight year of bad drought for us here in
eastern Tennessee,'' he said. ``We didn't get any snow to speak of
last winter and we haven't had any rain to speak of this spring.
   ``Each year I've said one more bad year would be all I could
take and it looks like this will be the one that does me in.''
   About that time a neighbor stopped by to tell him about a
thunderstorm that left water standing in the fields and ditches
several miles down the road. He invited Clemmer to come and take a
look.
   ``No,'' Clemmer said, shaking his head. ``I couldn't stand to
look. It would just make me sick.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Strat Douthat is the AP Southeast regional
reporter, based in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
