<DOCNO> AP880620-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1431EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nicaragua-Rights     06-20 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Rights,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Already Undoing Limited Civil Liberties Gains, Group
Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nicaraguan human rights group charged Monday
that the Sandinista government has used limited improvements in
civil liberties to gain favorable international publicity, then has
quickly reimposed past repression.
   The result is that more than 10 months after a regional peace
accord was reached at Esquipulas, Guatemala, there has been little
or no progress toward realizing promised democratic reforms, said
the Nicaraguan Permanent Commission on Human Rights, an opposition
group.
   Commission Director Lino Hernandez said the Sandinista
government has made some concessions that seemed positive at the
time but which have been undone by subsequent actions and
ultimately appear to have been used only to project a benign image
to the world.
   ``The spaces that had opened under Esquipulas are being closed
once again in Nicaragua,'' Hernandez said at a news conference.
   The freeing of political prisoners and lifting of a state of
emergency by the leftist Managua government have been
counterbalanced by laws that violate human rights, the harassment
of labor unions and the use of government-inspired mobs to
intimidate opposition politicians, the group said.
   The positive steps taken early in the peace process ``in the
long run ... have turned out to be completely insufficient even to
create the proper climate for beginning a national reconciliation''
called for in the accords, the commission said in a report.
   The report specifically cited instances in which opposition
radio stations had been censored and newsprint rationed to the
opposition newspaper La Prensa. A 1981 decree is being newly
enforced to prevent publication of information about military
actions or about the prices of food and other consumer goods, it
said.
   A broadcaster who frequently lampoons the Sandinista government
and is also a member of the commission, Jose Castillo, was
physically assaulted by Interior Minister Tomas Borge in April
after being summoned to Borge's house, the report stated.
   The Sandinista military continues to forcibly conscript young
men and the regime continues to hold some 8,200 political
prisoners, the group charged. Political arrests continue at a rate
of about 50 per month, Hernandez said.
  
</TEXT>
