<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     06-20 1008</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,1044</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Something apparently tickled Madonna's funny
bone as she read on stage from a book about radiation and the end
of the world.
   Theatergoers watching David Mamet's hit Broadway play ``Speed
the Plow'' on Saturday night all had one question during
intermission: was the rock star's strange outburst of laughter part
of the play? Or was it an unscheduled case of the giggles?
   The latter, it turns out.
   ``It certainly isn't in the script,'' confirmed ``Speed the
Plow'' spokesman Bruce Campbell on Monday. The play opened to rave
notices on May 3, though the critics were not all kind to Madonna
who was making her Broadway debut.
   The embarrassing moment came toward the end of the first act as
Madonna, who plays a secretary to a Hollywood wheeler-dealer, tries
to persuade her boss that a book about radiation and the end of the
world would make a good film. Her boss, played by Joe Mantegna,
wants mainly to get her in bed.
   As Madonna started reading excerpts from the book she began to
giggle. She laughed for several minutes as the audience at the
Royale Theatre buzzed uncomfortably. Mantegna, seated next to her
on a couch, never took his eyes off her, cradling his chin in his
hands with a bemused expression.
   Regaining control at last, she said, ``I was saying...'' and
picked up where she left off.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joey Lawrence, at 12 already a star for five
years on the television show ``Gimme A Break,'' will become the
Arthritis Foundation's ``Ambassador for Youth'' to help juvenile
arthritis sufferers.
   Lawrence will make special appearances, tape public service
announcements and generally focus attention on and raise funds for
research and education about arthritis, foundation officials said
in a statement released Monday.
   ``The Ambassador for Youth is a special responsibility that
calls for a sensitive person,'' said Arthritis Foundation
Chairwoman Betsy Brewster Case. ``Joey's abilities and popularity
with other children make him an excellent choice as our main
spokesperson for children.''
   The foundation estimates that about 165,000 children in the
United States suffer from arthritis-related diseases.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An improper traffic turn led
to handcuffs and jail for Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu's wife,
Leah, who paid a fine Monday to get rid of the traffic offense.
   But Tutu, winner of the 1984 Nobel Peace Prize for his
campaigning against racial segregation, or apartheid, in South
Africa has complained about the treatment of his wife and indicated
he might pursue legal action.
   The fines, totalling $40 dollars, followed Mrs. Tutu's arrest on
June 10 by a traffic officer who handcuffed her.
   She was briefly held in a police cell, then released on bail
pending the magistrate's court hearing Monday. She was fined for
making an improper turn and failing to make an initial court
appearance in the case.
   Johannesburg municipal officials conducted an inquiry into the
incident while the Tutus were visiting the Soviet Union last week
and exonerated the police without hearing Mrs. Tutu's version of
the matter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dick Cavett declined to try the parallel bars
saying he hadn't worn his gym shorts, but the television talk-show
personality otherwise did his bit to honor an alma mater
celebrating its 100th year.
   Cavett spoke for about an hour Saturday to 350 people at a
banquet in Sokol Hall, a South Omaha private school for gymnasts.
Cavett, who was a Nebraska high school champion in gymnastics, used
the hall for workouts.
   ``We tried to get him (Cavett) to do something on the parallel
bars, but he declined because he didn't have shorts, or something
like that,'' said Frank Felner, the hall's assistant manager.
   Cavett also took questions from the audience and kept them
laughing. When asked, ``Will you comment on your high school love
life?'' Cavett shot back, ``Why? Is she here?''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEANBLOSSOM, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sweet mountain songs that echoed
through the trees and across the nearby blue hills sounded for the
final time when Bill Monroe fiddled his last tune at his annual
Beanblossom Bluegrass Festival.
   There was sadness and some disbelief among fans who attended the
final performances in southern Indiana during the weekend.
   ``You wouldn't believe the party that went on,'' said ticket
taker Debbie Guffey over the weekend. ``But today everybody looks
kinda hangdog and sad. I guess it's all over.''
   Monroe has packed his goodtime music after 22 years for a move
to Nashville where he'll open a restaurant with his son.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If he had it to do over, actor-activist
Martin Sheen says he would have trained for his career.
   ``I wanted to study (when he arrived in New York), but I
couldn't afford it,'' he said during a recent trip to Los Angeles
to promote his latest movie ``Da.''
   ``When I began to make my living (as an actor), I didn't feel
any great need for it. I figured that the only thing I would play
would be a human and I felt my classroom was in the streets. I'm
instinctual, but I don't think you can teach anyone to be a good
actor.
   ``The area of study I think is critical is on the body: You
should study dance and you have to be healthy. Also, you have to
know classical literature. If I had to do it again, that's what I'd
study,'' he said.
   Sheen, 48, is ardent in his work for the Roman Catholic Church
and his quest for world peace has made him a willing protester.
   ``I generally don't have a preconceived notion of a character
until I'm playing it,'' Sheen said. ``It means you're open to
changes in the character. I do surrender to the moment _ go with
instinct _ but it also means I might be shooting for several weeks
before I finally figure out the part.''
   `Da,'' based on the 1977 Tony Award winning play, deals with the
relationship between an Irish father and his son.
</TEXT>
