<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Attack     06-20 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Attack,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Attack Prime Minister's Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of Prime Minister Maudud Ahmed
was attacked by anti-government students Monday and her car was set
ablaze, but she was not injured, witnesses said.
   Hasna Maudud had her sari torn in the scuffle, the witnesses
said.
   Mrs. Maudud, a Parliament member of the ruling Jatiya Party, was
attacked inside the Dhaka University campus when she went to attend
the annual meeting of the university senate as a government nominee.
   The students set her car ablaze and beat up her chauffeur. A
security guard also was attacked by the students when he tried to
protect Mrs. Maudud, according to the witnesses, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   ``We did not know that the prime minister's wife was coming to
attend the meeting. We were not informed or we would have taken
precautionary measures,'' said Mustafizur Rahman, a senior
professor at the university.
   An hour after the attack, about 50 students marched on campus,
shouting anti-government slogans. Two homemade bombs exploded as
they passed the vice-chancellor's office, but no one was injured,
witnesses said.
   Dhaka University is a major center of opposition to the
government of President Hussain Muhammad Ershad.
</TEXT>
