<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1447EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoldingTrial     06-20 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolding Trial,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maryland Nurse Acquitted of Killing Three Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UPPER MARLBORO, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Monday acquitted a nurse
accused of killing three of her patients with lethal doses of
potassium chloride, saying prosecutors failed to tie her to the
deaths.
   ``The state's reach hopelessly exceeded its grasp,'' Prince
George's County Circuit Court Judge Joseph S. Casula said in
dismissing the case. ``Simply put, the evidence failed to supply
the missing link that would connect the defendant with alleged
criminal acts.''
   Jane Bolding, 30, who claimed she had been forced into
confessing to killing two of the patients during a marathon
interrogation, faced three counts of first-degree murder in
connection with the deaths of three patients at the Prince George's
Hospital Center, located about 30 miles from Washington, D.C. She
also was charged with trying to kill two others the same way.
   ``I said three and a half years ago that I was innocent,''
Bolding said after Casula issued his decision in the non-jury
trial. ``It's been proven now.''
   Bolding, who now works filing medical records, did not say when
or if she would resume her nursing career.
   ``She can't go to a nurses' station and say, `Please restore my
reputation,''' defense attorney Fred Joseph said. ``That's going to
take a long time.''
   ``I'm very disappointed in the outcome,'' Assistant State's
Attorney Jay Creech said. ``I feel that the evidence I presented
was strong and compelling.''
   During the month-long proceedings, no witness testified to
seeing Bolding give the patients unauthorized injections, and no
causes of death ever were established, although post-mortem
examinations revealed all three had high levels of potassium.
   Creech based his case on a study by the federal Centers for
Disease Control that revealed that patients in the hospital's
intensive care unit suffered an unusually high number of heart
attacks while Bolding was working.
   According to the study, Bolding was the primary care nurse when
57 heart attacks occurred. The next-highest number for any nurse
was five.
   Dr. Jeffrey J. Sacks, the author of the study, testified that 88
heart attacks occurred while Bolding was on duty from January 1984
to March 1985, the period covered by the study.
   Health statistics projected that just 31 heart attacks should
have taken place during that time, and Sacks estimated that the
odds of Bolding not being in some way connected with the rash of
heart attacks were about one in 100 trillion.
   However, under cross-examination, Sacks also testified that his
statistical findings could not be used to address the matter of
intent to commit a crime.
   In the absence of a witness to the alleged crimes, Casula ruled
that he could not give undue weight to the CDC study.
   ``A conviction cannot rest soley on a statistical study,'' said
Casula, who added that a guilty verdict under such circumstances
would turn courtrooms across the country into ``mathematical
quagmires.''
   Bolding became the subject of an investigation in 1985 after
hospital officials became suspicious of the high number of heart
attacks on her shift. She signed a letter of confession to two of
the killings later that year.
   However, the statement was ruled inadmissible as evidence after
revelations that it came in the midst of 33 straight hours of
interrogation in which she was denied access to an attorney.
   Murder charges then were dismissed, but reinstated after a grand
jury heard testimony on the CDC study.
   Two medical experts testified they were certain outside
injections of the electrolyte had caused heart attacks in several
victims, but other experts said numerous medical occurrences can
cause high potassium levels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
