<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--NorCalQuake     06-20 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--NorCal Quake,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Report 4-Second Temblor From Calaveras Fault Movement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORGAN HILL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake jostled
communities in the southern San Francisco Bay area on Monday, eight
days after a much stronger shaker struck in the same fault zone.
   No damage or injury was reported from the latest quake.
   The new quake, generated by the Calaveras Fault, set the ground
quivering at 8:26 a.m., with an epicenter seven miles east of
Morgan Hill and a Richter scale reading up to 4.0.
   ``It was a good one,'' said Morgan Hill police dispatcher Nancy
True. ``We felt it for about four seconds, but we didn't get a
single (telephone) call,'' or any reports of damage.
   ``We never felt a thing,'' said Gilroy police dispatcher Manuel
Texeira, 10 miles to the south. ``And the only calls we've gotten
have been from reporters.''
   A quake of 4.0 on the Richter scale can cause moderate damage.
