<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-Thatcher     06-20 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Thatcher,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thatcher Shifts Into Key Role: This Time No One Seems To Mind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America is the most powerful participant and
Canada is the host, but it is British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher who has subtly taken over a key role at the seven-nation
economic summit.
   Often resented and sometimes ostracized at other international
gatherings, Mrs. Thatcher appears to have moved to center stage
this time with scant sign of demurral from her fellow leaders of
the world's major industrialized countries.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney invited the 62-year-old
British prime minister, now the longest serving leader in the
Western world, to make the opening address and set the tone on
economic issues for the three-day gathering.
   Canadian officials said the invitation reflected Mrs. Thatcher's
seniority at the gathering of the United States, Canada, Britain,
West Germany, Italy, France and Japan.
   In office for nine years, she has held power longer than
President Reagan, nearing the end of his second and final four-year
term.
   Reagan, to whom Mrs. Thatcher has been the closest and most
loyal foreign ally, has always sought to bolster her international
prestige. Last December, Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev also
increased her standing by conferring with her en route to a
superpower summit meeting in Washington.
   But at meetings of the 12-nation European Economic Community,
France _ Britain's longtime rival _ has openly resented and sought
to block Mrs. Thatcher's moves to dominate or get her way.
   In contrast, Britain and France are allied at the Toronto
meetings in pressing a less enthusiastic U.S. delegation to agree
to substantive debt relief measures for the poorest African nations.
   Some analysts believe Mulroney's deference toward Mrs. Thatcher,
a fellow conservative, has been spurred by Canada's elections next
year. The British leader's high profile at the summit provides a
ringing endorsement for Mulroney's conservative cause.
   Mrs. Thatcher lauds free-enterprise policies that she says have
wrought an economic transformation in Britain and account for
steady growth among the summit seven.
   ``That sort of talk fits Mr. Mulroney's agenda perfectly,''
commented Toronto's Globe and Mail newspaper.
   ``Clearly the hope was that she would set the agenda for the
summit,'' a British government spokesman, who insisted on
anonymity, said of Mulroney's invitation to Mrs. Thatcher.
   Canadian delegation spokesman Derek Burney said he thought that
was overplaying things a bit.
   But Thatcher's spokesman saw no conflict, saying Canada invited
Thatcher to set the economic tone, while Reagan set the agenda for
talks on East-West relations. ``This is the greatest non-issue of
the summit ... forget it,'' said the British spokesman.
   The robust response reflected the exuberance and confidence that
the Thatcher government displays at international conferences,
often to the irritation of its allies.
   Yet the briefings by Mrs. Thatcher's blunt-speaking press
secretary, Bernard Ingham, attract the largest numbers of reporters.
   And in the fleeting glimpses that cameramen and reporters get of
the leaders, Mrs. Thatcher rivals Reagan as a favorite target for
cameramen.
   Other differences were sidelined in Toronto, including over
South Africa.
   In the Commonwealth, the 48-nation association of Britain and
its former colonies, Mrs. Thatcher has been isolated because of her
refusal to impose tough embargoes against the white-minority
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
