<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RedSquare     06-20 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Red Square,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moscow On the Nightclub Circuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pictures of Stalin, May Day parades in
Moscow and everyday life in the Soviet Union flashed on screens at
the new ``Red Square'' nightclub, touted as a cultural classroom in
disco guise.
   ``We want to make the idea of peace sexy, something people will
want to pursue,'' said Sanford Keller, one of two local nightclub
owners presenting the once-a-week event in a former warehouse that
for years was a dance hall.
   Patrons at Saturday night's opening gala absorbed the cultural
experience, even getting into the spirit by wearing T-shirts with
pictures of the Kremlin emblazoned on them, but most said they were
just looking for a good time.
   ``Hey, with (President) Reagan and (Soviet Union leader Mikhail)
Gorbachev's meetings in the news all the time, red is hot this
year, comrade,'' shouted Jeff O'Neill, 31, over the din of the rock
music.
   Among the guests were Alexander D. Terekhin, consul general in
San Francisco for the Soviet Union, and several of his aides and
their spouses.
   ``They said it definitely had the feeling of the Soviet Union,''
said Brian Raffi, the second partner in the nightclub.
   Raffi said Terekhin reacted favorably toward his idea of opening
a U.S.-style nightclub in Leningrad called Union Square, after the
famous San Francisco landmark.
   In the San Francisco club, giant cloth and metal red cupolas
dominated the interior of the disco. Paintings and sculptures by
modernist Russian artists decorated the walls. Halfway through the
night, a ballet company put on a fashion show of gaudy 14th century
Russian outfits.
   If people were just showing up for fun, that didn't disappoint
Raffi, who also owns one of the avant-garde music clubs in the
city's burgeoning nightclub district in the South of Market area,
known as SoMa for short.
   ``At my other club I've always tried to display art from new
artists and expose young people to new bands and new types of
music, and with this I've taken it a step farther by attempting to
expose them to a whole new culture,'' Raffi said. ``While they may
not come for an education, they can't really avoid it.''
   Keller, who described his ethnic heritage as three-quarters
Russian, said the nightclub has received enthusiastic support from
San Francisco's Russian-American community, one of the largest in
the United States.
   With their help, Red Square was able to highlight the night with
performances of traditional Russian songs and, the Cossack dance,
where a squatting man kicks his legs straight out from beneath him
one at a time.
</TEXT>
