<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-Japan     06-20 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Japan,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Japanese Tout Agreement on Agricultural Products</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The benefit of the increased imports and lower
tariffs on U.S. beef and oranges that Japan agreed to Monday will
be available to other countries worldwide, said an official of the
Japanese delegation to the seven-nation economic summit said.
   The official, who spoke on condition that he not be identified,
said Australia had expressed a particular interest in the issue
because of its beef production. He said Japanese Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita may send his agriculture minister, Takashi Sato,
to Australia soon.
   He said he did not know whether it would be necessary to
negotiate a separate agreement in such cases.
   ``I don't know the technicalities, but in principle, the
benefits of the agreement have global application,'' he said.
   The agreement reached in Tokyo calls for Japan to increase
imports and lower some of its tariffs on U.S. beef and oranges over
the next six years, U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said
in the Japanese capital.
   Japan would nearly double its imports of beef by 1991 and would
phase out its Livestock Industry Promotion Corporation, which
controls most beef imports.
   The Japanese would be allowed to set tariffs of 70 percent in
1991, 60 percent in 1992 and 50 percent in 1993 to give their
farmers time to adjust to the new rules.
   Yeutter said he expects the value of U.S. beef exports to Japan
to at least double as a result of the pact, reaching more than $1
billion a year.
   The Tokyo government agreed to expand market access for fresh
oranges by 22,000 tons per year, bringing them to 192,000 tons in
1990.
   From then on, fresh oranges from the United States could be
imported in unlimited quantities, at current tariff rates of 40
percent in season and 20 percent off season. Quotas on orange juice
will be phased out.
   The agreement was signed by Yeutter and Sato.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
