<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Political, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0555,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Officials Endorse US Position on Laundering of Drug Profits</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout with political statement; No Pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the seven summit nations today
endorsed a U.S. proposal to curb the laundering of drug profits and
strongly condemned terrorism in all forms, including the taking of
hostages.
   The leaders pledged their ``full contribution'' to international
efforts to resettle Afghan refugees. And while welcoming
U.S.-Soviet reductions in nuclear arms, they said the Soviet
military buildup in the Far East is a ``major source of instability
in Asia.''
   In a statement read by Canadian Foreign Minister Joe Clark, the
leaders took ``positive note'' of East European countries' growing
interest in ending their economic isolation, but said commerce with
those countries should be on a commercial basis under the rules of
international trade.
   The statement said ``terrorists must not go unpunished'' and
endorsed the principle that hijacked aircraft should not be allowed
to take off once they have landed.
   On drugs, the leaders supported the recent U.S. initiative for a
special task force to coordinate the global fight against narcotics
and said greater efforts are especially needed ``to trace, freeze
and confiscate the proceeds of drug traffickers and to curb money
laundering.''
   Left out of the joint statement were several contentious
regional issues where the leaders took an unofficial stand.
   On the Middle East, they said the violence on the Israeli-held
West Bank showed the need for a negotiated settlement between
Israel and its Arab neighbors, and on South Africa, they called for
clemency for the Sharpeville Six, five black men and one woman
sentenced to hang for a lynch-mob attack on a black policeman. On
Southeat Asia, they called for the withdrawal of Vietnamese troops
from Cambodia and reestablishment of the country's independence.
</TEXT>
