<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Explosion     06-20 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Explosion,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gas Explosion Injures 24, Nursing Home Evacuated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HERZLIYA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tanks of cooking gas exploded in a
pizzeria in this coastal resort Monday, injuring 24 Israelis and
forcing the evacuation of 60 residents of an adjacent nursing home,
police said.
   The cause of the explosion was under investigation, but appeared
to be accidental, police said.
   ``All of a sudden we heard a blast and everything went up in the
air,'' said Rachel Bardo, a waitress at the Pizzeria Rimini who was
hospitalized with a facial injury. ``We were all up in the air.
   ``I didn't understand what was happening ... I lost
consciousness and got up somehow and went outside to call for
help,'' she told Israel television.
   Police said gas leaked from 15 tanks stored in the pizzeria,
located about 150 yards from the Mediterranean. Herzliya is about
six miles north of Tel Aviv.
   The explosion gutted the restaurant, blew away the rear wall and
damaged the second floor, said Associated Press photographer Max
Nash. Two trucks and one car were overturned, he said.
   Police said the blast also damaged the staircase leading to the
nursing home on the second and third floors above the pizzeria.
   ``We were just about to take the patients out to serve something
to drink when everything collapsed,'' Yeshayahu Kroiter, a nursing
home employee, told Israel TV. ``There was hysteria, and everything
went dark and that's the last thing I felt.''
   Nursing home residents were evacuated by a fire department
crane. A bloodied blanket hung out of one of the shattered
second-floor windows.
   Some of the elderly victims, including a man and a woman with
blood on their arms and legs, appeared to be in shock.
   ``Take it easy, mummy, take it easy,'' one woman told her
elderly mother, who was walking amid the rubble in a daze.
   Police said it took two hours to evacuate the nursing home
residents and take those who escaped unharmed to a nearby hotel.
   Of the 24 injured, a 20-year-old woman was serious condition
with a fractured skull, and two men suffered moderate injuries,
said Dr. Shlomi Entebbi of nearby Meir Hospital. The other 21
sustained minor injuries, he said.
   Police said the explosion was triggered by the gas leak, but
that the cause was still under investigation.
   ``It apparently was not terrorism, but we still must see why
there was a leak,'' said a Tel Aviv police official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
