<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENID, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randy Hylton's job is driving stars around,
so when word got out that the bus parked outside his home here had
a destination sign that said ``Burt Reynolds,'' Randy got a lot of
knocks on his door.
   For the past eight years, the Enid resident has driven show
buses _ customized Greyhounds emphasizing creature comforts _ for
entertainers on tour. Some of his passengers have been such singers
as Julio Iglesias, Julian Lennon, Jermaine Jackson, Tanya Tucker,
Stevie Nicks, magician David Copperfield and, his favorite, Crosby,
Stills and Nash.
   The buses, Hylton said recently, feature all the comforts of
home with two television sets, two stereos, two VCRs, a microwave
and a refrigerator and can sleep nine.
   Hylton said people frequently come by to gawk at the large
custom-painted showbuses _ costing as much as $300,000 _ that he
parks outside when he's home between jobs on the road.
   During a recent stopover, road crew members jokingly rolled a
destination sign on the bus to reveal actor Burt Reynolds' name. A
lot of neighbors were sure that the actor who recently married
actress Loni Anderson was taking a delayed honeymoon trip to Enid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST MINERAL, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A festival named for a coal shovel was
a mighty big time of dancing, singing and politicians stumping for
votes at the ``Big Brutus Summer `88 Celebration'' in southeast
Kansas.
   About 10 politicans campaigned on the stage underneath Big
Brutus, a coal shovel that stands 16 stories tall. State Sen. Phil
Martin, a Pittsburg Democrat, brought a calliope to the festival.
   ``I think calliopes and politicians have a lot in common,''
Martin said. ``We are both loud and we run on hot air.''
   Candidates for the Kansas Legislature, county offices and a
congressional seat also turned out to campaign.
   Festival officials said an estimated 8,000 people attended the
weekend festival.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even Rembrandt, Picasso and da Vinci might be
envious of four local artists whose works will soon be seen by tens
of thousands of onlookers every hour.
   The work of the four, selected from 77 entrants in the 2nd
annual billboard competition sponsored by Patrick Media Group of
Dallas Inc., will be displayed next month on billboards throughout
Dallas.
   ``Most of the artwork, you have to go to a gallery or museum to
look at,'' contest winner Chong Keun Chu told the Dallas Morning
News. ``But this way, everyone can look at it. It's another way to
communicate.''
   Marilyn Jolly, fellow artist and contest winner, agreed.
   ``The more that people can look at your work and respond to it,
the more that communication goes on,'' Ms. Jolly said.
   ``I think when you take something that's really commercial and
then take the commerce out of it, that's real interesting,'' said
Pamela Nelson, whose original artwork measured about the size of a
bumper sticker. Soon, it will compete with skyscrapers to capture
the attention of freeway drivers.
   Contest winner Arthello Beck Jr. said the billboard artist must
keep it simple to get across his or her message.
   ``If someone's going to drive by, you just get a glimpse of a
billboard,'' Beck said. ``You should say something real quickly and
get to the point and not have a lot of detail.''
   Ms. Nelson, whose artwork features a distinctively Dallas
clothesline with fashions ranging from Neiman-Marcus to Hypermart,
said some of the entries did not follow Beck's philosophy.
   ``There were some (paintings) I thought might need to be by a
red light,'' she said.
   The winning billboards will change locations every 60 days for
the next 12 months. But Chu said no matter where his work winds up,
he will find it.
   ``Wherever they put it, I'm going to go look at it _ a lot.''
</TEXT>
