<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit Rdp, 6th Ld-Writethru,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summit Leaders Turn Attention Toward Arms Control</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Consolidates material in a0690, a0693; cuts final six grafs
to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the seven-nation economic summit
called on the nations of the Soviet bloc today to ``end their
economic isolation'' and gave a solid endorsement to U.S. efforts
to reduce nuclear arms.
   The leaders summed up their political discussion by issuing a
joint statement at the mid-point of their three-day conference.
   ``Our peoples stand in solidarity within the framework of our
existing alliances for the cause of freedom, to safeguard democracy
and the prosperity which it has produced,'' the statement said.
   The leaders repeated earlier condemnations of terrorism and also
endorsed efforts to hamper hijackers by preventing commandered
aircraft from taking off once they have landed.
   On drugs, the leaders backed a U.S. proposal to establish a
special task force to improve international cooperation in the
battle against illegal narcotics. The effort is aimed at choking
off the flow of profits to drug traffickers.
   The leaders put aside or resolved their disagreements on Third
World debt and farm subsidies as they took discussed East-West
relations in the wake of President Reagan's Moscow summit with
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``We take positive note of Eastern countries growing interest in
ending their economic isolation, for example in the establishment
and development of relations with the European Community,'' the
political statement said.
   Canadian Foreign Minister Joe Clark read the statement to an
auditorium filled with journalists as the leaders began their
second formal meeting of the day.
   In a companion statement read along with the poltical
communique, the countries expressed their ``abhorence of
apartheid'' and said that every legal option should be exercised to
obtain clemency for the Sharpeville Six, black South Africans who
were convicted of complicity in the 1984 mob killing of black town
councilor during riots provoked by a rent increase.
   The political statement also endorsed U.S. arms control
negotiations with the Soviet Union and called for further
negotiations to reduce non-nuclear forces in Europe.
   The summit leaders congratulated Reagan for his efforts to
obtain a U.S.-Soviet treaty to eliminate medium-range nuclear
weapons and said the ratified document ``sets vitally important
precedents for future arms control agreements.
   ``We now look for deep cuts in U.S. and Soviet strategic arms,''
the leaders said.
   The Western leaders held a morning and afternoon session on the
second day of the summit, broken up with a luncheon at a downtown
hotel. It was at the luncheon that the officials gave final
approval to the political communique.
   The morning meeting, like the first session on Sunday, ran
overtime, lasting 35 minutes longer than scheduled.
   The morning discussion between Reagan and the other world
leaders focused on progress made in refining the economic
coordination process, including a U.S. proposal to add a commodity
price index to the list of indicators the countries monitor to make
sure they are pursuing complimentary policies, presidential
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said at a briefing.
   The index will include gold as one of about 40 commodities being
monitored, but the United States has insisted that index is not an
effort to return the world to the gold standard which was abandoned
in 1973.
   The United States received good news on one contentious trade
issue while the Toronto summit was going on. Negotiators in Tokyo
announced they had reaced agreement on the issue of opening the
Japanese market to more shipments of American beef and oranges.
   The landmark agreement calls for Japan to lower tariffs on beef
and oranges over the next six years with U.S. officials predicting
it could double the value of U.S. beef exports to the country,
pushing them to more than $1 billion annually.
   The 14th annual economic summit meeting between leaders of the
United States, Japan, West Germany, Britain, France, Italy and
Canada began on Sunday and is scheduled to conclude with a final
economic communique on Tuesday.
   At the opening session, the Western leaders quickly decided to
play down a contentious dispute involving farm subsidies and
approved in principle a debt-relief package for the poorest
countries of the world.
   The leaders pledged in a statement after their first session
Sunday afternoon to continue their close economic cooperation,
which they credited for keeping the world economy out of a
recession following the October stock market collapse.
   ``We all feel we have made real progress in recent years. Our
message is and should be one of confidence and optimism in dealing
with the challenges confronting us,'' the leaders said.
   In an effort to moderate their generally optimistic tone, the
leaders interjected a note of caution in their joint statement,
which was issued by Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney.
   ``There is no room for complacency. Difficult challenges
remain,'' the statement said. ``Our countries must develop further
our economic coordination efforts. Sound policies must be
continued.''
   U.S. Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III echoed the positive
statement today, saying, ``I think there is to some extent an air
of satisfaction, but I must say I don't believe it's an air of
complacency.''
   Baker, interviewed by CBS-TV, said finance ministers had engaged
in an extensive discussion on inflation and that ``the general
consensus (is) that while we must remain vigilant, we think it is
pretty well under control.''
   The U.S. official described the ministers as ``pleased with the
degree of exchange rate stability'' that exists and have found
``the world economy is in pretty good shape.''
   On the agenda today were two formal sessions and a dinner
designed as a brainstorming session on long-range problems. Closing
ceremonies are scheduled for Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
