<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PuertoRico-Bomb     06-20 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico-Bomb,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Killed, Second Man Injured In Bomb Blast in Car</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK GAUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAYAGUEZ, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb blew up in a car Monday and
killed an American who apparently was putting the explosive
together, officials said. A second man was seriously injured,
police and the FBI said.
   The explosion occurred about 1:40 a.m. in the Balboa sector of
Mayaguez, about 100 miles west of San Juan.
   The dead man was identified as Jeff Parker, an American believed
to be a resident of Miami. Injured was Antonio Alfredo Gonzalez
Olmeda, a Cuban also believed to live in Miami.
   Parker's body was found inside the small car. Gonzalez Olmeda
was standing beside the car when the bomb went off, police said.
   Gonzalez Olmeda underwent surgery at the Rio Piedras Medical
Center for serious injuries in the face and upper body.
   Police Capt. Ramon Ortiz, chief of the Criminal Investigations
Corps in the western region of Puerto Rico, said police were
questioning about 25 people in the case.
   Harry B. Brandon, special agent in charge of the San Juan office
of the FBI, said the bureau joined the Puerto Rican Police
Department in the investigation of the explosion and the two men
involved. He refused to give more details.
   Authorities said they didn't know where the bomb was to have
been placed or if Parker and Gonzalez Olmeda were hired in the
United States to plant the bomb in Puerto Rico.
   Police explosives expert Jesus Garcia said fragments of the bomb
were sent to the police laboratory in San Juan for analysis.
   The explosive was not encased in a receptacle, which led him to
conclude Parker was in the process of putting it together when it
exploded in his lap, Garcia said.
   In the trunk of the car, police said they found a briefcase
containing documents indicating the car was rented and airline
tickets for a Monday afternoon flight to Miami. Officials said they
also found an Immigration and Naturalization Service card and a
driver's license, both issued to Gonzalez Olmeda.
   The briefcase also contained a digital remote control detonator,
police said.
   Mayaguez District Attorney Eric Velazquez said charges would be
filed against Gonzalez Olmeda, but he did not specify what he would
be charged with.
   Parker and Gonzalez Olmeda, both about 25 years old, were
staying at Perichi's, a small tourist hotel in the Joyuda sector of
Cabo Rojo, about 45 minutes south of Mayaguez.
   They had registered at Perichi's Friday. Both men spoke Spanish
and, according to hotel employees, said they were lobster fishermen
on vacation.
   Dr. Juan Angel Nazario, director of the Medical Center's
emergency room, said Gonzalez Olmeda may lose one eye and not
regain sight in the other.
</TEXT>
