<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Africa-Talks     06-20 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Africa-Talks,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Praises Egypt For Hosting New Round of Negotiations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Monday welcomed as a
``statesmanlike initiative'' Egypt's offer to host in Cairo this
weekend a new round of negotiations on a regional settlement of the
Angolan and Namibian problems in southern Africa.
   The talks ``involving Namibian (South-West African) independence
and the departure of all foreign forces from Angola and Namibia
will take place in Cairo'' Friday through Sunday, ``and will
continue the effort begun at the May 3-4 meeting in London,'' said
department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley.
   As in London, delegations from South Africa, Angola, Cuba, and
the United States will participate at Cairo, and all have accepted,
she said. The U.S. delegation will be headed by Assistant Secretary
of State Chester A. Crocker.
   ``We greatly appreciate the statesmanlike initiative of the
government of Egypt in hosting this round of negotiations,'' Mrs.
Oakley told reporters. ``Acceptance of the government of Egypt's
invitation by all parties attests to Egypt's stature as a founding
member of the Organization of African Unity and a consistent
supporter of the peaceful resolution of African problems.''
   Mrs. Oakley said the talks already have ``elicited growing
African diplomatic support,'' and they take place ``against the
backdrop of intensified allied and US-Soviet consultations on
southern Africa.''
   Jonas Savimbi, leader of the anti-communist Angolan guerrillas
backed by the United States, will not be represented at Cairo, she
said. The question of how South Africa, which has no diplomatic
relations with Egypt, could participate in talks at Cairo should be
referred to the Egyptian government, she said.
</TEXT>
