<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FloridaEnglish     06-20 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Florida English,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>English Only Opposition Group Goes on the Offensive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A campaign is being launched this week against a
Florida constitutional amendment which would make English the
state's official language.
   English Plus will air radio spots and sponsor speakers around
the state to deliver the message than an English-only law is
discriminatory and could cripple business and tourism in a state
with strong ties to Latin America.
   ``The immediate impact, even if nothing else happens, is to make
us look like a redneck state,'' said Ambler Moss, a committee
member and former ambassador to Panama who now works at the
University of Miami.
   Advocates of the constitutional amendment appear to have
sufficient signatures to put the issue on the ballot. The law,
aimed largely at Florida's growing Spanish-speaking community,
would prohibit state and local governments from using languages
other than English in conducting public business.
   English Plus, composed of community and bussiness leaders,
counters that the law would make it impossible for state and local
government to promote Florida in Latin America, besides sending a
message to foreign businessmen and tourists that they are not
welcome.
   ``The issue goes to the very heart of what Florida is all
about,'' said English Plus chairman Osvald Soto.
   Other English Plus supporters include the Greater Miami Chamber
of Commerce, which has made defeat of the amendment a top priority,
Harvard-educated lawyer Jon Weber, and the Hispanic coalition
Unidos.
   Supporters say the amendment is necessary, and claim it would
even help foreigners by forcing them to learn English.
   Opponents largely agree that immigrants who come to this country
need to learn English, but don't think the amendment would
accomplish that. Mark Gallegos, president-elect of the Hispanic
National Bar Association and a spokesman for several national Latin
interest groups, said supporters are masking their true purpose.
   ``If it passes, not one single person will learn English because
of it,'' he said. ``It's merely a statement of false nationalism.
It's a reflection of underlying bigotry and xenophobia.''
</TEXT>
