<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Nancy     06-20 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Nancy,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nancy Asks Children to Read: `You'll Always Have a Friend'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Nancy Reagan on Monday encouraged
young children to develop a love for books, advising them that
``you'll never be lonely if you read.''
   Mrs. Reagan joined the wives of four other world leaders
attending the annual economic summit of industrialized nations in
making a pitch for reading to 150 children from five schools in
downtown Toronto.
   The children, ranging in age from 8 to 11, listened intently as
Mila Mulroney, wife of Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, read
about a mischievous cat named Josephine who disrupted school one
day.
   Five children who accompanied Mrs. Reagan and the other wives
took turns reading from ``Can You Catch Josephine?'' The book was
written by Stephane Poulin, a 24-year-old author from Montreal,
Canada.
   After finishing the tale, the children shyly asked the wives in
their native language a question.
   Gina Lin, 8, a third-grader at Lord Lansdowne School, asked Mrs.
Reagan what type of books she preferred.
   ``I read every kind of book,'' the first lady told the child.
   ``I read a lot,'' she said. ``My husband reads a lot. Our
children read a lot ever since they were very young. ...''
   ``If you learn to read when you're young,'' Mrs. Reagan
counseled, ``as you get older, you know that you'll never be lonely
if you read. You'll always have a friend there. There's always
something to do.''
   Anna Maria De Mita, wife of Italian Prime Minister Ciriaco De
Mita, explained how she would tell stories to her children in the
morning and evening.
   Her evening stories, she said, were sweet stories that would
leave the children with pleasant dreams.
   Morning stories, she related, were designed to stimulate the
imagination and make the day more interesting.
   Not only children like stories, she said. ``I do too.''
   Hannelore Kohl, wife of West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, told
the children that the story of Hansel and Gretel differed in
English and in German.
   ``Our version is a better one,'' she said, because the wicked
witch is roasted.
   Mrs. Mulroney, fluent in English and French, said, ``Every time
we read a book we can become whomever we like to be. We can become
the heroine or we can become the ogre.''
   John O'Leary, program director at Frontier College and moderator
of the reading, told the wives and children, ``In the midst of all
our busy lives ... we're coming together to sit still for a moment
to focus our attention, to listen together to hear a story.''
   ``Stories,'' he said, ``are wonderful things, wonderful ways of
uniting all of us.''
   Frontier College promotes educational opportunities and literacy
programs.
   The reading took place in a white tent on the harbor along Lake
Ontario. The children and the wives sat on low benches in front of
brightly colored posters promoting books.
   The children received a book and a bright yellow T-shirt that
said, ``Read, Avoid Extinction.'' Several dinosaurs decorated the
shirts.
   Before the wives arrived, he added a touch of humor to the
event. He asked the children, ``Would you rather read a book or
watch TV?''
   The reply, shouted in unison, was: ``Watch TV.''
</TEXT>
