<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Scotus-Catholics     06-20 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Catholics,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Overturns Contempt Citation Against Catholic Church</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday saved the Roman
Catholic Church, at least temporarily, from having to pay $100,000
a day in court fines for withholding documents in a lawsuit by a
group supporting abortion rights.
   The justices, voting 8-1, overturned a contempt citation against
the church stemming from a lawsuit challenging the church's
tax-exempt status.
   The justices sent the case back to the lower courts to determine
whether Abortion Rights Mobilization Inc. has legal standing to sue
the federal government to revoke the church's tax exemption because
of its anti-abortion lobbying.
   The suit by the pro-choice group is against the government, not
the church, and the underlying issue is whether private citizens
have the legal power to challenge a tax exemption granted by the
government.
   Writing for the court Monday, Justice Anthony M. Kennedy said
the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals must determine whether the
federal courts even have the authority to decide the underlying
issue.
   Kennedy said if the 2nd Circuit court decides the federal judge
who issued the contempt holding lacks proper jurisdiction, the
church is under no obligation to provide its records and may not be
held in contempt.
   A ruling that the abortion rights group does not have the power
to sue could kill the suit effectively.
   Lawrence Lader, president of the pro-choice group, said, ``We
feel this is simply delaying going to trial. The gods are not
favoring going to trial.''
   But Lader said he expected the lower courts would permit the
suit to proceed.
   Monsignor Daniel F. Hoye, general secretary of the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops and the U.S. Catholic Conference,
hailed the high court ruling.
   ``The action of the court gives the bishops some measure of
justice and vindicates their action in appealing to the Supreme
Court,'' he said.
   He said he hoped a federal appeals court ``will now reconsider
its earlier ruling and uphold the right of churches and other
tax-exempt organizations to participate in public debate and other
controversial issues free of retaliatory litigation brought by
their political opponents.''
   Beverly LaHaye, head of the conservative Concerned Women for
America, said the high court ruling ``is truly a victory for all
Americans and for the First Amendment in general.''
   She said the decision allows tax-exempt organizations ``to
challenge the legal basis of frivolous lawsuits against them''
without facing stiff fines.
   Abortion Rights Mobilization says in its eight-year-old suit
that the church's tax-exempt status gives it an unfair advantage in
the political battle over abortion rights.
   It said tax breaks for the church violate a provision of the
federal tax code barring any tax-exempt organization from spending
money on political activities.
   The Supreme Court was asked to decide whether the suit against
the government can go forward, not whether the church's tax
exemption should be revoked.
   The 2nd Circuit last year upheld a 1986 ruling by a federal
judge in New York City who found the church in civil contempt for
refusing to supply its records to the pro-choice coalition.
   The judge ordered the church to pay $100,000 a day until it
supplied the documents. The contempt ruling had been put on hold
pending a high court decision.
   The justices ruled Monday that the church, although a witness
rather than one of the opposing sides in the lawsuit, still had the
right to appeal the contempt citation prior to the outcome of the
suit.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall was the lone dissenter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880620-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1931EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-SouthAfrica 380   06-20 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-South Africa, 380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders Urge Clemency For Sharpeville Six</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of the seven-nation economic summit
on Monday said ``all legal options available'' should be used to
secure clemency for six black South Africans who have been
condemned to death.
   In a statement read to reporters by Canadian Foreign Minister
Joe Clark, the seven leaders also said that recent moves by the
white-led government to stop anti-apartheid groups from receiving
funds from foreign sources ``would place severe strain on the
relations each of us has with South Africa.''
   The statement on South Africa, issued separately from a
political communique, also urged an end to the civil war in Angola
and called on South Africa to implement long-standing United
Nations resolutions designed to grant independendce to Nabmibia, or
South-West Africa.
   The South African blacks, known as the Sharpville Six, were
convicted of complicity in the 1984 mob killing in Sharpeville
township of a black town councillor during riots provoked by a rent
increase.
   There has been an international campaign seeking clemency for
the six _ five men and a woman _ who have been sentenced to hang.
President P.W. Botha has rejected a clemency petition.
   The six were not convicted of directly killing the councillor,
but found guilty under the doctrine of common purpose, which held
them responsible because they actively participated in the mob
which killed him.
   The statement omitted any reference to the most contentious
issue, the impositon of sanctions against South Africa by the
wealthy western nations.
   British Prime Minisiter Margaret Thatcher, whose country is a
major trading partner with South Africa, and other European nations
have refused to implement such tough measures.
   Canada, the summit host, which has scant links with South
Africa, has for years beens sharply critical of the British
attitude.
   A British spokesman said, ``We have no problems with this
statement at all.''
   ``We declare our our abhorrence of apartheid, which must be
replaced through a process of genuine national negotiations by a
nonracial democracy,'' said the summit statement.
   The leaders said they also ``express our urgent opinion'' on the
other issues, including the Sharpeville Six.
   ``All legal options available in South Africa should be used to
secure clemency for the Sharpeville Six,'' they said.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
