<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Olympics     06-20 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Olympics,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roh Orders Emergency Government Setup to Ensure Safety of Olympics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo on Monday
ordered all government systems to be turned into an ``emergency
setup'' to help safeguard the Seoul Olympics.
   ``We should make all out efforts to ensure the safety of the
Olympics, and all government systems should be turned into an
emergency setup to that end,'' Roh told senior aides.
   ``The safety of the Seoul Olympics is our paramount national
task and the future of the nation hinges on it,'' he said.
   The president warned that anti-government and anti-South Korea
ideological groups are bent on disrupting the Sept. 17-Oct.2
Olympics.
   Roh did not say what he meant by the ``emergency setup,'' but
aides said it would make government officials work against possible
terrorist attacks on the Olympics.
   The government plans to mobilize 120,000 specially trained
guards to protect the Olympics. The United States also will deploy
Navy and Air Force units around the Korean peninsula.
   North Korea has said it will boycott the Olympics unless it can
be a co-host.
   A record 12,000 athletes from 161 nations, including the Soviet
Union and other communist countries, are expected to compete.
</TEXT>
