<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1936EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NuclearZones     06-20 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Zones,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honecker Suggests East-West Hotline To Avert Possible Crises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German leader Erich Honecker told a nuclear
disarmament conference Monday that Eastern and Western Europe
should establish ways to keep in constant touch to avert possible
military crises, and suggested a hotline.
   Honecker called for ``mechanisms for the peaceful discussion of
crises and for the prevention of military incidents.''
   ``For example, perhaps there could be a hotline between Prague,
Berlin and Bonn,'' Honecker said.
   Delegates from 110 countries are attending the three-day
conference in East Berlin that began Monday.
   Among the delegates are U.S. peace activists, West German
politicians, officials from the Warsaw Pact, Palestine Liberation
Organization leader Yassir Arafat, and Chedli Klibi,
general-secretary of the Arab League.
   Honecker has been a strong proponent of a European nuclear
weapons-free zone, and arranged the conference. He said in his
opening address that such a zone would ``lessen the military
confrontation in Europe.''
   But many NATO leaders including West German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl reject the idea, saying Western Europe would still be
endangered by Warsaw Pact troops outside such a corridor and by
Soviet nuclear forces.
   West Germany's conservative Christian Democratic Union and
Christian Social Union parties, coalition partners in the federal
government, turned down invitations to the conference.
   But invitations were accepted by the Free Democrats, junior
partners in the coalition, and by West Germany's opposition Social
Democrats and Greens parties.
   Piotr Demichev, Soviet Communist Party Politburo candidate and
the Kremlin's representative at the East Berlin meeting, read a
letter from Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev addressed to the
conference.
   Quoting Gorbachev, Demichev said the Soviet Union fully supports
setting up a nuclear-free zone in central Europe.
   ``The Soviet Union is ready ... to give up its status as a
nuclear power as soon as possible,'' Demichev said.
   ``But as long as we have this status, we are ready for radical
reductions and its practical forms. This includes support for
establishing nuclear-free zones,'' Demichev said, reading from
Gorbachev's letter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
