<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChicagoLibrary     06-20 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Library,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Design Chosen For Harold Washington Libary Center</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserFoto CX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city forged ahead in its long-delayed quest
to build a new $140 million central library when a design for the
building was chosen Monday from among five proposed plans.
   ``We're one step closer to the library's completion,'' Mayor
Eugene Sawyer said as officials announced the selection of a design
for the proposed Harold Washington Library Center. ``There's a
light at the end of the tunnel and it's the light of learning.''
   The Sebus group submitted the design selected from the five
teams of architects, developers and builders whose proposals were
considered for the project that city officials have debated since
1976.
   ``Our main concern was building a first-class building within
the historic context,'' said Thomas Beeby, the head architect for
the Sebus group.
   The library's interior will feature international television
programs picked up by satellite, a 400-seat theater and a 2.3
million volume book collection.
   The city's Library Board still must vote on whether to build the
new library.
   The new 700,000-square-foot library would cost $140 million to
build and is scheduled to be completed in 1991.
   The bulk of the central library's collection has been kept in a
warehouse since 1974, when it was moved from a central library
building built in 1897. The building built in 1897 replaced a
library destroyed in the great Chicago fire of 1871, but the
replacement was deemed inadequate within two decades.
   The library will be named for the city's first black mayor.
Washington died late last year of a heart attack.
</TEXT>
