<1ST_LINE>r w AM-KingHonored     06-20 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-King Honored,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Passes Bill To Rename Federal Annex in Atlanta After King</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved legislation Monday to
rename a newly renovated federal building in Atlanta in honor of
Martin Luther King Jr., the civil rights leader who was
assassinated 20 years ago.
   The bill, sponsored by Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., was approved by a
voice vote in the House. It now goes to the Senate, where favorable
action would make the federal annex the first federal building in
the nation to bear King's name.
   Lewis said he does not anticipate any problem in winning Senate
approval. He said he hopes to arrange a ceremony in late summer or
early fall to officially rename the building in honor of King, who
was slain in Memphis, Tenn., in April 1968.
   The annex, which housed a post office before a $10 million
renovation that began three years ago, will be the Atlanta
headquarters for the FBI, which waged a lengthy campaign to
discredit King during the 1960s civil rights movement.
   The FBI is one of several federal agencies scheduled to move
into the annex this month. Between 1,400 and 1,600 federal
employees will be located there when the moves are completed.
   The annex, which was built in the mid-1930s, is located across
from the Richard B. Russell Federal Building near the center of
downtown Atlanta.
</TEXT>
