<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1943EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HaitiReax     06-20 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti Reax,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Haitian Exiles Support Neither Manigat Nor Namphy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Haitians refugees support neither their
homeland's newly deposed president nor his military replacement,
and worry that violence and confusion will only further impoverish
the country, exile leaders said Monday.
   Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy declared himself president Monday, only
hours after his troops invaded the Haitian presidential palace in
Port-au-Prince and took civilian President Leslie Manigat into
custody.
   ``They imposed Manigat on us, they imposed Namphy,'' said the
Rev. Gerard Jean-Juste, head of the Haitian Refugee Center. ``This
is just one more intrigue between hard-core Duvalier supporters.''
   Namphy was president of the three-man junta that ruled Haiti for
two years after dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to exile in
France in February 1986. The junta was disbanded after Manigat was
elected president in January.
   Manigat won his post in a January election that many Haitians
here felt was rigged, and which excluded all major opposition
figures. In the latest crisis Manigat formed an unsuccessful
alliance with Col. Jean-Claude Paul, who is under indictment in
Miami for drug trafficking and also was blamed for the violence
that aborted Haiti's first post-Duvalier presidential election in
November.
   Few in Miami's Haitian community, which may number up to
100,000, feel there is much difference between Manigat and Namphy.
   ``The people are sick and tired of the same names every day,''
said Fred St. Armand on a street in Little Haiti. ``There has to be
somebody new _ something has to be done.''
   Some, however, saw Manigat as the lesser of two evils, and
regret the coup.
   ``The military is messing up everything in Haiti. They have the
money, (but) they they had no patriotism,'' said Viter Juste, a
Haitian exile who lives in Miami. ``It is still better to keep
Manigat.''
   The coup ``means more than ever, the Duvalier regime is getting
back in power,'' Juste said.
   Jean-Juste said he and several other vocal Miami-area opponents
of the Haitian regime are on a death list drawn up by the remnants
of the dreaded tonton macoute, the Duvaliers' secret police. The
list was published in Haiti at the same time the group promised to
overthrow Manigat, he said.
   ``I take it seriously,'' said Jean-Juste. ``But we have many
people supporting us here in Miami.''
   Jean-Juste and many Haitian leaders blame the United States for
supporting the military despite its poor human rights record and
lack of respect for democracy.
   ``The fact is that the United States has armed the Haitian
military for so long, and it was the same military that shot
civilians who were trying to exercise their right to vote,'' said
Roger Biamby of the Haitian-American Community Association of Dade.
   ``The thing to do is to remove those military macoutes from
power so that the Haitian people can go about their business of
building democracy and the economy of the country,'' Biamby said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880620-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1732EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Lyng-Drought     06-20 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lyng-Drought,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agriculture Secretary Says Farmers Face Drought Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought withering crops in parts of the
nation won't mean hunger if it continues, but could mean disaster
for farmers and spiraling costs for consumers, Agriculture
Secretary Richard E. Lyng said Monday.
   Lyng said the worst threat to the agricultural economy is in the
Corn Belt, the Midwestern region where corn and corn-fed livestock
are raised. But problems also are looming for Southern soybean
growers.
   ``Corn is the most important crop in the United States. Soybeans
is second,'' Lyng said after a speech to the Institute of Food
Technologists convention. ``If those are lost who can say what it
will mean, it's never happened before.
   ``It won't mean hunger, not hunger. But the threat is severe.''
   Loss of corn and soybeans would lead farmers to start
liquidating their livestock, Lyng said, resulting in an immediate
decline in beef prices followed by a sharp rise.
   The effect on beef prices could last for years, he said.
   The drought could be devastating for farmers who made it through
a series of economic setbacks in recent years.
   ``There's no question things had been improving, but there were
still some difficulties,'' he said. ``Yes, it could be the telling
blow for some farmers.''
   ``We've done all we can at this time to help farmers with the
situation. Our next step will have to be to help those who have no
crops because of the drought,'' Lyng said. ``There will have to be
disaster declarations in some areas so we can get things like low
cost loans to people who need them.''
   On another matter, Lyng praised a trade agreement signed today
in Tokyo that will ease some Japanese restrictive quotas on
agricultural imports.
   ``Japan's beef imports will expand by $1 billion. Citrus imports
will double,'' Lyng said. ``The potential for the United States to
increase its exports to Japan is tremendous.''
</TEXT>
