<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1956EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--TobaccoOutlook     06-20 0132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Tobacco Outlook,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cigarette Export Boom Cutting Stockpiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boom in cigarette exports is putting heavier
demands of U.S. tobacco supplies, a report by the Agriculture
Department said Monday.
   Total disappearance of tobacco in 1987-88 probably will be up
about 3 percent from last season, the department's Economic
Research Service said in its new outlook analysis.
   As a result, stockpiles of unmanufactured tobacco leaf may be
down 13 percent from last year's 3.33 billion pounds. The new
marketing year for flue-cured begins July 1, while the year for
burley and other kinds will start Oct. 1.
   ``Domestic leaf disappearance is increasing largely because U.S.
cigarette production is rising,'' the report said. ``This
production increase is the result of big gains in cigarette
exports; domestic cigarette consumption is declining.''
</TEXT>
