<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1810EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Science     06-20 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Science,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan, Takeshita Sign Agreement To Open Japanese Labs To US
Researchers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita of Japan signed an agreement Monday to open up Japanese
laboratories to American researchers and limit publication of joint
research on technology with possible military uses.
   At a ceremony in the Royal York Hotel, where he is staying
during the seven-nation economic summit, Reagan reviewed the
relationship between the United States and Japan in science and
technology and said, ``Our hope is to strengthen the relationship
for peaceful purposes.''
   Takeshita said the agreement ``lifts our sights to the 1990s and
beyond.''
   ``The agreement is not exclusive,'' Takeshita said. ``It is open
to be shared by all the world.''
   The agreement was approved by the Japanese Cabinet on June 17
following 10 months of negotiations. Since it is an agreement, not
a treaty, it is not subject to ratification by the Senate.
   The five-year agreement replaces a pact that was temporarily
renewed five times since it expired in 1985.
   Because private industry accounts for 80 percent of the funds
Japan invests in research and development, compared with 50 percent
in the United States, the U.S. government has been pressing for
more access to the private laboratories where the bulk of Japanese
research takes place.
   Japan's agreement to restrict publication of sensitive material
on jointly developed technology was the outcome of criticism that
the Japanese government has been too lax in controlling exports of
sensitive technology to communist nations.
   In one case last year, U.S. officials disclosed that Toshiba
Machine Co., a subsdiary of the Japanese electronics maker Toshiba
Corp., had exported submarine-silencing equipment to the Soviet
Union.
   The pact is scheduled to take effect at the end of this month,
when the current three-month extension expires.
   Both countries also agree to protect intellectual rights and
determine rights to patents arising from joint research before the
start of laboratory work. The agreement also calls for the Tokyo
government to increase finding for scientists and engineers coming
to Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
