<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MultipleKillings     06-20 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Killings,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Stays Execution of Simmons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ The state Supreme Court on Monday postponed
the execution of murderer R. Gene Simmons, who had pleaded after
his sentencing last month that there be no such delays.
   The action came one week before Simmons, 47, was scheduled to
receive a lethal injection for killing two people in Russellville
during a 40-minute shooting rampage that left four others wounded
on Dec. 28. It would have been the state's first execution since
1964.
   When he was sentenced on May 12, Simmons told Judge John S.
Patterson he was ready to die, saying, ``Let the torture and
suffering in me end.''
   He apparently hoped to avoid a July 18 trial for the deaths of
14 relatives, whose bodies were found on his isolated property in
the Ozark Mountains north of Dover.
   The 6-1 ruling Monday improves the possibility that Simmons will
be tried in July because, even if the state Supreme Court lets his
sentence stand, Gov. Bill Clinton would set the next execution date
and that process usually takes about 40 days.
   In the ruling, the state's highest court said it would look into
issues raised by would-be intervenor Louis J. Franz of Star City.
   Franz, a minister, heads Arkansas Churches for Life, which
opposes the death penalty.
   ``I am naturally pleased, because I think it gives us an
opportunity to look further into the matter, which has been our
hope,'' Franz said in Star City.
   Marvin Evans, assistant warden at the maxium security unit of
the state prison, said Simmons had no particular reaction when
informed of the court's decision. When asked if he wanted to make a
statement for the media, Simmons declined, Evans said.
   The court said it wants to explore these questions:
   _Whether Franz has a right to get into the case as a
representative of Simmons' interests, as Franz has filed to do.
   _Whether the state Supreme Court should have mandatory review of
death cases or, if there is no mandatory review, whether the court
should review a death case waiver of appeal and whether the waiver
was made knowingly and intelligently.
   The Supreme Court order said Simmons, the state, and Franz may
appear June 28 for oral arguments.
   In a dissenting opinion, Associate Justice John Purtle said
there is no requirement or procedure for mandatory review of all
death sentences. Simmons had the right to waive the appeal,
provided he did so knowingly and intelligently, Purtle wrote.
   The Franklin County Circuit Court in Ozark, where Simmons was
convicted, held two hearings in which Simmons' competency to waive
his appeal was considered.
   Simmons was convicted May 12 of killing Kathy Kendrick, 24, and
James Chaffin, 33, at separate Russellville businesses. Simmons
surrendered after telling a bystander he had gotten everyone who
had hurt him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
