<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Haiti 3rdLd-Writethru a0759 06-20 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Haiti, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0759,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Condemns Coup D'Etat in Haiti</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 4 grafs with comment by former ambassador</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States condemned the military
takeover in Haiti on Monday and called it a ``serious blow to hopes
for democracy.''
   After reviewing the situation for several hours, the State
Department issued a statement through spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley,
saying, ``It is now clear that a military coup d'etat has taken
place in Haiti.
   ``The United States government strongly condemns this serious
blow to hopes for democracy in that troubled land.''
   Mrs. Oakley also noted that Col. Jean-Claude Paul, a Haitian
army officer under indictment on drug charges in Miami, appeared on
the platform with Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, when Namphy announced the
civilian government led by president Leslie Manigat had been
deposed and declared himself president.
   Manigat, who had taken office Feb. 7, arrived with his family in
the Dominican Republic on Monday, according to military sources
there.
   Mrs. Oakley said the United States had no advance knowledge of
the coup, would continue to press for democracy in Haiti and would
consult with governments in the region on future steps.
   ``We're simply looking at the situation and will decide what to
do,'' she said.
   Since the removal of Haitian dictator Jean Claude Duvalier in
February 1986, the United States has sought the creation of free
government institutions and, as Mrs. Oakley put it, ``devoted
considerable resources to the hoped-for transition to democracy.''
   Progress toward democracy has been a condition for restoration
of $60 million in direct U.S. aid, which was suspended last autumn
during an election campaign marred by massive violence. The aid
remained withheld after the United States said Manigat's election
in January was engineered by military authorities.
   Mrs. Oakley said the United States still sought strict
observance of human rights in Haiti, economic progress ``to
alleviate the suffering of the Haitian people,'' cooperation on the
problem of narcotics trafficking and ``most important, the
establishment of credible transition to a democratic government led
by civilians in Haiti.''
   Meanwhile, the United States issued an advisory to would-be
travelers to Haiti to defer non-essential trips to the country
``due to the changing political situation and resulting security
uncertainties.''
   Mrs. Oakley said there were no reports of American in Haiti
being harmed during the coup.
   In Toronto, Canada, where President Reagan was attending the
economic summit of major industrialized democracies, White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said, ``We do not know exactly what is
happening or who was behind this coup attempt.''
   He said, ``Our information is sketchy and we are still trying to
make sure we know all the facts and details.'' He said the coup did
not come up in the discussions between Reagan and the other leaders.
   Reagan, asked by a reporter what was going on in Haiti, said,
``We are assessing that right now.''
   Ernest Preeg, U.S. ambassador to Haiti from 1981 to 1983, said
the events in Haiti reminded him of the situation in Panama, where
military leader Manuel Antonio Noriega has resisted U.S. pressure
to give way to civilian rule.
   ``I think one lesson that we should have learned is that even
with relatively small, weak, poor countries such as Haiti, the
United States is not able just to flex its financial _ or whatever
_ muscle and make things happen in a certain way,'' Preeg said on
Cable News Network.
   The local power structure in Haiti is willing to buck U.S.
pressure, he said.
   ``I think that's a factor that has some relationship, some
bearing, with recent experience with Panama and its something that
will be a factor in the months ahead in Haiti,'' Preeg said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880620-0164 </DOCNO>
