<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,0732</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Farmer Killed; Police Accuse Palestinians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with two soldiers injured by
firebomb; raises injury toll in gas explosion to at least 24;
Israeli farmers block roads to Arab villages; new Shamir quote.
EDITS to TRIM. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli farmer was found stabbed and
bludgeoned to death in his vineyard Monday. Police blamed
Palestinian activists and rounded up 20 Arab suspects.
   ``This is very serious,'' Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, head of
the right-wing Likud bloc, said on Israel television. ``If it is
determined that the murder was motivated by the (Arab) struggle
against Israel, we will respond appropriately.''
   Farmer Eli Cohen was the fourth Israeli to be killed in the Arab
uprising that began Dec. 8. At least 210 Palestinians have died.
   Recent Palestinian-Israeli violence has occurred primarily in
Jerusalem or in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, where 1.5
million Arabs live under Israeli military rule. It has rarely
spilled over into Israeli towns.
   Two soldiers were injured when assailants threw a firebomb at an
army jeep patrolling Gaza City, an army official said. Several
Arabs were detained, he said.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, soldiers shot an 18-year-old
Arab in the leg during a clash with stone-throwing protesters, Al
Ittihad hospital officials said.
   A dozen soldiers then raided the hospital looking for
protesters, dragged three Arab youths outside, then released them
after an interrogation, said the hospital officials, speaking on
condition their names not be used. The military said it had no
report of the demonstration or the raid.
   The slaying of Cohen was particularily shocking to many Israelis
because it occurred in a small, isolated farming community inside
Israel.
   Angry residents of the farming community where Cohen lived on
Monday night blocked several roads leading from the neighboring
Arab villages to the so-called Green Line dividing Israel and the
West Bank, Israel radio said. The report did not elaborate.
   Cohen, a 33-year-old father of two whose wife was pregnant, was
stabbed in the back and beaten, apparently with an iron rod, and
his head was crushed, police said.
   His body was found near the Shekef Moshav, or collective farm,
where 33 families live. The community is near the West Bank and
about 25 miles south of Jerusalem. It borders three Arab villages.
   ``We find ourselves among a hostile population of 40,000 Arabs .
.. 40,000 potential murderers,'' said David Ulinsky, the security
officer at the farm, speaking on Israel radio.
   Cohen left home Sunday evening on a tractor to spray insecticide
on his vineyard 10 miles away, said Etti Elinsky, a farm
spokeswoman. He never returned.
   His body was found Monday morning by another farmer. Police
quickly sealed off the neighboring Arab villages and placed two of
them under curfew.
   Also Monday, Israeli soldiers welded shut the doors of a
Palestinian charitable organization, the El Bireh-based Family
Welfare Center, and claimed it was being used to ``brainwash''
children.
   The center's director, Samiha Khalil, told reporters her
organization only helped girls and women in distress.
   The army also closed four Arab schools, bringing to nine the
number of schools shut in the last three days.
   Dozens of Palestinians staged a sit-in at the Red Cross building
in the Gaza Strip, in solidarity with Arab children involved in the
uprising. The two-hour protest was in keeping with the latest
underground leaflet, which called for Monday to be a day to honor
``Palestinian Children Martyrs.''
   The Association for Civil Rights in Israel said the army has
resorted to jailing thousands of Palestinians without trial simply
to alleviate the overload of cases in military courts.
   The organization also said military police were ``lethargic'' in
investigating allegations of violence by soldiers against Arabs.
   An army spokesman said jailing without trial was only used in
cases where a public trial would endanger Israeli intelligence. He
denied military police were slow to probe brutality allegations and
said 350 such cases had been investigated to date.
   An explosion caused by a gas leak at a pizzeria in the seaside
resort of Herzliya near Tel Aviv, injured at least 24 Israelis. Tel
Aviv Police Chief Yigal Marcus said police were investigating
whether someone had intentionally caused the leak.
</TEXT>
