<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hot And Dry On Plains, Only Scattered Rain Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Dry weather with record high temperatures dominated the Plains
and Midwest on Monday with showers and thunderstorms mostly
confined to the edges of the nation.
   Record highs included 92 at Alpena, Mich.; 101 at Billings,
Mont.; 95 at Cleveland, tie; 104 at Concordia, Kan.; 98 at Des
Moines, Iowa, tie; 100 at Dickenson, N.D.; 104 at Dodge City, Kan.;
99 at Dubuque, Iowa; 97 at Havre, Mont.; 99 at Kansas City, Mo.;
100 at Lamoni, Iowa, tie; 98 at Madison, Wis.; 100 at Moline, Ill.;
101 at Rapid City, S.D.; 100 at Rockford, Ill., tie; 101 at Sioux
Falls, S.D.; 105 at Williston, N.D.; and 93 at Youngstown, Ohio.
   Showers and thunderstorms produced around a tenth of an inch of
rain as they sagged from southwestern Lower Michigan into dry
northern Indiana during the morning before dissipating in the
afternoon. The storms brought only about a tenth of an inch of rain
to an area that is 5 to 7 inches below normal in rainfall so far
this year. Kankakee, Ill., reported 0.69 of an inch.
   Elsewhere, thunderstorms developed along the Gulf of Mexico
coast and eastern Florida, and over parts of the central
Appalachians.
   Scattered thunderstorms moved into northern sections of New
England with a possibility of severe weather.
   Other thunderstorms were over parts of the central valleys of
California.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Crescent City, Calif., to 107 at Hill City, Kan. The low
for the day was 40 at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Tuesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the central and eastern Gulf Coast across the Florida
Peninsula and across the upper Great Lakes. Showers and
thunderstorms will become numerous in the afternoon from southern
Idaho through western parts of Utah into northern Arizona.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted along the California coast and
northern Maine; in the 90s from southwestern sections of Washington
state through central Oregon into the valleys of California;
between 95 and 105 from the central Rockies through the northern
and central Plains into the middle Mississippi and lower Ohio
valleys; between 100 and 110 over the desert Southwest; and in the
80s or low 90s across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
