<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Martin     06-20 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Martin,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>``The Mother Of Gospel Music'' Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sallie Martin, who was known as ``the mother of
gospel music,'' has died at age 92.
   Mrs. Martin died Saturday in Hyde Park Community Hospital, 59
years after making her first record.
   ``Her greatest contributions were her energy and love for the
music. She made gospel music, that's all there is to it,'' said
Otis Clay, a gospel and rhythm and blues artist who met Mrs. Martin
in the 1960s.
   Clay was one of the singers and musicians backstage at the
Chicago Music Festival held here over the weekend who remembered
Mrs. Martin and said they owe their popularity to her booming
soprano voice and lifelong dedication to gospel music.
   ``Even when she gave her last concert in April, she was as
dedicated as the day she started,'' said Gregory Cooper,
keyboardist and her personal assistant for the last four years.
``She was disciplined, but a fire burned within her.''
   ``She was the mother of gospel and we are her children,'' added
Billie Barrett, of the Barrett Sisters. ``In heaven today, I'm sure
she is rejoicing, and I look forward to meeting her in the Great
Beyond.''
   Mrs. Martin was born in Pittfield, Ga., and started singing in a
Baptist church.
   ``We didn't have no soloists. We would all sing together, or if
you felt like you were going to testify, you might start out with a
song yourself,'' Mrs. Martin had said of her early years.
   Her search for work brought her to Cleveland and then Chicago,
where in 1932 she teamed up with the Rev. Thomas M. Dorsey.
   Together they criss-crossed the South. Mrs. Martin sang Dorsey's
syncopated hymns at churches and meeting halls along the way. After
performances, she sold sheet music for 10 cents a copy.
   Mrs. Martin was featured in the documentary film ``Say Amen,
Somebody.''
   ``Sallie Martin was a gifted singer. She was a pioneer. Her
death is a great loss. We will miss her. The world will miss her,''
gospel singer Albertina Walker said.
</TEXT>
