<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Glance     06-20 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Glance,0324</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits a0783 to fix cycle designator.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Haiti, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on Haiti:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE LAND _ Haiti covers 10,700 square miles on the Caribbean
island of Hispaniola, slightly more than Maryland. Most of the land
is arid and mountainous, deeply eroded and treeless, allowing
little more than subsistence farming. The Spanish-speaking
Dominican Republic occupies the eastern, more fertile, two-thirds
of the island.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE PEOPLE _ Ninety-five percent are descendants of African
slaves brought to the New World to cut sugar cane. A slave revolt
led by Francois Dominique Toussaint L'Ouverture led to independence
from France on Jan. 1, 1804, as the first black republic in history.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ECONOMY _ Haiti is the Western Hemisphere's poorest country.
Life expectancy is 54 years, per capita annual income is $379 and
85 percent of Haitians live in poverty. Only 13 percent have access
to ptable water. Thousands, including about 15,000 abandoned or
orphaned children, live and sleep in the streets of the capital,
Port-au-Prince, without shelter, sanitary facilities or other
necessities. A privileged class of about 60,000 has nearly half the
national wealth.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ Haiti controled all Hispaniola in 1818-1839. U.S.
troops occupied the country from 1915 to 1934 after a long period
of instability. A 10-year boom after World War II brought foreign
investment, tourism and public works on a grand scale but little
was done to help the poor. More turmoil culminated in 1957 with the
election of Francois Duvalier, a doctor who declared himself
president-for-life in 1964. ``Papa Doc'' died in 1971 and was
succeeded by his 19-year-old son, Jean-Claude. The Duvalier family
amassed an immense fortune and created the notorious Tonton
Macoutes, a private militia that throttled political opposition by
arresting, torturing and killing at will. Jean-Claude fled in
February 1986 after food riots grew into nationwide protests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
