<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0769,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Leaders Pledge Better Cooperation To Fight Drugs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 6th graf bgng: France ultimately ...
to UPDATE with Reagan quote. Picks up 7th graf pvs bgng: The
statement ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the seven largest industrial
democracies pledged Monday to step up a worldwide fight against the
illegal drug trade, saying narcotics abuse ``poses grave risks'' to
society.
   ``The complexity of the problem requires international
cooperation, in particular to trace, freeze and confiscate the
proceeds of drug traffickers, and to curb money laundering,'' they
said in a statement issued at the midpoint of the three-day summit.
   But a U.S. proposal to set up a task force of the seven nations
to oversee the coordination effort was blocked by France, which
said it did not want to see the annual seven-nation summit develop
into a year-round effort to run world affairs.
   ``The seven countries don't have the right to direct the rest of
the world,'' said French spokesman Hubert Vedrine.
   He said France would support a task force involving ``all
affected countries.''
   France ultimately abstained on a watered-down sentence
supporting the U.S. idea for a task force, Vedrine said, but backed
the rest of the summit statement on cooperation to fight drugs.
   Later, at a group photo with his summit colleagues, President
Reagan said he believed the task force can help us ``win the war
against drugs and we're going to win.''
   The statement said that ``the illegal use of drugs and illicit
trafficking in them poses grave risks to the peoples of summit
countries as well as the peoples of source and transit countries.''
   President Reagan fought hard to include the drug issue in the
statement dealing with political issues, said Rozanne Ridgway, the
assistant U.S. secretary of state.
   ``This is the first time that we have an initiative that tries
to address as a complex this set of concerns about production,
financing and trafficking of the drug trade,'' she said.
   No date has been set for the task force to start its work, and
which countries will be members has not been determined, she said.
   She said its activities might include improving
intelligence-sharing, increasing funds for anti-drug organizations
and working for better cooperation between central banks of the
various countries.
</TEXT>
