<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TimberStrike     06-20 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Timber Strike,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Spreads To Boise Cascade Plants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB BAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Northwest woodworkers' strike spread
to 12 Boise Cascade Corp. plants Monday, bringing the total of
striking workers to about 6,600 in four states.
   Woodworkers also set up pickets at a Willamette Industries Inc.
paper mill in Albany, Ore., where 300 paperworkers refused to cross
the lines.
   Two woodworkers' unions _ the International Woodworkers of
America-U.S. and the Western Council of Industrial Workers _ are
attempting to regain wages and benefits cut in the last round of
contract negotiations two years ago, when the industry was in a
recession.
   The unions have reached a two-year contract agreement with
Bohemia Inc. of Eugene, Ore., for a 5 percent wage hike the first
year and a 4 percent increase the second. Union leaders want the
agreement to serve as a standard for other companies, but the other
companies have balked.
   Boise Cascade spokesman Doug Bartels said his company would not
be competitive if it agreed to the Bohemia terms.
   The Boise Cascade walkout affected 2,078 workers at 13 plants in
Oregon, Washington and Idaho, Bartels said. The walkout against the
company began at a mill in Independence, Ore., Sunday and moved to
the other facilities Monday.
   The woodworkers' strike began June 6 against Willamette
Industries, DAW Forest Products Co. and Champion International
Corp. operations in Oregon, Washington and Montana. The smaller
Lakeview Lumber Co. also was struck last week after its owners
imposed wage cuts.
   Bill Hubbell, president of the International Woodworkers of
America-U.S., said chances are good the walkout will continue to
grow.
   ``Undoubtedly as bargaining falls apart with the various
companies, there's a good possibility that it will go beyond what
it is now,'' he said.
   The bargaining council representing both unions has negotiations
scheduled this week with representatives of Simpson Timber Co. and
next week with the biggest of the region's wood products companies,
Weyerhaeuser Co.
   Simpson has about 2,000 workers and Weyerhaeuser about 6,000.
   Hubbell said the unions realized that concessions were necessary
during the last talks. ``But in light of record profit years the
last two years,'' he added, ``we felt certain there would be some
social justice at the table with these employers but so far we
haven't seen any.''
   Contracts have expired at only two Boise Cascade plants, in
Independence and St. Helens, Ore., but pickets were set up at all
13 of the company's plants that have union representation in the
Northwest. The workers were not crossing the lines, Bartels said.
   ``I guess by the legal definition of it they are recognizing
sympathy pickets,'' he said. ``But the reality is the plants are
shut down.''
   The pickets shut down plants in La Grande, Elgin and Joseph in
Oregon; Yakima, Goldendale and Kettle Falls in Washington; and
Emmett, Cascade and Council in Idaho. Some of the sites have more
than one manufacturing plant, Bartels said.
   The company has eight non-union plants in the Northwest
unaffected by the walkout, Bartels said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
