<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Space Telescope,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Conducts Tests on Space Telescope</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA's $1.5 billion space telescope,
languishing in a ``clean room'' in California, is being exercised
around the clock for 5{ days this week in what the space agency
calls ``one of the most comprehensive tests ever undertaken.''
   The telescope, which will enable astronomers to photograph stars
seven times farther away than now, is scheduled to ride into space
aboard the shuttle next June 1. In the meantime, it is at the
Lockheed plant in Sunnyvale, Calif. The test will be conducted from
the Goddard Space Flight Center in Maryland.
   ``This is the first time we have operated the spacecraft for
this period of time and at this level of sophistication,'' said
Goddard's Ron Felice, the deputy project manager of flight
operations for the telescope.
