<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     06-20 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebel Leader Confirms Secret Talks With U.N. Official</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One name for Najib is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan rebel field commander said
Monday he met with a senior U.N. official to ask that aid be
withheld from the communist government in Afghanistan.
   Abdul Haq, a Moslem rebel commander in the Kabul region, told
The Associated Press that he met Sunday and Monday in New York with
Giandomenico Picco, a U.N. undersecretary-general who was involved
in mediating accords for a Soviet troop withdrawal and Afghan
reconstruction.
   U.N. officials on Monday refused to confirm or deny the meeting.
The United States has demanded that no U.N. aid be distributed
through the communist government of Afghan President Najib.
   Speaking in English at his midtown Manhattan hotel, Haq said he
would meet agaion with Picco on Tuesday.
   U.N. officials have met with Afghan rebel political leaders
based in Pakistan, but this was believed to be the first official
U.N. contact with a military field commander.
   The Moslem rebels, supported by the United States, continue to
fight to topple the Afghan government and establish an Islamic
republic. The rebels were not part of the accord signed in Geneva
on April 14 calling for Soviet withdrawal and Afghan reconstruction.
   Haq is a member of the Hezb-i-Islamic-Khalis party, one of the
more moderate Islamic groups fighting the Afghan government.
   He said he has discussed with Picco two issues: financial
support for Afghan reconstruction and political solutions to the
civil war, which began in 1979.
   ``I told him that while the Soviets were in the country and the
(Najib) regime in power, it is possible that they would get some of
that money,'' Haq said. ``If they use that to build a road or
bridges for military purposes, in killing some of my people, the
United Nations is responsible.
   ``Also, this money is coming for the return of refugees. Who are
the refugees? They are my people, not Najib's,'' said Haq.
   About 5 million Afghan refugees are now living in Pakistan and
Iran.
   On the subject of political solutions, Haq said he told Picco
that ``the Soviets must go.''
   The Najib government has said Soviet military advisers will
remain in Afghanistan after the 103,000 Red Army soldiers return
home.
   Soviet troops, which intervened in 1979 at the invitation of the
government, began their withdrawal from Afghanistan on May 15, in
accordance with the Geneva pact. They are scheduled to complete the
pullout by Feb. 15, 1989.
   ``The U.N. is in favor of a broad-based government, so to have a
broad-based government Najib must step down,'' he added.
   Haq said he believed that Picco was inclined to agree with his
views that Najib had no place in a representative Afghan government.
   Pakistan and Afghanistan signed the Geneva accord, with the
Soviet Union and United States serving as guarantors. The accord
calls for the United Nations to supervise the Soviet pullout and to
coordinate relief and reconstruction efforts and refugee
resettlement.
   The coordinator for the U.N. Humanitarian and Economic
Assistance effort in Afghanistan, Sadruddin Aga Khan, has said the
United Nations will ask the world community for $1.17 billion for
an 18-month campaign to resettle Afghan refugees and see them
through two harvests.
   He said $25 million already had been pledged.
   A three-year recovery program would follow, Sadruddin said,
which was estimated to cost $839.6 million.
   Sadruddin has said relief aid will be distributed through
whatever authority controls a region in Afghanistan, but has not
specified the central government in Kabul, the capital, suggesting
the United Nations may work with local and regional governments and
religious authorities.
   Richard Williams, a United States delegate to the U.N., said
during a pledge review meeting on June 14: ``The aid should not
come under the control of the illegitimate Kabul regime, which
lacks credibility with the refugees and controls little territory.''
</TEXT>
