<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0684 06-20 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0684,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Says Official Vote Estimates Too High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs `In the...' with 1 graf to CORRECT turnout
estimate to less than 23 percent, sted less than 22 percent.
INSERTS 1 graf after 8th pvs `Urban said...' to UPDATE with quote
from Sejm deputy. PICKS up 9th pvs bgng, Onyszkiewicz said that ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government figures saying 56 percent of
the electorate voted Sunday for local and provincial People's
Councils were dramatically inflated, supporters of the Solidarity
trade union said Monday.
   The turnout figure appeared lower based on spot checks of
polling places, said Solidarity national spokesman Janusz
Onyszkiewicz.
   In the southwestern city of Wroclaw, a Solidarity-organized
monitoring operation that watched nearly 300 polling stations
concluded that less than 23 percent of voters took part, according
to opposition spokeswoman Maria Pinior.
   Even according to the official figure of 56 percent turnout
nationwide, it was the lowest turnout for any election in Poland
since the communists took power after World War II.
   The previously lowest-attended election _ a nationwide
referendum on political and economic reforms _ drew 67.3 percent of
the 26 million eligible voters last year.
   The last council elections, in 1984, attracted 75 percent of the
electorate, according to official estimates, and 56 percent,
according to the outlawed union.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said before the voting that the
government would be satisfied if a majority of eligible voters
participated. Voting would not be interpreted as an indicator of
support for the government.
   Urban said poor economic conditions discouraged some people from
attending, but that the elections were a breakthrough for Poland:
the first time candidates actively campaigned for votes and the
first time since 1947 that some races were contested between people
of different parties, in about 4 percent of districts.
   Mikolaj Kozakiewicz, a deputy in the Sejm, or parliament, told
Polish TV the turnout was not a victory for the government or the
oppositon but a sign of ``social apathy, which is our most serious
disease.''
   Onyszkiewicz said that although the government attempt to
portray the election as a ``turning point, this obviously failed.
No one thinks these elections have any significance.''
   Solidarity had called for a national boycott of the vote, but it
did not attempt to monitor voting nationwide, said Onyszkiewicz.
However, some local leaderships of Solidarity did undertake vote
counts, he said.
   Solidarity activists estimated turnout in the Baltic port city
of Gdansk at 28 percent to 30 percent, and in some Warsaw districts
the numbers were around 30 percent, said Jacek Kuron, a senior
Solidarity adviser in Warsaw.
   Lech Walesa, chairman of the outlawed union, planned no comment
on the turnout, according to aide Bogdan Olszewski.
   ``If he announced (his figures) he would be a sadist,'' said
Olszewski. ``It would look like he was torturing the government.''
   Onyszkiewicz said officials' inflation of turnout figures was
``not the result of central planning, but the fact that every local
functionary is responsible for good turnout in his area. So it is
in his interest to correct the figures in a certain way.''
   He said the union's call for a boycott may have kept some people
from voting, but also that ``obviously the mechanical ritual of
voting is gradually being reduced. The barrier of fear is crumbling
down.''
   Until the 1970s, Poland reported voting turnouts of around 99
percent, and people who did not vote feared official sanctions.
</TEXT>
