<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Britain     06-20 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Britain,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Advises Britain To Shun Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high Iranian official meeting with a
British parliamentary delegation in Tehran on Monday said the
British government should avoid linking itself with U.S. policies
toward Iran.
   Mahdi Karrubi, deputy speaker of the Iranian Parliament, told
the four British lawmakers their country should ``shun complicity
with Washington's hostile policies against the Islamic
Revolution,'' the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, said Britain's condemnation of
Iraq's use of chemical weapons was a ``positive'' sign.
   ``This act can influence the outlook of the Islamic Republic
officials and people towards Britain,'' the report quoted Karrubi
as saying.
   The four arrived in the capital on Monday, the agency reported,
on a private trip arranged by Archbishop of Canterbury Robert
Runcie. The visit was privately arranged by the Church of England
at the invitation of the Iranian government, Runcie said last week.
   In a two-paragraph report, the agency said the British
parliamentarians were scheduled to hold talks with senior Iranian
officials during their three-day visit.
   It gave no details. But the British legislators said before they
left London they hoped to see Iran's Parliament speaker, Hashemi
Rafsanjani, the most powerful figure in the country after
revolutionary patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   The lawkmakers cautioned before they left London against raising
hopes their visit could lead to the release of British hostages
held by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem factions in Lebanon.
   Three Britons are among 18 foreign hostages held in Lebanon.
Among the nine Americans in the group is Terry Anderson, the
longest held hostage. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for
The Associated Press, was abducted in Beirut on March 16, 1985.
   Britain's relations with Tehran have been strained since
Khomeini's 1979 Islamic revolution toppled the late Shah Mohammed
Reza Pahlavi.
   The Iranians have long considered Britain to rank second to
``the Great Satan,'' as Iran usually calls the United States, as a
hostile Western nation.
   The British delegation includes Cyril Townsend and Robert Hicks
of Britain's governing Conservative Party; Thomas Clarke of the
opposition Labor Party and Lord Tordoff of the liberal Social
Democrats.
</TEXT>
