<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 2140EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Violence     06-20 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Violence,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Leftist Rebels Kill 11 Peasants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavily armed police searching for leftist
guerrillas blocked major highways leading into the capital before
dawn Monday and arrested more than 1,300 suspects after scattered
bomb attacks, officials said.
   In the highlands, guerrillas of the Maoist Shining Path movement
killed 11 peasants and wounded two, police said.
   The arrests in Lima were aimed at blunting rebel attacks
commemorating the second anniversary of prison riots that left
hundreds of guerrilla inmates dead, officials said.
   In the southern Andes Mountains, stronghold of the Shining Path,
a column of rebels disguised in military uniforms seized the
village of Cuticsa. The rebels accused villagers of being
government collaborators and killed 11 peasants and wounded two,
police said.
   The attack on Cuticsa, 180 miles southeast of Lima, occurred at
sunset Friday, but authorities did not learn of it until Monday
because the village is isolated, police said.
   The massive interception of traffic in Lima came hours after
rebels bombed police stations and a municipal headquarters Sunday
night in attacks that coincided with the anniversary of the prison
killings.
   Police erected roadblocks on major avenues late Sunday night and
early Monday, stopped buses and private cars and arrested anyone
who did not have proper identification papers, officials said.
   A 15-year-old boy was injured in the legs Sunday night when he
tried to put out a burning stick of dynamite that was left near a
suburban Lima police station, police said. Minor damage but no
injuries were reported in the other bombings.
   The Shining Path, a dogmatic rebel group, has been fighting
since 1980 to overthrow Peru's elected government and install a
peasant and worked state based on the ideas of China's Mao
Tse-tung. More than 10,000 people have died in the violence.
   On June 19, 1986 security forces killed more than 250 guerrilla
inmates during prison riots. The government has admitted that at
least 100 of the prisoners were executed after surrendering.
   The Shining Path declared June 19 the ``Day of Heroism'' and
vowed to seek vengeance for the prison deaths.
</TEXT>
