<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FoxNetwork     06-20 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fox Network,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rupert Murdoch Says He's in Network Business For Long Haul</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Steve Fox, 8th graf, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rupert Murdoch said Monday he is confident he
will successfully establish Fox Broadcasting Co. as a fourth TV
network and has ``every intention of continuing this investment for
an indefinite period.''
   Murdoch, chief executive of Fox's parent News Corp., said the
fledgling network is ``making pleasant progress, particularly on
Sunday nights where its share of audience is growing every week.''
   He responded to a report in Investor's Daily last week in which
Richard Sarazen, finance director of News Corp., was quoted as
saying the network would be shut down if results didn't improve
dramatically in the next six months.
   Fox Chairman Barry Diller said Sarazen was quoted out of context
after responding to a question about the worst-case scenario for
Fox.
   ``If somebody asks you what if it rains, that's one thing,''
Diller said. ``But if they ask you what if it rains every day for
the next 10 years, you have a different scenario.''
   Steve Fox, president and editor of Investor's Daily, said: ``I
think this is much ado about nothing. They're not saying that we
quoted Mr. Sarazen incorrectly, only that it's out of context. I
don't think it comes as a surprise that any company losing $80
million a year cannot go on indefinitely.''
   Because no one from Fox had called ``to say the story is wrong
we have no reason to change our story,'' he said.
   Sarazen said at a meeting of security analysts in New York
Thursday that Fox Broadcasting had lost $80 million last year,
which is $30 milllion more than it had anticipated losing.
Investor's Daily quoted him as saying, ``If it doesn't improve
dramatically in the next six months, we'll close it down.''
   Murdoch acknowledged Monday that ratings for the Fox network's
Saturday shows were ``disappointing.'' But he said new programs are
being produced for that night.
   ``Furthermore, we are aggressively developing programming for
additional nights,'' he said. ``We have every intention of
continuing this investment for an indefinite period and remain
confident of its ultimate success, both for itself, our own
stations and our affiliates.''
   Fox, which began its prime-time programming on Sunday and
Saturday nights more than a year ago, has 125 affiliated stations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
