<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChemicalFire 1stLd-Writethru a0777 06-20 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0777,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four-Day-Old Blaze Quelled, Residents Allowed To Return</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 4-5 bgng ``No damage'' with three grafs to UPDATE
with all residents returning, crews working into the night to
remove containers. Picks up 6th graf pvs ``My roses.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters poured neutralizing
chemicals on barrels of chloride, and cheering residents returned
home Monday after a four-day fire that spewed poisonous gas and
forced evacuation of 25,000 people.
   ``I'd like to thank the people for the patience they have
demonstrated,'' Mayor Richard E. Neal said. ``Throughout, our
primary concern has been the public safety.''
   About 275 people were injured and thousands camped out in
shelters as explosions rocked the century-old mill housing the
Advanced Laboratories plant, which made chloride pellets for
swimming pools.
   Officials said the fire was among the worst in memory in this
city of 170,000 people. No damage estimate was available, but Neal
said city lawyers were ``agressively pursuing'' plans to recoup
expenses.
   Residents waved to police and cheered as the first school bus
with returning evacuees moved through a barricade about 1 p.m. The
last of the evacuees returned home at 6:30 p.m. and only the street
in front of the plant remained closed, Fire Commissioner Darnell L.
Williams said.
   Two fire trucks and police patrols were to remain on the scene
overnight as crews worked to remove the containers of chlorine
compounds weighing up to 300 pounds, authorities said.
   ``My roses are black and my tomatoes are dead,'' Antoinette
Harris, 37, said after returning home Monday. ``But the dog is all
right.''
   After more than 36 hours of flooding the factory with more than
6,000 gallons of water a minute, barrels of chloride stopped
exploding Monday.
   Clean-up crews then poured a solution of neutralizing chemicals
on ``hot spots'' where the chloride compounds were decomposing and
producing toxic chlorine gas.
   John Higgins, regional director of the state Department of
Environmental Quality Engineering, said firefighters shut off their
hoses briefly Sunday afternoon so officials could quickly tour the
plant, but barrels of chloride started exploding again soon
afterward.
   Hoses from all city pumpers flooded the building until 6:15 a.m.
Monday. By 8 a.m., no barrels had exploded, and the neutralizing
mixture of boric acid and sodium sulfate was poured onto the
remaining chloride barrels, some of which were bubbling.
   State-contracted clean-up crews gingerly removed more than 8,000
pounds of chlorine-containing compounds left in the building as
firefighters stood by Monday afternoon.
   The material was taken to the city's sewage treatment plant and
used in lieu of the chlorine the city normally buys for the
facility, Higgins said. ``At least that way the city can get back
some of the money it's spent,'' he said.
   At the fire's peak Saturday night, flames shot 100 feet in the
air and a cloud of poisonous gas 100 feet high, four blocks wide
and three miles long streamed over Springfield and into neighboring
Chicopee. The fumes could be smelled 15 miles away.
   In the cloud's path, trees and lawns were withered by the
corrosive gas.
   ``What's going to happen to my garden?'' said Wavel Watson, who
lives a few blocks from the plant. ``The annuals, the shrubs, the
lawn _ everything is withered and I just put it all in three weeks
ago.''
</TEXT>
