<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AbductedWoman 1stLd_Writethru a0796 06-20 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abducted Woman, 1st Ld _ Writethru, a0796,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bookstore Owner Charged In Kidnapping</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds.: Recasts lead to add that suspect was acquitted in 1971
killing; SUBS last 2 grafs bgng ``The abduction'' with 2 grafs to
elaborate on suspect's background and aquittal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORRY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bookstore owner acquitted of an Ohio man's
murder in 1971 was charged with kidnapping on Monday in the
abduction of a bank branch manager's wife who was found dead after
a failed attempt to ransom her.
   David C. Copenhefer, 41, was being held in Erie County Jail
under $100,000 bond in the kidnapping of Sally Weiner, 37.
Investigators said they believe she was abducted Friday afternoon
at Corry Plaza, where Copenhefer operates Corry Books & Cards.
   She apparently was lured to the plaza on the pretense of
planning a civic tribute to her husband, Pennbank's Corry branch
manager, Harry Weiner, investigators said.
   Mrs. Weiner was shot in the back of the head and left near an
abandoned gas well on a farm five miles northwest of Corry, where a
farmer found her Sunday.
   Police declined to say what led them to Copenhefer, but served
search warrants on him at 2 a.m. Monday. Local and state police and
FBI agents were seen at Copenhefer's home, confiscating armloads of
guns, including high-powered automatic rifles, and a personal
computer, desktop printer and computer printouts from his business.
   Copenhefer surrendered and was arraigned on charges of
kidnapping, attempted robbery and attempted extortion.
   No homicide charge was filed. Authorities said their
investigation was continuing and that further charges were pending.
   Copenhefer has lived in Corry since September, when he left
Greenfield, Ohio, where police said he managed a grocery store.
   Mrs. Weiner last spoke to her husband Friday afternoon when she
called him at his office. Sounding as if she were reading a
statement, the woman warned that her captors would kill her unless
Weiner followed instructions in a note in the bank parking lot,
according to Pennbank President Thomas Doolin.
   Weiner obeyed, going alone to an isolated rendezvous carrying an
unspecified amount of money. But no one approached him and he left
two hours later. There was no further contact from Mrs. Weiner or
her captor.
   The abduction and killing shocked this quiet community of about
7,100 people in northwest Pennsylvania, where Copenhefer and his
wife moved from Greenfield, Ohio, a small town about 50 miles
northeast of Cincinnati. The couple moved to Corry about a month
after their three-bedroom ranch home was severely damaged by fire.
   In August 1971, Copenhefer was acquitted of the shooting death
of a former seminary student from Kettering, Ohio. John L. Calkins'
bullet-riddled body was found three days after being insured for
$550,000 in accidental death policies paid by Copenhefer, who was
listed as a beneficiary on all but one policy.
</TEXT>
