<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 2253EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Japan-Poll     06-20 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Poll,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll: Japanese View of Relations With U.S. Improves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of Japanese surveyed describe
relations between their country and the United States as friendly,
a reversal of the opinions found last year, according to results of
a poll released Monday.
   However, the Japanese are still much more negative about
relations between the two countries than they were three years ago,
according to the CBS News-Tokyo Broadcasting System Poll.
   The poll found that 54 percent of Japanese surveyed termed
relations with the United States as ``friendly,'' while 43 percent
said they were ``unfriendly.'' In 1987, 43 percent said they were
``friendly'' and 55 percent said they were ``unfriendly.''
   In 1985, the breakdown was 73 percent saying ``friendly'' and 21
percent ``unfriendly.''
   The current poll found Americans' opinions about bilateral
relations to be more positive than the Japanese view: 73 percent of
those surveyed answered ``friendly'' and 17 percent said
``unfriendly.''
   The survey also found that one-third of the Japanese interviewed
said their personal feelings about the United States were
unfriendly _ twice as high as the proportion of unfriendly opinions
reported among American respondents.
   Despite their positive opinions, the poll found Americans are
clearly concerned about trade with Japan. Almost the same
proportion of Americans surveyed said trade with Japan is bad for
the American economy (41 percent) as those who said it is good (42
percent).
   The poll found that respondents in both countries cited Japanese
government restrictions on imports of U.S. goods as the main reason
more U.S. goods are not sold in Japan. Forty-seven percent of
Americans surveyed cited the Japanese restrictions, and 46 percent
of the Japanese. Last year, 48 percent of Japanese surveyed said
the main reason was that U.S. goods were of lower quality.
   According to the poll, substantial numbers of Americans (41
percent) and Japanese (55 percent) think Japan should deal with the
trade imbalance by increasing its imports, rather than by
decreasing its exports. Sixty-six percent of the Japanese surveyed
said the United States should increase its exports to Japan, while
41 percent of the Americans said the United States should
concentrate on reducing Japanese imports.
   The poll also found:
   _Respondents in both countries _ 55 percent in the United
States, 88 percent in Japan _ agreed that blue-collar workers in
Japan work harder than their American counterparts.
   _Seventy-one percent of Americans and 74 percent of Japanese
surveyed would choose to buy a car made in their own countries. But
as a second choice, while 16 percent of Americans surveyed opted
for a Japanese car, 20 percent of the Japanese preferred a German
car.
   _Fewer than 1 percent of the Americans surveyed could name the
current Japanese prime minister, Noboru Takeshita. Nine out of 10
Japanese surveyed could name the president of the United States.
What's more, while 59 percent of the Japanese surveyed gave
President Reagan a favorable rating, only 42 percent of the
Americans queried did the same.
   CBS News interviewed a nationwide random sample of 1,539 adults
by telephone May 14-18. The Tokyo Broadcasting System interviewed a
nationwide random sample of 1,335 adults in person May 12-18. The
sampling error was said to be plus or minus 3 percentage points for
results based on the total sample in each country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880620-0196 </DOCNO>
