<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Killings,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Retrial, Man Convicted Of Murdering Two Policemen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 35-year-old ex-convict was convicted for a
second time Monday of murdering two police officers.
   The original 1983 conviction of Andrew Wilson was overtured last
year by the Illinois Supreme Court, which ruled that a confession
had been beaten out of him.
   A sentencing hearing begins Tuesday and prosecutors said they
would ask for the death penality.
   ``Let's go for it, all the way,'' said Patricia Fahey, the widow
of slain officer William Fahey.
   Fahey and Richard O'Brien were shot to death after they pulled a
car over for a traffic violation. The defense insisted Andrew
Wilson was not in the car, even though his eyeglasses were found at
the scene.
   Andrew and his brother, Jackie Wilson, were both convicted of
murder in 1983 and Andrew Wilson was sentenced to death.
   Jackie Wilson's conviction and life prison term also were
overturned because he wasn't given a separate trial. He is awaiting
a retrial.
   A witness, Derrick Martin, testified that the Wilson brothers
had let him out of a car two blocks from the shooting scene, just
before the officers were shot.
   Martin said Andrew Wilson had said he wanted to get some police
uniforms to help a friend escape from jail.
