<DOCNO> AP880620-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 2318EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reed     06-20 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reed,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State NAACP President Indicted A Second Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARVIN HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury Monday indicted state Rep.
Thomas Reed, the state NAACP president, on charges of accepting
$10,000 to secure the parole or early release of a convicted
murderer.
   The Montgomery County grand jury charged that Reed agreed to use
his position as a member of the Legislature's Joint Prison
Committee to get Anthony Dennis Chesser an early release and parole.
   A federal grand jury Thursday indicted Reed on charges of
accepting more than $15,000 in cash and restaurant equipment to
secure the early release of the same inmate. Chesser is serving a
40-year sentence for the murder of his wife in Russell County in
1984.
   Reed, 60, said earlier that the federal investigation stemmed
from his attempt this year to have the Confederate battle flag
removed from atop the Capitol dome. Federal prosecutors denied
Reed's claim.
   A longtime leader of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, Reed was one of 14 black state
legislators arrested Feb. 2 when they tried to scale a fence around
the state Capitol to remove the flag.
   Reed surrendered Monday to the sheriff's office and was freed on
a $5,000 appearance bond, said District Attorney Jimmy Evans.
   Efforts to reach Reed for comment Monday were unsuccessful, and
a person who answered the phone at his home said he was not there.
   After federal indictments were handed down last week, Reed had
said he would have no comment other than to reiterate his innocence.
   If convicted of the state charges, Reed could be sentenced to up
to 10 years in prison and fined up to $5,000.
   The federal indictment charges Reed with two counts of violating
the Hobbs Act through extortion and three counts of violating the
Interstate Travel Act by using the highways between Tuskegee and
Columbus, Ga., as well as an interstate telephone call to obtain
$10,000 in cash from Chesser's parents.
   Reed has several business interests, including a fried chicken
restaurant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
