<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The CIA's former station chief in Costa Rica
was indicted Monday on charges he participated in an illegal
conspiracy to arm the Nicaraguan rebels and lied to his superiors
to keep the operation secret.
   Joseph F. Fernandez, 51, also known as Tomas Castillo, was
charged with helping former National Security Council aide Oliver
L. North and arms dealer Richard V. Secord ship arms to the Contras
in 1986 when Congress had banned U.S. military assistance to the
rebels.
   The five-count indictment also charges that Fernandez obstructed
the Iran-Contra investigation conducted last year by the
presidential commission headed by former Sen. John Tower, R-Texas,
by stating falsely that he did not know that North was involved in
covert aid to the Contras or that supplies Fernandez helped deliver
included weapons and ammunition.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court gave cities and states a
major victory Monday in their escalating legal assault on exclusive
membership policies in private clubs, unanimously upholding a New
York City law that bans such discrimination.
   The court said the city's law, aimed at large clubs that exclude
women and minorities as members, is constitutional.
   ``The law merely prevents an association from using race, sex or
other specified characteristics as shorthand measures in place of
what the city considers to be more legitimate criteria for
determining membership,'' Justice Byron R. White wrote for the
court.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Republican senator on Monday rebuked the
Justice Department for halting 1985 testimony he said would have
revealed how defense contractors and private consultants were
illegally obtaining Pentagon weapons secrets.
   Sen. Charles E. Grassley, R-Iowa, said in a Senate floor speech
that he was duped by a top department official, who grabbed the
microphone from a Defense Department investigator about to testify
on his findings.
   The incident occurred in October 1985, and would have revealed
an alleged contract bribery scandal that became public just last
week, Grassley said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although the leaders of the world's most powerful
democracies meet in a summit cocoon of strict privacy, their
statements and the gist of negotiations are relayed in a
near-torrent of briefings by official spokesmen and senior advisers.
   But the picture that emerges can be as hard to fit together as a
pile of jumbled jigsaw pieces. Sometimes it's hard to believe that
all the briefers were even describing the same puzzle.
   Part of the problem is that the officials with the job of
carrying the news to some 3,000 anxious journalists are working
with second-hand information themselves. With rare exceptions, they
were not present at the discussions. The briefers had to be briefed
themselves.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just call him Ron.
   President Reagan invoked an air of informality at his first
summit seven years ago, and is trying to keep it up at his last.
   At the outset of the Toronto meeting, Reagan told the newcomers,
Prime Ministers Noboru Takeshita of Japan and Ciriaco De Mita of
Italy, that the leaders were on a first-name basis.
   ``My name is Ron,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
quoted the president as saying.
   Fitzwater didn't say whether they took him up on it.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MARYVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Clemmer has begun dreaming that his
drought-stricken fields are being drenched by a soft, gentle rain.
But this happy reverie turns to dust each morning, when the sun
comes streaming over the nearby Smoky Mountains.
   ``What I see when I look out my window in the morning makes me
sick to my stomach,'' says the 50-year-old Clemmer, who has been
raising cattle and crops in Blount County for the past quarter
century.
   What he sees is a rolling expanse of wilted, yellowish grass
that has been cropped to the nub by hungry cattle.
   And, lately, Clemmer has been seeing something else happening in
those seared fields, something he can hardly believe.
   ``Just look out there,'' he said Sunday afternoon while he and
some neighbors sat in the shade. ``It looks like a winter sight,
don't it? Here it is June and I'm feeding hay to my cattle.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official said 16 people were hurt in Armenia's
first ethnic riots since a territorial dispute began with
neighboring Azerbaijan, and a tape made available Monday showed
troops patrolling the Azerbaijani capital.
   The most serious violence in the ethnic dispute occurred Feb. 28
in Sumgait, an industrial city on the Caspian Sea northwest of
Baku, capital of Azerbaijan. Thirty-two people were killed _ 26
Armenians and six Azerbaijanis _ and 200 people were injured,
according to official figures.
   Reports from the area Monday indicated tension had not reduced
since the legislatures of both southern republics acted last week
on the land dispute between the Armenians, most of whom are
Christian, and the predominantly Moslem Azerbaijanis.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's biggest dealers of Suzuki Samurais say their sales
are slowly beginning to recover from the effects of a published
report that the sporty vehicles roll over too easily.
   The top 10 dealers say their June sales will be off from as
little as a tenth to more than half because of the critical June 2
report by Consumers Union, according to a survey by The Associated
Press.
   Separately, Consumers Union said Monday that it received a June
11 letter from American Suzuki Motor Corp. demanding a retraction
of the report. Consumers Union said it rejected the request,
writing back that its report was ``wholly fair and accurate, and
based upon properly conducted tests.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They were city kids on their first Cub Scout
camping trip. And when they came across a lake on a hot summer day,
they did what kids will do _ they jumped in.
   First one boy drowned, and then another, and no one seems to
know exactly how or why.
   Did Joel Nieves dive into Lake Ohrbach in grief after the body
of his friend, Luis Ruiz, was pulled from the bottom? Or did the
two 9-year-old Brooklyn boys drown together?
   ``We're in the process now of ascertaining that specific
information,'' said Deputy Inspector William Wallace, the detective
in charge of the case, as an investigation into the weekend deaths
continued Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The marriage of orangutans Josephine and
Denny is on the rocks after 19 years, and zoo officials are citing
irreconcilable genes.
   The couple hadn't been getting along anyway, but that wasn't the
reason for the breakup. A national species survival policy and
international zoo rules call for two genetic strains to be kept
separate, San Francisco Zoo Director Saul Kitchener said Monday.
   So the zoo is planning to move Josephine, a Bornean orangutan,
to the Philadelphia Zoo, where she can hook up with one of her own
kind, while Denny, a Sumatran orangutan, remains here. It was only
recently that experts became adept at determining the differences
between the two subspecies.
</TEXT>
