<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv29   06-20 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv29,0481</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wednesday, June 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Wednesday, June 29, the 181st day of 1988. There are
185 days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On June 29, 1767, the British Parliament approved the Townshend
Revenue Acts, which imposed import duties on glass, lead, paint,
paper and tea shipped to America. Colonists bitterly protested the
Acts, which were repealed in 1770.
   On this date:
   In 1776, the Virginia state constitution was adopted, and
Patrick Henry was made governor.
   In 1941, Polish statesman, pianist and composer Ignace
Paderewski died in New York at age 80. He received a state burial
at Arlington National Cemetery.
   In 1946, British authorities arrested more than 2,700 Jews in
Palestine in an attempt to stamp out alleged terrorism.
   In 1949, the government of South Africa began to implement its
policy of racial segregation known as apartheid with a ban on
racially-mixed marriages.
   In 1954, the Atomic Energy Commission voted against reinstating
Dr. J. Robert Oppenheimer's access to classified information.
   In 1966, the United States bombed fuel storage facilities near
the North Vietnamese cities of Hanoi and Haiphong.
   In 1967, Jerusalem was re-unified as Israel removed barricades
separating the Old City from the Israeli sector.
   In 1970, the United States ended a two-month military offensive
into Cambodia.
   In 1972, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the way the death
penalty was usually enforced constituted ``cruel and unusual
punishment.''
   In 1982, in a White House ceremony, President Reagan signed into
law an extension of the Voting Rights Act of 1965.
   In 1984, the Soviet Union offered to begin negotiations with the
United States on banning weapons from outer space. The U.S. said
such talks would have to include curbs on all missile systems.
   Ten years ago: Vice President Walter F. Mondale began a trip to
the Middle East, carrying letters from President Jimmy Carter to
the leaders of Israel and Egypt urging a resumption of peace talks.
   Five years ago: NASA officials completed a three-month operation
to nudge a communications satellite into its proper orbit using the
satellite's steering jets. The satellite had gone into a useless,
elliptical orbit after it was launched from the space shuttle
Challenger on April 4.
   One year ago: In a surprise move, the chairman of South Korea's
ruling party, Roh Tae-woo, demanded democratic reforms of the man
he was groomed to succeed, President Chun Doo-hwan, following weeks
of violent protests that racked the country. Chun agreed two days
later.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Ruth Warrick is 73. Sen. Carl Levin
(D-Mich.) is 54. Actor Gary Busey is 44.
   Thought for today: ``A happy life is one spent in learning,
earning and yearning.'' _ Lillian Gish, American movie actress.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880620-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 0929EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv30   06-20 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv30,0568</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, June 30</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, June 30, the 182nd day of 1988. There are 184
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Twenty-five years ago, on June 30, 1963, Pope Paul VI was
crowned the 262nd head of the Roman Catholic Church in an outdoor
ceremony at St. Peter's Square. In a homily delivered in nine
languages, the Pope said he intended to encourage ``greater mutual
comprehension, charity and peace between peoples.''
   On this date:
   In 1834, the Indian Territory was created by Congress.
   In 1859, French acrobat Emile Blondin crossed Niagara Falls on a
tightrope in front of 5,000 spectators.
   In 1870, Ada H. Kepley of Effingham, Ill., became America's
first female law school graduate.
   In 1906, the Pure Food and Drug Act and the Meat Inspection Act
became law.
   In 1934, Adolf Hitler began his ``blood purge'' of political and
military leaders in Germany. Among those killed was Ernst Roehm,
leader of the Nazi stormtroopers and Hitler's one-time ally.
   In 1936, Margaret Mitchell's novel ``Gone with the Wind'' was
published in New York.
   In 1952, ``The Guiding Light,'' a popular radio program, made
its debut as a television soap opera on CBS.
   In 1971, a Soviet space mission ended in tragedy when three
cosmonauts aboard Soyuz 11 were found dead inside their spacecraft
after returning to Earth.
   In 1971, the 26th Amendment to the Constitution, lowering the
minimum voting age to 18, was ratified as Ohio became the 38th
state to approve it.
   In 1977, President Jimmy Carter announced he had decided against
production of the B-1 bomber, saying it was too costly. The B-1 was
later revived by President Reagan.
   In 1982, the time limit for the proposed Equal Rights Amendment
to the U.S. Constitution expired, with proponents falling short of
the three additional states needed to ratify it.
   In 1985, 39 American hostages from a hijacked TWA jetliner were
freed in Beirut after being held 17 days.
   In 1986, in a 5-4 decision, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that
states could outlaw homosexual acts between consenting adults, even
in the privacy of their own homes.
   Ten years ago: Vice President Walter F. Mondale ran into both
hostile and friendly demonstrators as he began a four-day visit to
Israel to honor the Jewish state's 30th anniversary, and to
encourage resumption of stalled Mideast peace talks.
   Five years ago: The Justice Department announced it and the FBI
would conduct a formal investigation into how materials from
President Jimmy Carter's 1980 re-election campaign had gotten into
the hands of President Reagan's campaign staff.
   One year ago: The prosecutor at the trial of Klaus Barbie in
Lyon, France, denounced the crimes of the former Nazi Gestapo
official as ``particularly inhumane,'' and demanded the maximum
sentence of life in prison _ the sentence Barbie did end up
receiving.
   Today's birthdays: Actor David Wayne is 72. Singer Lena Horne is
71. Actress Nancy Dussault is 52.
   Thought for today: ``The cynic is one who never sees a good
quality in a man, and never fails to see a bad one. He is the human
owl, vigilant in darkness and blind to light.'' _ Henry Ward
Beecher, American clergyman (1813-1887).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880620-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 0930EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv01   06-20 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv01,0574</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday, July 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Friday, July 1, the 183rd day of 1988. There are 183
days left in the year. This is Canada Day.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On July 1, 1867, Canada became a self-governing dominion of
Great Britain as the British North America Act united the provinces
of Ontario, Quebec, New Brunswick and Nova Scotia.
   On this date:
   In 1535, Sir Thomas More went on trial in England, charged with
treason for rejecting the Oath of Supremacy.
   In 1690, the army of England's Protestant king, William III,
defeated forces loyal to the former Roman Catholic king, James II,
in the Battle of the Boyne in Ireland.
   In 1847, the first national adhesive postage stamps in the U.S.
were issued.
   In 1863, the Civil War Battle of Gettysburg began.
   In 1898, during the Spanish-American War, Theodore Roosevelt and
his Rough Riders waged a victorious assault on San Juan Hill in
Cuba.
   In 1916, Dwight D. Eisenhower married Mary (``Mamie'') Geneva
Doud in Denver, Colo.
   In 1932, New York Gov. Franklin D. Roosevelt was nominated for
president at the Democratic Convention in Chicago.
   In 1943, ``pay-as-you-go'' income tax withholding began for
American wage and salary earners.
   In 1966, the Medicare federal insurance program went into effect.
   In 1968, the United States, Britain, the Soviet Union and 58
other nations signed the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
   In 1969, Britain's Prince Charles was invested as Prince of
Wales in a ceremony at Caernarvon Castle.
   In 1977, fellow Britons cheered as tennis star Virginia Wade
received the Wimbledon women's singles trophy from Queen Elizabeth
II after defeating Betty Stove of the Netherlands.
   In 1982, more than 2,000 couples, members of the Unification
Church, were married in a mass ceremony at New York's Madison
Square Garden by the church's founder, the Rev. Sun Myung Moon.
   Ten years ago: Former President Richard M. Nixon received a warm
welcome in Hyden, Ky., where he arrived to dedicate a recreation
center named for him and make his first public speech since
resigning office in 1974.
   Five years ago: R. Buckminster Fuller, the inventor and
philosopher who designed the geodesic dome and preached technology
as the salvation of humankind, died in Los Angeles at age 87 after
suffering a heart attack at the hospital bedside of his wife.
   One year ago: President Reagan nominated U.S. Appeals Court
Judge Robert H. Bork to the U.S. Supreme Court, setting off a
tempestuous confirmation process that would culiminate in Bork's
rejection by the U.S. Senate the following October.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Olivia de Havilland is 72. Actor
Farley Granger is 63. Actress-dancer Leslie Caron is 57. Actress
Jean Marsh is 54. Film director Sydney Pollack is 54. Actor Jamie
Farr is 54. Dancer-choreographer Twyla Tharp is 47. Actress Karen
Black is 46. Actress Genevieve Bujold is 46. Actor-comedian Dan
Aykroyd is 36. Actress Lorna Patterson is 31. Singer Evelyn
``Champagne'' King is 28. Diana, Princess of Wales, is 27.
   Thought for today: ``We need the guidance of history. All our
yesterdays, it is true, have only lighted fools the way to dusty
death. But we need at least the dates of the yesterdays and the
list of the fools.'' _ Stephen Leacock, Canadian humorist and
educator (1869-1944).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
