<DOCNO> AP880620-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 0939EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Archaeology-Denmark Adv23   06-20 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Archaeology-Denmark, Adv 23,0739</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs June 23 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Museum Workers Reconstructing Stone Age Boat in Denmark</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, another archaeology story for release this date is
PM-Archaeology-Rome, b0293.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK POWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSKILDE, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts have begun painstakingly
piecing together the crumbling remains of a newly discovered
ancient dugout boat beached near a Stone Age settlement more than
7,000 years ago.
   The dugout, thought to be one of the oldest vessels ever
recovered, was spotted last summer by skin-diving scientists and
historians on an expedition to an area where Paleolithic flint
tools had been found earlier.
   Stone Age shipwrights made the boat by hollowing out a lime log
with flint axes. A carbon 14 test of the vessel's lime wood dated
it to 5250 B.C.
   By chance the divers caught sight of the boat's gunwales
sticking up from the sandy seabed at a depth of about 6{ feet.
   They named it the ``Korshavn Dugout'' after the bay in the
northeast of the island of Funen where it was found.
   Following a troubled salvage operation that shattered the hull,
the dugout was brought in pieces to Roskilde Ship Museum on the
main island of Zealand, which houses a major collection of restored
Viking-age ships from nearby excavations.
   ``It could take up to two years to assemble the thousands of
boat pieces onto a frame,'' said Tinna Damsgaard-Soerensen, the
historian in charge of reconstructing the dugout.
   ``It's like a big jigsaw puzzle, but solvable.''
   The delicate pieces, each wrapped in a spongy cloth, are laid
out in water-filled trays to conserve the wood. None is larger than
a paperback book.
   The painstaking task of drawing, photographing, conserving and
cataloging each piece is being carried out in full public view as a
working exhibition, which includes a video tape of the salvage.
   It proved impossible to measure the boat's length because the
ends were missing. But 12 feet of the dugout survived, and
restoration workers estimate it was at least 13 to 16{ feet long
with a 24-inch beam.
   The dugout had a surprisingly thin hull, less than two inches
thick at the bottom and 1.2 inches along the gunwales, said curator
Flemming Rieck.
   ``It's a superb example of handicrafting,'' he said.
   To gain a better understanding of Stone Age methods, Rieck's
group hauled a fresh lime log into the museum hall and carved a
replica of the Korshavn boat with flint tools.
   Rieck, an expert on ancient vessels of northern Europe, said
dugouts were used mainly for hunting and fishing close to home, and
for transporting people and goods between settlements.
   Dugouts like the Korshavn, which could carry four or five
people, often had a clay fireplace in the stern because ancient man
carried fire with him on his travels, Rieck said.
   The dugout apparently was abandoned on the shore near a
settlement. But the rising waters from melting glaciers north of
Denmark flooded the area, and the boat was discovered underwater,
Rieck said.
   The boat rested in an eight-inch-thick culture layer containing
bits of flint and food scraps that can reveal glimpses of
settlement life.
   The excavation of the Korshavn Dugout presented a special
problem requiring a method that had never been tried before, said
Rieck.
   Due to the advanced decomposition of the wood, salvagers decided
to bring up the boat together with the layer of sand in which it
was embedded.
   A strong salvaging frame was dug into position around the boat.
Thin copper pipes were inserted through the frame's lower edge
beneath the boat through which liquid nitrogen was pumped at a
temperature of minus 392 degrees Fahrenheit.
   It was hoped, Rieck said, the intense cold would freeze the
water around the pipes, forming a firm base of ice within the
salvaging frame that could be raised out of the sea with the dugout
intact.
   But a severe storm broke as the salvage was under way. Large
amounts of sand shifted as waves beat against the seabed. The next
morning the divers found the dugout lying in fragments within the
frame, which were sent to the museum on wooden planks.
   ``We still have faith in the freeze technique and probably will
try it again in some future excavation,'' said Rieck.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs June 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880620-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 0940EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Brazil-JusticeMakers Adv27   06-20 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Justice Makers, Adv 27,0703</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs June 27 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Brazilian Police Battle Vigilante `Justice Makers'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a summer evening in one of the
crime-ridden slums on Sao Paulo's outskirts, five men sat in a
run-down bar. The drinks would be their last.
   Seven men burst in with handguns, lined the five against a wall
and fired more than 30 bullets into them.
   The killers vanished into the night.
   Police say the vigilante-style slayings last February,
summertime in Brazil, were the work of ``justiceiros,'' Portuguese
for justice makers.
   The gangs are on the rise here in South America's biggest city,
where outnumbered and poorly equipped police can't keep up with
violent crime.
   Since 1986, police say, justiceiros have killed an estimated 400
people in the slums of this city of 10 million.
   ``Several victims were bandits. Others, like those gunned down
last February, were killed because they had witnessed justiceiro
killings. Many were killed for no apparent reason,'' said Waldemar
dos Santos Batista, a chief investigator on the newly created
anti-justiceiro squad of the Sao Paulo State Security Bureau.
   Since it began operations March 11, the 250-man squad has
arrested 30 suspected justiceiros who, Batista said, have confessed
to 120 murders over the past two years. About 100 justiceiros are
still thought to be at large, he said.
   The vigilante gangs are similar to the ``death squads'' in Rio
de Janeiro in the 1960s. Policemen, reacting to the shooting death
of a popular detective, began to summarily execute suspected
criminals, leaving skull-and-crossbones emblems next to the bodies.
   In Sao Paulo, justiceiros first surfaced about six years ago,
eliminating bandits who preyed on slum merchants and dwellers,
according to State Security Chief Luiz Antonio Fleury Filho.
   ``They were welcomed in the slums, because police lack
credibility among the poor and because of the impunity criminals
enjoy as a result of the excessively bureaucratic, inefficient and
slow-moving legal system,'' Fleury said in an interview.
   He added that about two years ago, justiceiros expanded their
activities and began dealing in drugs, forcing shopowners to buy
protection _ often killing those who didn't _ charging fees to
allow people to circulate unmolested in the slums.
   ``People who at first felt protected by these criminals started
being victimized by them, and gradually the slums started wanting
to get rid of the justiceiros,'' he added.
   Like the Rio death squads, justiceiro gangs are believed to be
made up largely of off-duty policemen, frustrated at what they
believe are legal obstacles keeping them from more forceful action
against criminals.
   ``Some policemen may be showing a certain tolerance towards the
justiceiros,'' Fleury said. ``We are investigating this possibility
as well as any other more serious involvement by police.''
   One of the most notorious justiceiros, Fleury said, was
Florisvaldo de Oliveira, a Sao Paulo state police corporal who,
during his off-duty hours, killed at least 50 people from 1982 to
1983, when he was arrested.
   Oliveira was sentenced to 84 years in prison. He escaped twice,
allegedly with help from sympathetic jailers, and was recaptured
this past May 25.
   Cidenor Ancelmo Brilhante of the industrial suburb of Sao
Bernardo do Campo openly calls himself ``the bandit hunter.''
Police say they suspect he is a justiceiro, but Inspector Carmine
Pepe of the anti-justiceiro squad said ``so far we have not been
able to prove anything.''
   In an interview with the Folha de Sao Paulo newspaper, Brilhante
said he couldn't remember how many people he has killed.
   ``Most of the time I hunt down bandits and turn them over to the
police or I kill them in shootouts, never in cold blood,'' the
paper quoted him as saying.
   ``Anyone who murders or rapes cannot be considered a human
being. For me such a person is nothing more than a louse, and lice
must be crushed.''
   The ``bandit hunter'' has become so popular among slum dwellers
that he is preparing to run for City Councilman in November's
elections, Folha de Sao Paulo said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs June 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880620-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 0924EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv26   06-20 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv26,0463</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, June 26, the 178th day of 1988. There are 188
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Twenty-five years ago, on June 26, 1963, President John F.
Kennedy visited West Berlin, where he was greeted by more than a
million of the divided city's residents. In a speech, Kennedy made
his now-famous declaration, ``Ich bin ein Berliner.'' (I am a
Berliner).
   On this date:
   In 1870, the first section of Atlantic City, N.J.'s famous
boardwalk was opened to the public.
   In 1900, a commission that included Dr. Walter Reed began the
fight against the deadly disease yellow fever.
   In 1917, the first troops of the American Expeditionary Force
arrived in France during World War I.
   In 1919, the first issue of the New York Daily News was
published.
   In 1945, the charter of the United Nations was signed by 50
countries in San Francisco. (The text of the charter was in five
languages: Chinese, English, French, Russian and Spanish.)
   In 1948, in response to the Soviet blockade of West Berlin, the
United States announced it would increase its daily cargo flights
to the western sector of the isolated German city.
   In 1959, President Dwight D. Eisenhower joined Britain's Queen
Elizabeth II in ceremonies officially opening the St. Lawrence
Seaway.
   In 1975, citing what she called a ``deep and widespread
conspiracy'' against her government, Indian Prime Minister Indira
Gandhi declared a state of emergency.
   In 1977, 42 people were killed when a fire, caused by an inmate
who had ignited padding material in his cell, sent toxic smoke
pouring through the Maury County Jail in Columbia, Tenn.
   In 1984, with only four seconds remaining in the countdown, the
first launch of the space shuttle Discovery was scrubbed when a
problem developed in an engine fuel valve.
   Ten years ago: A bomb blamed on Brittany separatists went off at
the Palace of Versailles in France, severely damaging one wing of
the historic building.
   Five years ago: The Soviet Union announced that 15
Pentecostalists would be allowed to leave the country, including
five who had taken refuge in the U.S. Embassy in Moscow for nearly
5 years.
   One year ago: Supreme Court Justice Lewis F. Powell Jr.
announced his retirement from the nation's highest court, leaving
open a vacancy that was eventually filled by Judge Anthony M.
Kennedy.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Eleanor Parker is 66. Singer Billy
Davis is 48.
   Thought for today: ``Custom may lead a man into many errors, but
it justifies none.'' _ Henry Fielding, English author and dramatist
(1707-1754).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
