<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1314EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Poland-Youth Adv27   06-20 0964</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Youth, Adv 27,0994</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, June 27, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>For Poland's Young: Should They Leave or Stay?
^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wlodzimierz Rucewicz, 28, university
graduate, husband and father of one, has a decision to make.
   Should he leave Poland for good and seek a better life in the
West, living among strangers and perhaps never being accepted as
anything but an alien?
   Or should he remain in the land of his birth and face a future
of paralyzing bureaucracy, consumer shortages and struggle for a
decent living?
   He's not alone in his pondering.
   The same questions loom to a greater or lesser degree for
virtually all of the 12 million Poles under 30 who must decide,
after 43 years of communism and nearly a decade of economic crisis,
whether there is any real reason to stay in Poland.
   Polish-born Pope John Paul II has advised them that their place
is in Poland.
   The government angrily has accused Western countries of
deliberately trying to draw away Poland's best and brightest.
   But public opinion polls and sociologists indicate that young
people are less and less hopeful for their future at home and that
more and more of them want to live abroad for at least two years.
   Rucewicz, who earns his living as a free-lance English
translator, says he looks in his address book and sees most of his
friends already are in the United States, Britain or Australia.
   ``Not too many people are starving here, like in Ethiopia or are
homeless in the sense that they have nowhere to go,'' he said.
``But it doesn't have to be that drastic to make your life a living
hell, right?''
   He cites low wages and the lack of housing as two of the main
problems.
   ``You've got something like 30 years to wait before you get an
apartment (in a housing cooperative).
   ``If you want to work honestly _ that is, come to work in your
office, do your job and go back home _ there is no way that you
could ever in your life earn enough money to buy your own place.
There are no jobs in Poland that could give you that much money.''
   Buying a modest house in the Warsaw outskirts costs at least 10
million zlotys ($23,000), while a couple working at decent jobs may
earn 1.2 million zlotys ($2,800) a year. With no mortgage system
for buying houses, a couple has save the entire sum before making
the purchase.
   Sociologist Jerzy Wertenstein-Zulawski mentions a welter of
other factors contributing to a sense of hopelessness among Polish
youth, including feelings of alienation and lack of control, a
``hostile'' school environment, oppressive laws and poor
environmental and health conditions in Poland.
   Citing an officially published study last year of Polish youth,
he said only 10 percent feel they have a degree of control in their
workplace, and the number of youths who believe the world will turn
to communism is falling.
   Young people also see their career prospects blocked by
politics, Wertenstein-Zulawski said. In a country where 75 percent
of managerial jobs belong to members of the Polish United Workers
Party, as the communist party is called, only 1 percent of people
under 35 have party membership cards.
   Emigration is one option for the young, especially since
Poland's liberalized passport policy allows large numbers to go
abroad.
   In the period 1980-87, about 365,000 Poles emigrated or legally
extended their stays abroad, while 370,000 illegally failed to
return from foreign trips, according to a recently published
article in the Polish weekly Odrodzenia. The number includes an
estimated 22,000 engineers, 3,000 economists, 3,000 doctors and
4,000 scientists.
   Wertenstein-Zulawski, who works for the Ministry of Culture,
said some young people have turned to drugs, alcohol, hard-rock
music, or cult groups practicing parapsychology or Buddhism.
   He added that Poles now are seeing in their midst growing
numbers of leather-jacketed Polish ``punks,'' a movement brought
back to Poland by young intelligentsia who traveled abroad and
which now is rooted in the working class.
   Poland's growing private sector has provided another outlet for
many disenchanted youth.
   Rucewicz said his once politically active friends have given up
hope of changing the system, and now are devoting themselves
single-mindedly to ``making money'' _ for instance in boutiques,
restaurants, shoe-sole manufacturing or tailoring services.
   The problem is that running a business in Poland is almost
impossible within the law, because of strangling taxes, regulations
and inability to obtain materials through legal channels, Rucewicz
said.
   ``If you don't cheat here and there, you're ruined immediately.
... That makes you practically a criminal.''
   As part of its economic reform program, the government is
starting to address the issue, promising to remove obstacles to
entering businesses and do away with many regulations.
   ``If I were the government I would do everything possible to
increase the private sector because this is the only thing for
these energetic people, the people with initiative,'' said
Wertenstein-Zulawski.
   A statement in February by government spokesman Jerzy Urban
assailing those who emigrate for better salaries has brought an
angry and anguished response from many young people.
   Piotr Stepniak, a junior faculty member at Poznan University who
says he and his wife hold down six jobs, wrote in the weekly
newspaper Prawo i Zycie (Law and Life) recently that the complaints
about greedy young people show ``the authorities do not want to
notice the real reasons for emigration.''
   ``The Polish crisis already has a chronic character,'' he said.
   ``Everything is provisional, relative and subject to reform. The
highest ideals in this perspective lose their sense for the young
generation. Today white is black, tomorrow red, the next day blue.
...''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, June 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
