<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--SocialistMayor Adv03-1stAdd   06-20 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Socialist Mayor, Adv 03-1st Add,0796</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv03</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
<HEAD>BURLINGTON, Vt.: Union Party.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Conservatism was in its heyday elsewhere when Sanders scored his
first victory in Vermont, squeaking into office with a 10-vote
margin over a Democratic incumbent.
   Voters, politicians and media weren't the only ones caught by
surprise.
   ``I woke up one day and was mayor of Burlington,'' Sanders
recalls, in a voice, right out of Flatbush, that still carries
traces of disbelief seven years later. ``Before that, the largest
business I'd ever run employed two people _ and not at the same
time.''
   The upset made him not only the highest elected official in
Vermont's biggest city, but also the only independent mayor of the
only three-party city in America.
   Built on the steep hills that rise from the shores of Lake
Champlain, Burlington looks out at New York's scenic Adirondack
Mountains. It's a casual, stylish little city that owes its
affluence to a nearby IBM plant, its academic flavor to the
University of Vermont.
   ``Burlington is a very nice city right next to Vermont,'' jokes
the mayor. It's a popular view of the commercial, cultural and
academic center of a determinedly rural state.
   While Vermonters may consider Burlington ``the big city,'' its
problems are closer to small-town scale, Sanders acknowledges. For
example, the city runs two emergency shelters with a total of 80
beds. ``On the worst night,'' he says, ``we might fill them both.''
   Whether Sanders' political success is strictly a Burlington
phenomenon is a notion the mayor will test in November, as an
independent candidate in a three-way race for the state's lone U.S.
House seat.
   While he's been re-elected as mayor three times, Sanders has
suffered his share of defeats while in office.
   Last March, the administration sought, but failed to get, voter
approval of a special assessment against all non-residential
property to launch a $600,000 day-care program.
   A proposal that some affordable housing be incorporated in all
new residential development never got past the board of aldermen.
   Despite Burlington's three-party status, Sanders' Independent
Progressive Party has never held a majority on the 13-member board
of aldermen. Currently, it comprises four Democrats, three
Republicans and six Progressives, the most favorable balance since
Sanders took office.
   Regardless of the gains, ``this is still one small city in a
capitalist country. My political dream is to develop a strong third
party. The reality is that the majority of people are Democrats and
Republicans.''
   Sanders views military spending and nuclear weaponry as local
issues. ``To the degree that the federal government spends more on
bombs and nerve gas, it also spends less on fire departments,'' he
says.
   Nancy Chioffi, Democratic president of the board of aldermen and
a possible candidate for mayor in next year's election, says not
everyone considers a global agenda appropriate for a small-city
mayor. ``There's a strong sense that the city should spend its time
on city business,'' she says.
   She praises Sanders for his tax reform, hiring and economic
development efforts, as well as ``opening the doors of city hall to
a broader spectrum of people. He's stirred the pot, and in so
doing, he's created a very exciting climate.''
   ``The other side is that he's shut out more traditional people.
His belief in the need for three parties has created a large rift''
between traditional Democrats and Independents, who tend to be
yesterday's liberal Democrats.
   The level of animosity became clear at a Democratic caucus in
April, at which Sanders, appearing on behalf of Jesse Jackson,
literally got his face slapped by a Democrat who thought he had no
business being there.
   Chioffi also accuses the mayor of economic oversimplification.
``If you're rich, you're bad; if you're poor you're good,'' she
says. ``He needs to recognize that there are some good rich and
some bad poor.''
   The uneven distribution of wealth is a recurring campaign theme
as Sanders rattles around the state in a rusting gray Honda
littered with empty yogurt containers, old sweat shirts and ratty
news clippings. To climb in is to enter a time warp, right down to
the '60s folk songs jammed into the tape deck.
   No matter what his fate in November, this will be his last term
as mayor. Among the most memorable events of his tenure was his May
28 wedding to Jane Driscoll, 37, director of the city's Youth
Office.
   The wedding, held at a city park and open to the public,
prompted Sanders to don a suit for the occasion. Equally startling,
he arrived early, a full eight minutes before the ceremony began.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
