<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--OtherFolks Adv03   06-20 1099</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Other Folks, Adv 03,1132</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 2 35mm slides.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ There are the celebrities, the news-makers, the
movers and shakers. Then there are the other folks, ordinary people
doing ordinary or extraordinary jobs, trying to cope in a
complicated world, chasing their own dreams. Here is the first in
an occasional series focusing on the Other Folks. Meet Linda Seay,
prison guard and country singer.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DAVID L. LANGFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   STARKE, Fla. _ It was a first for Linda Seay, a prison guard by
day, a honky-tonk singer by night, a country girl who knows what
it's like to work in the tobacco fields and is proud of it.
   ``Today we had a stabbing at the prison,'' she was saying the
other night at the 301 Lounge, a local hangout where she often
sings her song, ``Shed a Tear.'' ``It's the first stabbing I've
witnessed.''
   At age 32, Linda Seay, the daughter of a truck
driver-barber-insurance salesman, is still dreaming of making it
big in Nashville (a place she's never been) like her idol Loretta
Lynn (a person she's never met). She wants a little log cabin with
a creek running beside it, where she can go and fish and sit with
her guitar, picking out the tunes that come into her head.
   For the time being she's making ends meet working as a guard at
Union Correctional Institution, a maximum security prison for men
at Raiford, just across the New River from the main Florida state
prison.
   It's not a comfortable place for a bouncy brunette with curly
hair, who stands just 5-feet-1, weighs 125 pounds, and carries
neither gun nor billy stick. She hears the inmates sniffing her
perfume as she walks by _ ``It gives them a kick'' _ and sometimes
has to dress one down for getting fresh.
   ``I feel like Daniel in the lion's den,'' says Linda, giggling.
``What am I going to do, hit them with my purse?
   ``It's the new ones that come in and try you out. You have to
end up locking up and chewing out.''
   The giggle fades.
   ``It's a real dangerous place,'' she says. ``That ain't no
prison for bad-check writers. I don't want to be there. It's just
the only good-paying job in this area and I get homesick when I'm
away from home.''
   Linda earns $7.50 an hour, not bad money in this part of
palmetto-pocked, rural north Florida where the only major employers
are the nearby prisons, a Du Pont titanium surface mine, and Camp
Blanding, a National Guard training base 10 miles east of the town
of about 6,000. Linda's father worked at the prison for a while, as
does her brother, a brother-in-law, an uncle.
   ``I'm a correctional officer by day, but really my heart is a
rebel,'' she says.
   Most of the women guards at Union work in the eight towers
surrounding the prison, Linda says.
   ``You just sit up there and you have your gun in the corner,
ready to go,'' Linda says. ``If one gets across the first fence,
you fire a warning shot. If he gets through the second fence, you
stop him _ whatever it takes. You don't have time to look up this
man's file and see what he's in there for.
   ``It takes gutsy women.''
   A child bride, Linda got married at 16 _ ``when I was young and
dumb'' _ and was divorced six years later. Seay is her maiden name.
   Like her two younger sisters and a younger brother, she was
introduced to music in the Pentecostal Holiness Church, singing the
old-time gospel songs like ``In the Sweet Bye and Bye,'' ``I'll Fly
Away,'' and ``Amazing Grace.'' After she taught herself to play the
guitar by ear (she still can't read music), she became a favorite
at family reunions.
   When she was 13 she started singing professionally with a group
from Palatka called The Country Ramblers. ``We played all the
places that would let me in, since I was a minor.''
   She's been at it ever since, appearing at places like Bobby's
Hideaway in Waldo, the Happy Hour Lounge in Jacksonville, the
Holiday Inn (before it changed its name) and the Club 100 (before
it burned down) in Starke.
   ``I guess I've played every honky-tonk and beer tavern in a
100-mile radius,'' she says.
   Six years ago, at a small four-track studio in Florahome, near
Palatka, Linda cut a record with two songs she wrote, ``Shed a
Tear'' and ``Since I First Laid Eyes on You.''
   Backing her up was The Midnight Express, a truck driver on
drums, an eighth-grade teacher on the bass, the operator of a TV
rental store on lead guitar. Some 400 records were pressed, at a
personal cost of $2,500. A few wound up on jukeboxes around the
county and some truck drivers took a few to other parts of the
country.
   Four years ago, came the job at the prison.
   Correctional officers must have a high school diploma and
qualify firing such weapons as the AR15 rifle, .38-caliber
revolver, .357-caliber Magnum and the shotgun. They then go through
eight weeks of training.
   ``Oh, I hate that shotgun,'' Linda giggles. ``It kicks so bad.''
   Linda works in a glass-enclosed cubicle in a breezeway between
three buildings housing 96 prisoners each, keeping track of their
movements, logging them in, logging them out.
   She was at her post when the stabbing occurred.
   ``At lunchtime,'' she says, ``one inmate walked in, spoke to me,
and walked through the breezeway. When he opened the door to his
cell, his cellmate stabbed him with a homemade knife.''
   Linda is longing for the day she gets out of that prison, to
make it in music. She plays the Florida lottery every day, hoping
for the big break.
   ``I watch the country music awards, you know, and I fantasize.
How they must feel, if they've worked all their lives like I have.
I've worked in the tobacco fields stringing tobacco, I've
waitressed, I've tended bar, I've been a soda jerk. Just done
anything I could to make a living, but mostly singing.
   ``As long as I've got my guitar, I don't think I'll go without
food.''
   She's proud of her country roots, doesn't want to live anywhere
else.
   ``Country is something that's born into you,'' she says. ``You
can't take a Yankee and make him a country boy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
