<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Disney Boom, Adv 03-2 Takes,0860</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Walt Disney World, which already has made a lot
of people in Florida rich, is under going its biggest expansion
since Epcot Center opened in 1982. But some retailers, hoteliers
and operators of the satellite tourist attractions are beginning to
worry that Disney will have to much to offer that tourists won't be
throwing as much money their way.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The imagineers of Walt Disney
World have fashioned a $1 billion expansion of their Florida
playground, including a movie-TV production studio, a nightclub
complex, gigantic hotels and a retail shopping center.
   While much of the surrounding business community is delighted,
anticipating that a new influx of tourists will mean a continuing
supply of big bucks, a few skeptics exist.
   Some county officials and local leaders are concerned about the
effect on the economy, on traffic, the life style and utility
infrastructure of the two-county area that Disney dominates. A few
retailers, hotel people and operators of smaller attractions are
worried that Disney's expansion into more commercial activities
could mean more competition and less profit for them.
ohn Maynard Keynes that encourage
government deficits and more government control over the economy.
   After graduating from the London School of Economics in the
1920s with a doctoral degree, Hutt served as a pilot in the Royal
Air Force during World War II.
   He taught at the University of Cape Town in South Africa from
1926 until 1965 and was a leading critic of apartheid. His book,
``Economics of the Color Bar'', is considered a classic in the
field of economics and race relations.
   In the 1940s, Hutt helped found the Mont Pelerin Society, an
international organization of scholars supporting free enterprise.
   Hutt came to the United States in 1965 and lectured at the
University of Virginia, the University of Chicago, Stanford
University and Texas A&M University.
   He moved to Irving in 1971 and lectured at the University of
Dallas, serving as professor emeritus after his retirement in the
early 1980s.
   He is survived by his wife, Grethe Hutt.
</TEXT>
