<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--MexicoElections Adv03-2Takes   06-20 0965</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Mexico Elections, Adv 03-2 Takes,0995</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Mexico's Institutional Revolutionary Party, or
PRI, has never lost a presidential election or gubernatorial race
since coming to power in 1929 and is not likely to in the elections
coming up on July 6. Nonetheless, with the country in an economic
crisis, critics of the PRI say it has outlived its usefulness and
now is addicted to power and bloated by corruption. There is a cry
for change growing among the country's 80 million citizens.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shocked by the political and economic
tensions of the 1980s, Mexicans are talking more frequently about
the need for change as they grope for a new sense of national
purpose.
   The process may stop short of national soul-searching, but there
has been widespread recognition of Mexico's difficulties and the
loss of credibility in a system of government that has lasted most
of this century.
   Even Carlos Salinas de Gortari, a certain winner in July 6
elections as the presidential candidate of the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, talks consistently of the need for reforms.
   Salinas de Gortari's term will last until 1994, and the next
president will govern to the year 2000.
   The 21st century suddenly seems to be approaching very quickly
and is a handy reference point for the time when change inevitably
must occur.
   ``I think that the opposition is carrying out its struggle, and
with time, in the next century it will obtain political
positions,'' former President Luis Echeverria said recently in a
rare published interview.
   ``Until the next century?'' the reporter asked.
   ``That's not much time,'' Echeverria replied.
   The ruling party, known here as the PRI, has held power since
1929. It never has lost a presidential election or gubernatorial
race in any of Mexico's 31 states since its inception.
   So entrenched is it that a book that might be described as
political science fiction was published called, ``The Day the PRI
Lost.''
   It won't be July 6, 1988.
   Salinas de Gortari, budget secretary for President Miguel de la
Madrid until his nomination last fall, is certain to win over
divided opposition.
   Yet the opposition, most notably dissident Cuauhtemoc Cardenas
of the coalition Democratic National Front and Manuel J. Clouthier
of the conservative National Action Party, have generated an
unusual amount of attention through the long campaign.
   Mexico simply is no longer the largely rural nation in which the
PRI was formed to resolve the chaos lingering from the Mexican
Revolution of 1910-21.
   Now with more than 80 million inhabitants and the world's 13th
largest economy, Mexico is characterized more by offshore oil
platforms and teeming cities than the old stereotypes of ``charro''
hats and guitars still snapped up by foreign tourists.
   There is little doubt that a certain amount of repression and
vote fraud played some part in PRI control over the decades, but
the party also became a master at the art of consensus. It held out
that the ``social peace'' was being conserved, and an expanding
economy always was able to provide hope for the growing population.
   An old saying has it that the government first tried to make
friends with everyone. If that didn't work, it tried to buy you
off. And in the few cases where neither approach worked, it killed
you.
   The stress on that longstanding, pragmatic system increased in
1982, when international prices started falling for the petroleum
exports that had brought in unmatched prosperity for the previous
five years.
   ``La crisis'' _ ``the crisis'' _ has lasted throughout de la
Madrid's six-year term, causing a drop by some estimates of as much
as 50 percent in consumers' purchasing power and fraying the
patience of millions of Mexicans forced to make corresponding
cutbacks.
   A one-peso coin, worth about 4 cents just seven years ago, now
is negligible. New coins have been issued for 1,000 pesos, now
worth some 40 cents.
   ``The crisis reveals the incredible banality of the bourgeoisie
in power,'' wrote Carlos Monsivais, a leading essayist.
   Among the results he observed is ``the omnipresent idea of the
failure of the official nation.''
   Mexico City these days, except in its most luxurious
neighborhoods, has taken on a tattered, run-down look. Only part of
the cause is lingering damage from the devastating earthquake of
Sept. 19, 1985. Repairs and appearances generally are pushed back
for more pressing needs.
   Cars, taxis and trucks purchased during the oil boom years are
still on the streets _ some of them just barely. The number of
street vendors, entertainers and beggars has proliferated.
   The debate about the causes of the crisis and the ways to
resolve it has spilled most noticeably into Mexican cultural life.
   ``In this period marked by survival, popular nationalism is
expressed as anti-governmental malice, lack of confidence ...
cynicism and skepticism about the national future,'' Monsivais
wrote.
   Salinas de Gortari focused one of his campaign forums on
``Culture and National Identity,'' where he said: ``Mexican culture
is so strong that it is what is going to allow us to remain as an
independent nation.''
   ``The PRI has made national identity its own,'' poet, novelist
and ecological activist Homero Aridjis said. ``They've created a
symbiosis of the country with the governing system.''
   As a result, he said in an interview, those who criticize the
government often have been accused of attacking Mexico.
   Recent campaigns to whip up enthusiasm, especially on the
private Televisa broadcast network that pervades Mexico, have
focused on such national symbols as the red, white and green colors
that are shared by the country and the PRI.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880620-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1438EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--MexicoElections Adv03-1stAdd   06-20 0851</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Mexico Elections, Adv 03-1st Add,0881</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
<HEAD>MEXICO CITY: the PRI.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``People are tired of being manipulated,'' Aridjis said.
``People are less stupid than the government believes.''
   Even those who criticize the government most sharply refer to
the tremendous reservoir of Mexican culture that provides a base
for the nation.
   ``It has a solidity comparable to that of the old Oriental
cultures,'' Enrique Krauze, managing editor of the magazine Vuelta,
said at Salinas de Gortari's campaign forum. ``The profound Mexican
culture doesn't need to be defended from anyone other than its
defenders.''
   Vuelta was founded by Octavio Paz, the poet and essayist whose
``The Labyrinth of Solitude'' remains a key work in the search for
Mexican identity.
   The raw material for Mexican nationalism and culture runs deep,
far beyond the red, white and green.
   Each Sept. 15, 1 million Mexicans crowd the Zocalo plaza in
downtown Mexico City to commemorate the ``grito'' or shout of
independence in 1810.
   Just off the plaza, the ruins of the Aztec Indians' Great Temple
have been uncovered. The artifacts found there are on display in a
newly opened, magnificent museum.
   On Dec. 12 each year, hundreds of thousands of faithful visit
the Basilica of Our Lady of Guadalupe, the revered Roman Catholic
patron saint of Mexico whose image is found everywhere from
construction sites to the bedrooms of the wealthy.
   ``The PRI, Televisa and the (Catholic) church are the great
manipulators,'' Roberto Marquez, a 27-year-old artist who moved to
Phoenix, Ariz., three years ago, said in an interview.
   He said, however, that living abroad has given him a new
appreciation of the complexity of Mexico.
   ``I think that this is a moment of change, because the Mexican
Revolution already happened 60 years ago,'' Marquez said. ``Now,
the Mexican reality is something else. We can't keep on in the same
way.''
   ``In Mexico right now there's great skepticism, very strong
pessimism,'' said Luis Mandoki, the young director of the Academy
Award-nominated movie ``Gaby: A True Story.''
   He said that frustration among many Mexicans has not been able
to find an outlet because of the lack of organization among the
opposition.
   Others are milder in their evaluations.
   Philosopher Leopoldo Zea said resentment of the government's
inability to confront the economic crisis has not become
generalized anti-government feeling.
   He attributed that in part to the stoic nature often attributed
to the Mexican people, referring to a saying: ``The Indian gets
angry every 100 years, but when he gets angry, he gets really
angry.''
   The myths of modern Mexico blend the Indian and colonial Spanish
heritages into the mestizo, demonstrated in the Plaza of Three
Cultures that showcases Indian ruins, a colonial church and a
modern office tower.
   Reality also can include substantial racial and class
differences.
   Guadalupe Loaeza, a witty chronicler of the upper class, has
published her collected columns as ``Rich Girls.''
   She wrote that a wealthy woman who once traveled six times to
San Diego or Europe each year now goes just four times and
believes: ``How good that the peso was devalued, because now the
lines of `nacos' won't be as long for skiing.''
   ``Naco'' is the epithet for low class.
   The PRI traditionally has had its base in the working and
peasant classes, increasingly more open to modern ideas through the
spread of television and hit especially hard by the crisis.
   ``It's up in the air,'' Rafael Segovia, former director of the
prestigious Colegio de Mexico research institution, said in an
interview. ``Being Mexican has no other condition than being
Mexican. You don't have to paint like Diego Rivera.''
   Rivera and other artists earlier in this century turned to
``Mexican-ness,'' a search for identity in the supposedly pure
Indian roots of the nation.
   Most contemporary artists look elsewhere for images, however.
   ``It's certainly not the reality of the cities, not Mexico
City,'' said Marquez, the young artist.
   There may be too many different regions, classes and other
factors at work for modern Mexico to be summed up simply.
   ``There's a new search in light of what's happening,'' said
Arturo Azuela, a novelist and director of the school of philosophy
and letters at the National University of Mexico. ``I think that a
crucial work is going to come out very soon.''
   His father, Mariano Azuela, wrote ``The Underdogs,'' one of the
most famous novels about the Mexican Revolution.
   The opponents of the PRI say it has outlived its usefulness and
now is a creation addicted to power and bloated by corruption.
   Guadalupe Robles Romero, a 36-year-old administrator in the
government's Social Security Institute, walked into Cardenas'
offices last fall and now is a candidate for city assemblywoman in
her first experience in politics.
   ``I think that there's going to be change,'' she said. ``And not
in the long run _ in the short run.''
   The PRI has surprised in the past by displaying an astonishing
ability to adapt to the needs of the times. Salinas de Gortari and
his supporters say they can muster the necessary changes this time.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
