<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1442EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv03   06-20 0899</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 03,0919</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv03</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was the thorniest dilemma of the 1988 Tony
Awards:
   Three little-known but accomplished actresses with names that
sound confusingly similar _ Kimberleigh Aarn, Kimberly Scott and L.
Scott Caldwell.
   All three were from the same Broadway play, and all three were
nominated for a Tony in the same category. Their competition was
the talented and much better known performer, Kate Nelligan. But
when the winner was announced last month, it was L. Scott Caldwell,
taking the prize for best featured actress in a play.
   ``This is going to sound funny, but a part of me expected to
win,'' says Caldwell, pointing to her heart. ``In my head I didn't
think about it much because when I intellectualized it, I thought
`Well, the Tony voters might get mixed up about who's who and Kate
Nelligan is an established actress.'''
   In her Tony acceptance speech, the actress first thanked her
mother, brothers and sister back in Chicago.
   ``Because I was interested in the theater, they were,'' she
says. ``I converted them in a way, but they have always pushed me,
saying `You can do it.'''
   The interest was born in Chicago when Caldwell was 8 years old
and spent every afternoon in a South Side movie theater where a
friend of her mother's worked as a cleaning lady. For almost a
year, her baby sitters were stars like Joan Crawford, Bette Davis
and Loretta Young up on that big screen.
   ``I think that's how it kind of got to me,'' Caldwell recalls.
``I didn't say to myself `I want to be an actress' or anything like
that. But I loved film, and I loved what they did.''
   What they did was what she wanted to do, but it took a while for
her to realize that ambition to act. Her persistence paid off last
month when Caldwell picked up that Tony for her performance in
``Joe Turner's Come and Gone'' by August Wilson.
   The play, now on view at Broadway's Ethel Barrymore Theater, is
one in a series of works by Wilson chronicling the black experience
in America during the 20th century. Wilson plans one play for each
decade. So far, ``Ma Rainey's Black Bottom,'' ``Fences'' and ``Joe
Turner'' have made it to Broadway, and a fourth, ``The Piano
Lesson,'' is a possibility for next spring.
   ``Joe Turner'' is set in a Pittsburgh boarding house in 1911 and
concerns the children of slaves coming to terms with their past and
present. Each character searches for what Wilson refers to in the
play as their ``song.''
   In ``Joe Turner,'' Caldwell plays Bertha Holly, the patient,
practical wife of the boarding house owner. It's a role, she says,
that has softened her own, less optimistic view of life.
   ``I think it was a happy accident that I got this role because
I'm a cynical person,'' the actress says. ``I don't have a real
rosy view of the world. It's kind of cautiously optimistic. Bertha
is just positive through-and-through. It balances me out to play a
woman who doesn't have any question about who she is and about
life.''
   For Caldwell, the idea of becoming an actress didn't crystalize
until she was in high school and saw a production of Douglas Turner
Ward's ``Day of Absence'' at the Hyde Park Theater.
   ``It was the first time I saw black people on stage,'' she
recalls, ``and I thought `I could be up there.'''
   Her family didn't have the money to send her to drama school, so
Caldwell went to work as a telephone operator. She got married, had
a son and decided to go to college, majoring in communications and
theater at Loyola in Chicago.
   Her obsession with the theater grew when she saw Uta Hagen
discuss her acting school on a television talk show. Caldwell sent
for an application to HB Studios, the school Hagen runs with her
husband, and was told she would have to come to New York for an
audition.
   With her husband's approval, Caldwell came to New York in 1979
for what she thought would be a two-month visit. She ended up
staying, getting into Hagen's acting class as well as the Negro
Ensemble Company, run by Douglas Turner Ward.
   Caldwell made the difficult commitment to remain in New York.
Her marriage ended, and she sent her son, Ominara, back to Chicago
to live with his father. The boy, now 15, also was singled out for
special praise in Caldwell's Tony acceptance speech.
   But her professional career kept going forward. The job with the
Negro Ensemble Company blossomed into a role on Broadway when the
company's production of ``Home'' moved to the big time. Since then,
she has worked steadily in regional theater, soap operas and
commercials. Now ``Joe Turner'' has finally given her recognition
in the New York theater community.
   ``I'm very proud of the work I've done in `Joe Turner,'''
Caldwell says. ``I'm extremely proud of it because I feel the role
wasn't all there on paper. I felt I was able to give the character
three dimensions and I'm very, very happy about that.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 13</NOTE>
