<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Afghanistan-Rebels Adv26   06-20 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Afghanistan-Rebels, Adv 26,0457</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Afghanistan _ Rebels Diverse but United, for Now</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a package of three stories.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although they put up a united front,
the leaders of Afghanistan's Moslem insurgents _ the mujahedeen
(holy warriors) _ are a diverse group.
   What unites them is a common belief in Islam and a determination
to crush the Marxists who run Afghanistan's government in Kabul.
   The seven-party mujahedeen alliance is mainly an arms conduit to
guerrillas fighting the Soviet and Afghan armies inside
Afghanistan. It also is an identifiable organization with which the
international community can deal.
   Here is a rundown of the leaders and groups:
   _Sibghatullah Mojadeddi, head of the Afghan National Liberation
Front, recently claimed his group would be among the strongest if
he received his fair slice of the supply pie.
   _The most visible and contentious of leaders is Gulbaddin
Hekmatyar, chief of the Hezb-i-Islami fighters and current chairman
of the alliance. The radical wing accuses him of of murder, theft
and fanning party rivalry. Still, Hezb-i-Islami has been a major
recipient of U.S., Chinese and Saudi Arabian arms.
   _A target of Hekmatyar's antagonism has been the
Jamiat-i-Islami, another fervent Moslem group but considered to be
one of the best military organizations. Its leader is the venerable
Professor Burhanuddin Rabbani, a Tajik, but the majority of Afghans
are Pathans like Hekmatyar.
   _Maulvi Yunis Khalis, the red-beareded, barrel-chested leader of
a faction that split off from Hekmatyar, is often called the
fighting mullah. He abruptly resigned as alliance chairman in
March. A month later, he was back fighting in Afghanistan.
   _The lightweight party on the radical wing is Abdul Rasul
Sayyaf's Ittehad-i-Islami. However, it spawned Ahmad Shah, newly
appointed president of an all-mujahedeen government.
   _Moderates also claim to be devout Moslems but are known for
their Western manners and tastes. They are Syed Ahmed Gailani's
National Islamic Front of Afghanistan, Maulvi Nabi Mohammadi's
Harakat Party and Mojadeddi's Nifa. All three are considered small
although Mojadeddi reportedly got an increase in arms supplies
recently when he resigned from the alliance then rejoined.
   Despite the differences and diversities, the insurgent military
strategies are increasingly more coordinated and the mujahedeen
have moved into several abandoned bases in Afghanistan without
infighting.
   The alliance maintains there will be no armed power play in
postwar Afghanistan.
   Perhaps a more reliable barometer is the man in the field. Many
guerrillas say they are prepared to die fighting the Marxist
government, but they will not fight for a political leader who
seeks only power.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
