<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Afghanistan-Border Adv26   06-20 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Afghanistan-Border, Adv 26,0349</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Afghanistan _ The Pashans, a Tribe Inseparable</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a package of three stories.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORKHAM, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The inscription chiseled in 1948 on the
turret-like gates separating Pakistan and Afghanistan reads: ``We
are brothers. No power on earth can separate us.''
   Not even the coils of barbed wire slumped along the border fence
like tumbleweed.
   ``Najib has made that, I have not,'' says one of three Afghan
soldiers peering through steel bars into Pakistan.
   Najib is the current leader of Afghanistan's Marxist government,
which has been fighting a guerrilla war with Pakistan-based Islamic
insurgents.
   The border bisects this village of 1,000 people in a valley of
the famed Khyber Pass through which the armies of Alexander the
Great, Genghis Khan and Great Britain marched in search of riches
in the East.
   People on each side live under different flags but consider
themselves Pathans, the ethnic majority of Afghanistan and
northwest Pakistan.
   They believe in the inscription on the gate, not the barricade.
   Most of the Afghan-Pakistani border is tribal territory and a
political no-man's land.
   The law is laid down by tribal chiefs like Nader Khan, leader of
the Afridi Pathan tribe.
   ``We may seem two different people but we are actually the
same,'' he said at his home on the Pakistan side.
   Khan says his people support the Afghan guerrillas, most of whom
also are Pathans. He says tribal members who have been found to be
aiding the Kabul government have been punished under tribal law.
   ``We have burned their homes down,'' he said.
   Najib is a Pathan and former acquaintance of Khan's, but now
they are enemies _ to a point.
   As Khan says, if Najib must flee Kabul he could come home to his
tribal area and feel safe.
   The Pathan code of ethics demands that.
   ``He can come,'' said the chief.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
