<DOCNO> AP880620-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 2143EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   06-20 1017</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,1055</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty years ago, George Romero probably didn't
envision that his modest little horror movie, ``Night of the Living
Dead,'' would mutate into decades of celluloid zombies.
   But the dead rose again and again until Ken Wiederhorn's recent
``Return of the Living Dead, Part II,'' which Lorimar Home Video
has released. But unlike Romero's heroic scare effort in which
radiation turns corpses into killers, the latest work is a
mindless, boring tale about a green vapor that turns the living
into zombies who love to eat brains.
   Since the ``Living Dead'' movies have a cult following, Lorimar
is spicing up its release with a toll-free telephone number which
will enable viewers to order wearables including tank tops,
T-shirts and sweartshirts.
   The R-rated video on VHS and Beta retails for $89.95.
   Other home video companies also have commercial or merchandising
tie-ins.
   Walt Disney Home Video is sponsoring a sweepstakes with its
release of ``Benji the Hunted.'' The prize is a trip for four to
Walt Disney World for four days and three nights, plus $1,000. All
viewers have to do is answer two trivia questions about ``Benji''
and fill out an entry form, which will be available at video stores.
   MCA Home Video is offering a rebate for ``E.T. The
Extra-Terrestrial,'' which will retail for $24.95, for those
viewers who buy Pepsi products and mail in the proof of purchase.
   Another sweepstakes is being offered with the release of this
year's Academy Award-winner, ``The Last Emperor,'' which will be
available to home viewers from Nelson Entertainment on Aug. 31. The
movie, which won nine Oscars, will retail for $89.98.
   The radio promotion sweepstakes for ``The Last Emperor'' offers
a grand prize of a trip to Hong Kong and the Forbidden City in
China.
   Videos reviewed this week: ``Suspect'' and ``Citizens Band.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Suspect'' (RCA-Columbia Home Video; VHS-Beta, $89.95; Rated R)
   
   ``Suspect'' begins with seemingly unconnected events: A Supreme
Court justice blows his brains out; a woman's body is found lying
in the Potomac River, the victim, apparently, of vagrants.
   These are the raw _ in every sense of the word _ ingredients of
this surprisingly droll, diverting whodunit based in Washington
that takes a few choice pokes at politics along the way.
   It may even remind you of the real-life Watergate break-in. That
was no ordinary burglary. This is no ordinary murder.
   Some advice to viewers, without giving away the ending: Suspect
everyone. Everyone.
   Cher plays Kathleen Riley, a somewhat world-weary public
defender with an interesting touch of diffidence. She is assigned
to defend a violence-prone deaf vagrant who is accused of the
murder.
   Along comes Eddie Sanger, a Washington milk lobbyist played with
convincing sleaze by Dennis Quaid. Sanger gets named to the jury on
thismurder case. Sanger, apparently wiser in the ways and wiles of
official Washington, senses that the deaf defendant may be the fall
guy for some very powerful villains.
   He starts playing detective and feeds Cher the clues that nearly
get them both killed, but which ultimately solve the crime.
   All right, all right _ it's jury tampering, but let's not be
picky.
   The end of ``Suspect,'' written by Eric Roth and directed by
Peter Yates, is somewhat disappointing. We'd have respected Cher
much more if she didn't melt with a girlish giggle into the arms of
Quaid.
   And the body of the dead woman is so obviously a dummy that you
want to ask the studio why they were too cheap to arrange for a
halfway convincing corpus delicti.
   _ By Lee Mitgang, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Citizens Band'' (Paramount Home Video; VHS, $59.95; Rated PG)
   
   ``Citizens Band,'' released in 1977 when the CB radio craze was
at its height, is one of few American films of recent years that
may rank with the screwball comedies of the 1930s or Frank Capra's
whimsical slices of Americana.
   Set in a small town, this gently funny movie brings to life a
rich and diverse assortment of characters, including a
down-on-her-luck prostitute, an embittered high school basketball
coach and a bigamous long-haul truck driver _ all of whom rely
heavily on their citizens band radios to relate to the outside
world.
   The hero, known by his CB ``handle'' of Spider, is a radio
repairman trying to cope with his brother, his ex-girl friend and
his aging father, a retired trucker who keeps threatening to eat
the family dog. Spider, played by Paul Le Mat, becomes a sort of
airwaves vigilante, tracking down the many eccentrics in the
community who use their CBs for illicit purposes or rudely cross
into other people's channels.
   Screenwriter Paul Brickman (who later wrote and directed ``Risky
Business'') and director Jonathan Demme (``Melvin and Howard'' and
``Something Wild'') brilliantly weave this zany assortment of
characters into a cohesive plot.
   But they do even more _ the citizens band radio becomes a
metaphor for the alienation and self-deception that are part of the
modern human condition. And when the characters overcome their
confusions and misunderstandings and break through their isolation,
the result is an ending that's not just happy, but joyous.
   In a truly ensemble cast, all the performers are first-rate.
Perhaps deserving special mention are Roberts Blossom, as Spider's
crotchety father, and Marcia Rodd and Ann Wedgeworth as the
trucker's wives who discover they are married to the same man and
resolve their predicament with amazing good humor and aplomb.
   _ By Mike Silverman, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
