<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   06-20 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0604</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Mona Lisa's Sister'' (RCA) _ Graham Parker
   
   It's only the second verse of the first song on ``The Mona
Lisa's Sister'' when Graham Parker lets fly against one of his pet
peeves.
   ``Some people are in charge of pens,'' he spits. ``That
shouldn't be in charge of brooms. They have the nerve to rip up a
man's life in a paragraph or two.''
   Lighten up, Graham. We like you. And we like your album.
   Parker, a soulful British rocker, burns with an intensity you
can see through sunglasses. He bitterly left two record companies
when they didn't make him the star he, and others, thought he
should be.
   ``The Mona Lisa's Sister,'' is his 10th album and one of his
best. Parker has stripped down his music, with an acoustic guitar
the anchor instead of his rollicking former backup band, the
Rumour. It's a smart move, since the songs lose nothing in power
and Parker's strong melodies are accented.
   All this would mean little, of course, if the songs weren't
there, and this is Parker's strongest collection since 1979's
``Squeezing Out Sparks.''
   Parker has a keen eye for injustices of any sort, and along with
critics, he takes apart polluters, big defense spenders,
hypocritical yuppies, girls who grow up too fast and shallow
successes.
   ``Somebody's pouring salt on a wound,'' he sings in ``OK
Hieronymus.'' ``Scooping out monkey's brains with a spoon. Working
up warfare on the moon, that's just the latest phase. We just want
to curl up and die.''
   Fortunately, Parker's world view is not entirely negative. On
the fine ballad, ``Blue Highways,'' he recognizes there's a better
America beyond what he doesn't like on the surface.
   And the album closes with a gorgeous version of Sam Cooke's
``Cupid.'' The idea isn't new, but rarely has the sense of love as
a salvation been carried out so well on a record.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Aliens Ate My Buick'' (EMI-Manhattan) _ Thomas Dolby
   
   Thomas Dolby's new album secures him a place next to Howard
Jones as the best of the synthmeisters.
   Dolby might cringe at that label, because synthesizers are often
associated with droning, shallow music, and ``Aliens Ate My Buick''
is anything but that. Instead it's hip, witty, intelligent and
highly musical.
   It doesn't take long for Dolby to hit high gear on the opening
cut, ``The Key to Her Ferrari.'' After an introductory voiceover by
Robin Leach, Dolby sings, ``I don't want your love; I don't want
your money; I just want the key to your Ferrari.'' The record's
tone is set.
   Other highlights include ``My Brain Is Like a Sieve,'' which
along with a great title features a beguiling melody; ``Hot
Sauce,'' a George Clinton composition that will steam up any dance
floor with its groove and lyrics; and ``Airhead,'' in which Dolby
sings about a woman friend:
   ``She's an airhead: stun gun and mace; Kharmann Ghia plates say
`Lost in Space.'''
   Dolby sings in French and Latin, impersonates a Jamaican and
calls on actor Ed Asner for a cameo. Searing guitar breaks, snappy
bass lines and even a trombone help keep the synthesizers in their
place. The artist's name notwithstanding, there's no need for noise
reduction on ``Aliens Ate My Buick.''
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
