<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Director Martin Sheen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Not content with being a ``hired hand'' as
well as head of an acting dynasty, Martin Sheen has taken the leap
into the treacherous world of film production.
   The chairman of the board of Symphony Pictures is proud of two
current films he fostered: ``Judgment in Berlin,'' a Cold War
adventure and courtroom drama; and ``Da,'' based on the hit play by
Hugh Leonard. Sheen stars in both movies and also served as
executive producer for the projects.
   ``I had wanted for a very long time to be more than a hired
hand,'' he said. ``I wanted to have more say in the choice of
material from start to finish and to realize a personal vision. I
think most actors who want a long career feel that way.
   ``This presented an opportunity to pursue that intention _
basically not to be at the whim of a producer or a project because
of financial or professional need. I can't think of a television or
theatrical movie or a play that I didn't want to project some
personal change into. It becomes very frustrating because you're
always at the mercy of the director, the editor or whoever.''
   Both new films were hard sells. ``Judgment in Berlin,'' based on
the book by Judge Herbert J. Stern, combined a plane hijacking and
a court case. Sheen and his partner, William Greeblatt, could find
no company for the project until they uttered the magic words: Sean
Penn. The hot young actor agreed to play a small but vital role in
the movie because his father, Leo Penn, was directing. New Line
Cinema agreed to finance the film.
   ``When Sean came into the picture, in large measure to support
his father, he had a supporting, not a starring role,'' Sheen said.
``For him to have shown so much respect for his father and to risk
a measure of his own career, we owed him a huge debt of gratitude.''
   Sheen, who is half Irish, fell in love with ``Da'' when he first
saw the play 10 years ago. It tells of a New York playwright who
returns to his native Ireland to bury his father. But the old man
returns to life in the son's memory to relive their troubled lives
together. The play won a Tony award for the veteran American actor,
Barnard Hughes, who also stars in the movie version.
   ``Bill (Greenblatt) and I were flabbergasted when we tried to
acquire the rights for `Da' and found them available,'' Sheen said.
``We were told by Bill Leonard that there had been an arduous
journey for many people who had tried to get the screen version
made.
   ``We couldn't get anyone interested, not even a network; we
would have settled for getting a television presentation done. We
were told: `Nothing really happens _ no car chases, no violence, no
sex, nothing to attract a modern audience.' We believed there was
an audience for a show that came from the heart, a show about human
relationships.''
   FilmDallas agreed to sponsor ``Da,'' and Matt Clark directed it
on locations in Ireland.
   Production companies can sometimes seem like ego trips for
actors. That doesn't appear to be the case with Sheen. While he has
been praised for his solid competence, reviewers have lavished
praise on Penn in ``Judgment at Berlin,'' and on Hughes in ``Da.''
That doesn't bother Sheen.
   ``I always want to work with the very best talents available,''
he said. ``I couldn't be happier than to have had the opportunity
to work with these two extraordinary actors. I say that as a fellow
actor, but also as a producer.''
   Martin Sheen was born Ramon Estevez 47 years ago in Dayton,
Ohio, one of 10 children of a Spanish father and Irish mother. He
left Dayton after high school to study acting in New York, and he
changed his name to Martin Sheen. The play and movie of ``The
Subject Was Roses'' brought him to prominence, and he has been
working ever since, always at others' bidding _ until now.
   Symphony Pictures has a heavy schedule ahead, including ``Out of
Control'' with Al Pacino; ``Illusions,'' based on the Richard and
Leslie Bach book; plus a number of TV projects. Several have social
implications, expectably from political activist Sheen.
   What about hiring his own clan, which includes actors Charlie
Sheen and Emilio Estevez?
   ``In fact, Charlie was supposed to play a younger version of me
in `Da,''' said Sheen. ``But our production was delayed, and
Charlie had to take another project. Then we tried Emilio 10 days
before shooting in Dublin, but it was too short a time and he
couldn't make it. So we went with a young Irish actor and made a
discovery with Karl Hayden.
   ``I'm getting ready to direct my first film, and Charlie is the
star. And I know very well that the major reason I'm allowed to
direct it is because of Charlie. The three of us, as well as my
son, Ramon, and daughter, Renee, have worked together on a lot of
projects, and I'm sure we'll do more down the road.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 1-3 and</NOTE>
