<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Benita Valente Wants Documentation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lyric soprano Benita Valente gets the kind of
reviews for ravishing tone and precise yet effortless delivery that
superstars usually receive.
   But her name is not a household word. Still, she's philosophical
about it.
   ``I've had a wonderful life and most wonderful career,'' she
said. ``I've done most of the things I want to do, worked with
wonderful people mostly, done good repertory and made good music.
That's all so satisfying.
   ``I've been able to live a life, got married, had my child. My
career would never have been as good if I hadn't gotten married. I
think one needs to live a full life.''
   She was in Paris in June to sing in Brahms' ``Requiem'' with the
Orchestra of Paris. Since 1984, she has been been making recordings
``fast and furious'' _ lieder, Christmas music with the
Philadelphia Singers, Beethoven's ``Ninth Symphony'' with the
Atlanta Symphony, Haydn's ``Seven Last Words of Christ'' with the
Juilliard String Quartet.
   She also had one big, splashy triumph at the Metropolitan Opera
in 1983 in Handel's ``Rinaldo.'' It was a decade after she had made
her Met debut.
   ``Most of the things I've been involved in, I've had a really
good time,'' she said in an interview. ``I like to work with good
people. I like to be creative and work off other people. Doing
opera is my favorite thing because I have a lot of company.
   ``I love the recital repertory. It's the most lonely of the work
I do. On last fall's recital tour I took my son, Peter, with me; he
took a semester off from Marlboro College in Vermont. We had such a
ball.''
   Miss Valente, who a native of Delano, Calif., was shy as a child.
   ``I can remember dressing up the cats in dolls' clothes,'' she
said. ``I much preferred to play with animals. I decided to be a
singer when I was about 3. We had a huge radio. I'd switch the
dials. I figured out Saturday afternoon was the Met broadcast. I
was fascinated by that kind of sound and I could imitate it. My
father had Caruso records. I knew the tenor arias when I got to the
Curtis Institute of Music. Then I had to learn my own repertory.
   ``Music drew me out of myself,'' she said. ``I couldn't sing in
front of my family. I could sing in the next room. I found my
outlet was being expressive on the stage.''
   Her high school music teacher, Chester Hayden, taught her stage
deportment, and how to dress and groom herself. He sent her to
audition for coaching by Lotte Lehmann and for Curtis.
   ``Curtis had seven openings and I got in. The only advice he
gave me I didn't take was to marry for money,'' she said. ``I've
got a bassoonist husband who thinks he's a manager.''
   Miss Valente met her husband, Anthony Checchia, at Curtis.
They've been married for 28 years.
   ``Tony was contracting for orchestras. All my instrumentalist
friends knew him. A cellist had been saying for months we should
meet. I was always very shy about matchmaking. I would have nothing
to do with it. We met by chance. It crossed my mind, `Wouldn't it
be strange if I marry this man.' I never thought that about another
person.
   ``He's first generation Italian. I'm first generation Italian
(father) and Swiss (mother). So many of my family look Spanish. I
always have the feeling somebody wandered over from Spain.''
   ``Rinaldo'' at the Metropolitan Opera was a gift from the
Canadian government for the Bicentennial. The production was put
together and performed first in Ottawa.
   ``Marilyn Horne went to bat for (bass) Sam Ramey and me,
although I had been singing at the Met already,'' Miss Valente said.
   ``We sold out every night and people were clamoring to get in.
The Met never repeated it. We always had the feeling they felt like
`Rinaldo' was pushed down their throats. They acted like we didn't
exist, Marilyn included.''
   The best of the ecstatic reviews were for Ramey and Miss
Valente. Did it make a difference in her career? ``It wasn't a
stepping-stone to getting any further at the Met. It could have
been a detriment. I've been back to do `Idomeneo.'
   ``I'm virtually unknown in Italy; I spent 25 years becoming an
American singer,'' she said. ``The Met `Rinaldo' did lead to
singing in `Rinaldo' in a tour of northern houses in Italy. I sang
in Handel's `Samson' in Florence, and conductor Riccardo Muti's
wife heard me and told him how good I was. I work with him now and
he always says his wife heard me first.
   ``I always do a lot of solo recitals, orchestra dates and
chamber music. I sang at a tribute to Lotte Lehmann at the Y in New
York in February. I usually sing with the Handel Society in
Washington. I sang in Handel's `Ariodante' with Tatiana Troyanos
last summer at the Santa Fe Opera. This summer, Tatiana and I are
going to start doing some duo concerts.''
   As for recordings, she says, ``If you're getting singing jobs,
you think they'll come. But you have to set the time aside for
them, deliberately.
   ``I never took the time before. Now I feel that I should be
documented.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, July 1-3</NOTE>
