<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Even the Red Army Likes Heavy Metal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Army's defenses crumbled in the face of
an onslaught of heavy metal music by the West German band Scorpions.
   Not only did security forces relax restrictions so fans could
stand in front of the stage, but the Red Army joined in the
applause at the Leningrad concerts, billed as the first by a major
hard rock band in the Soviet Union.
   ``Every face was saying, `Oh, it's so great,''' lead singer
Klaus Meine said. ``Even the soldiers _ they threw their caps onto
the stage.''
   Meine, who was recently in Miami with the rest of the Scorpions
for a concert to launch their U.S. tour, smiled as he recalled the
band's 10 shows in Leningrad in late April. He said Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev's new policies of ``glasnost'' that permit a more
open society made the shows possible.
   ``Musicians there told us this wouldn't have happened one year
ago,'' Meine said. ``But now you have the feeling that you can talk
to everybody about everything.''
   The concerts at the Lenin Sports Concert Complex confirmed the
worldwide popularity of the Scorpions, who have played in such
distant locales as Brazil and Thailand. Every show drew a sell-out
crowd of 15,000.
   ``We thought they were crazy to hold 10 shows in one place,''
bassist Francis Buchholz said. ``I thought by the last show we
would have three people. But people flew in from everywhere, from
Siberia to Moscow.''
   Pop music artists such as Billy Joel have performed in the
Soviet Union, but until recently heavy metal was an underground
genre.
   ``We went into a record store and tried to get some rock music,
and they didn't know what it was,'' Buchholz said.
   He said the Scorpions, whose five members grew up within 100
miles of the Berlin Wall, initially had Soviet authorities nervous.
But the well-mannered band, which relies on catchy melodies rather
than bluster to sell records, wasn't interested in inciting a
rebellion.
   ``Our music is not that aggressive,'' Buchholz said. ``Our
audience doesn't carry chains and knives and stab each other. The
audience is like the music we have _ it's positive.
   ``Drugs are out anyway now. Sex is questionable. So we try to
put some messages into our music.''
   For the Leningrad concerts, Meine and guitarist Rudolf Schenker
composed a new song called ``Living for Tomorrow,'' which is about
taking a chance to improve things. Meine, who sings in English,
introduced the tune at each show by reading the lyrics in Russian:
   ``Evil power won't kill the human race;
   ``If we give life a human face.''
   Buchholz said: ``The audience loved it.''
   The Scorpions, whose new album, ``Savage Amusement,'' is in the
Top 10 in the United States, are now part of the five-band, 25-city
Monsters of Rock tour headlined by Van Halen. The bands performed
at the Orange Bowl on June 4.
   ``We have no problem playing under Van Halen. We respect each
other. It's a great band,'' Meine said. ``At the end of the day we
blow each other off the stage with a smile. ... It's a great way to
come back to America.''
   The group's last studio LP, ``Love at First Sting,'' sold more
than 4 million copies worldwide. The 1985 double LP, ``Worldwide
Live,'' was also a big seller. The Scorpions have had one
double-platinum, two platinum and two gold albums in the United
States, and no other continental European band has approached that
level of sales. Albums are deemed gold when they've sold 500,000
copies, including cassettes and compact discs. Platinum means 1
million copies have been sold.
   Composers Meine and Schenker met in Hanover, Germany, while
practicing with separate bands, and formed the Scorpions in 1972.
When they first appeared in a Hanover band contest, they were
disqualified for being too loud.
   Buchholz joined in 1973, drummer Herman Rarebell in 1977 and
guitarist Matthias Jabs in 1979.
   The theme of physical sexuality has dominated the Scorpions'
album titles and cover art. Their dense sound is built around
Meine's soaring voice and Schenker's piercing guitar lines.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 1-3</NOTE>
</DOC>
