<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--CivilRightsSlayings Adv01-03   06-20 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Civil Rights Slayings, Adv 01-03,0775</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, July 1-3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: Schwerner, Goodman and Chaney Remembered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Their names were Michael Schwerner, Andrew
Goodman and James Chaney.
   They died at the hands of the Ku Klux Klan in a rural section of
Mississippi 24 years ago, their bodies bulldozed beneath a dam.
   The names may no longer bring instant recognition or raise angry
hackles. But the deaths of Schwerner, Goodman and Chaney _ two
whites from New York and a black from Meridian, Miss. _ affect
American policies today, the authors of a new book on the civil
rights movement say.
   ``This was a slaying with profound political implications. This
wasn't a psychopath running amok, although several psychopaths were
involved,'' said Seth Cagin, co-author of ``We Are Not Afraid''
(The MacMillan Co., $22.50), a history of the civil rights movement
which hinges on the Neshoba County slayings.
   ``We were interested in this because it changed America,'' Cagin
continued. ``You could draw a line _ and I don't think you would be
too far off _ from the early civil rights movement through the
killings of Schwerner, Goodman and Chaney through voting rights for
blacks through Martin Luther King to the campaign of Jesse Jackson
today.''
   The book is the result of 3{ years of interviews, Freedom of
Information requests and vast research into the Mississippi Summer
Project, which sent more than 1,000 northern whites into the South
to fight for civil rights.
   ``We wanted to do a story about young people. And the last time
young Americans were willing to risk their lives for something they
believed in was the civil rights movement,'' said Cagin. ``It's
difficult to think of any cause today that people would risk their
lives for.''
   Or give their lives for.
   The three men were shot to death on June 21, 1964; their bodies
were found 44 days later following an intense federal probe which
drew national attention to the civil rights battle.
   When Schwerner and Goodman left New York for Mississippi, they
were well aware of such risks _ another factor which made the story
intriguing to Cagin and co-author Philip Dray, who were barely in
their teens at the time.
   ``That idea _ what made them do it _ is really the germ of our
book,'' said Cagin. ``It was incredible to us. What would make
people travel down there, knowing what was going to happen? I mean,
if we had the opportunity, would we get on a Greyhound bus and go
down to get our heads busted?''
   In the course of their research, Cagin and Dray encountered many
veterans of the civil rights battles, as well as the families of
all three victims.
   ``A lot of the movement veterans are like war veterans. There's
a certain patina about them _ some are chain smokers, some are
heavy drinkers _ that makes them stand out,'' Dray said.
   ``Some of them suffer like war veterans,'' agreed Cagin. ``Like
Vietnam veterans, no one remembers what they did. Their sacrifices
are unrecognized, and they feel unfulfilled, their work unfinished
... But the people who think they failed really succeeded.''
   The families carried the scars as well, they said.
   ``In all three families, it was like this had occurred last
week. The pain was very fresh,'' Cagin said.
   When he met with John Chaney's mother, Dray learned first-hand
how fresh the pain remains.
   ``I was interviewing Mrs. Chaney, and she started saying she
didn't know if that was her son, she wasn't sure because she had
never seen him after (the bodies were found),'' Dray recalled.
``She broke down crying ... I had always accepted his death as
historical fact, and here she was saying maybe he isn't dead.''
   While the book _ which was edited by Edward T. Chase, father of
comedian Chevy Chase _ details the civil rights movement from its
earliest days through 1964, it does not pretend to be a balanced
account of the time, the authors say.
   None of those involved in the slayings were interviewed; none of
them was ever tried or convicted of murder in the case, though
seven were convicted on federal civil rights charges.
   ``We don't mind being one-sided in this case. What's the other
side?'' asked Cagin. ``That it's all right to go around killing
blacks? It's OK to murder civil rights workers?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 1-3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880620-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 2152EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Dean Adv01-03   06-20 0800</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Dean, Adv 01-03,0828</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<HEAD>Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>Adv03</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, July 1-3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: He Popularized ``Cotton-Eyed Joe''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Al Dean, who made ``Cotton-Eyed Joe''
one of the most popular country tunes ever, looks like a character
out of the ``Cowpokes'' comic strip, and is happiest mending ences
and corralling cattle.
   But though Dean would rather be out on the range, his music
always brings him to the bandstand one more time.
   The 57-year-old musician has gained regional popularity, but has
not fared as well financially as some of the other country
entertainers, including superstar George Strait, who once requested
to sing with Dean's band but was rejected.
   Dean's band still plays the song that continues to bring in the
bucks, but not much publicity.
   ``To this day, we play the `Cotton-Eyed Joe' twice a night and
sometimes three times a night,'' he said. ``If you're a
country-western band, and if you come to Texas, you'd better know
how to play the `Cotton-Eyed Joe.'
   ``There are several versions of the `Cotton-Eyed Joe,' but ours
is a magic mix and I don't think it can be duplicated.''
   ``Cotton-Eyed Joe,'' a mixture of fiddle, guitar and drum
rhythm, has been around as long as people can remember.
   It has been played in jukeboxes at roadside cafes and in
honky-tonks from Texas to Montana. It gained even more popularity
after it was featured in the movie ``Urban Cowboy.''
   The song is closely associated with a dance in which several
two-steppers, with their arms around each other's waists and
shoulders, move counter clockwise, taking several steps forward and
a few backward as they kick up their heels.
   The rhythm intensifies and the pros are quickly separated from
the amateurs.
   The song is known throughout the country, and is synonymous with
Texas, but Dean admits few people know the artist's name.
   ``There were times when people would try to impersonate me to
make some money,'' he said. ``People didn't know my face, so it was
hard to convince them that I was the real Al Dean.''
   The song, Dean says, gained popularity in Mexico because it was
released as a single with one of his other recordings, ``Jalisco.''
   Last year, the Texas Juke Box Dealers presented Dean with its
first classic music award for the most-played jukebox record in
Texas.
   Bud Daily, secretary-treasurer of the Daily Inc. record
distributing company, has distributed Dean's ``Cotton-Eyed Joe''
recording for almost a decade and is surprised by its continued
success.
   ``There must be several hundred versions of `Cotton-Eyed Joe'
that have been recorded down through the years, but Al Dean's has
just outlasted them,'' Daily said.
   ``I don't know what it is, but there is a certain chemistry that
comes together _ the beat, the sincerity with which the music is
played, the sincerity with which a singer projects and the
sincerity that comes together that makes the record.
   ``Al's got the perfect beat for the dance. The dancers like it
and it just works.''
   Dean's road to success started in rattlesnake-infested Freer,
Texas, a community midway between Corpus Christi and Laredo.
   In 1952, at age 22, he became the lead singer of the Texas
Teen-agers, a group of mostly high school kids who played in south
Texas. When they split up about two years later, Dean recorded a
few songs on his own in San Antonio, but with little success.
   Then, in 1967, he scraped up several thousand dollars, traveled
to Nashville and recorded his first album, ``Texas to Nashville,''
which had ``Cotton-Eyed Joe'' on it.
   The album was on Dean's independent ``KIK-R'' label, and he had
to work to get disc jockeys to play it.
   He was rejected, but later released ``Cotton-Eyed Joe'' and
``Jalisco'' as a single. Soon after, a San Antonio radio station
began playing the country tune, and requests came in for more
records.
   Dean recalls a certain day on the road with his band.
   ``I remember we were at the Dilley rodeo one day and some kid
comes up to the bandstand and says that he would like to sing a
song with us,'' Dean recalled. ``I told him flat out, `No. We don't
let people from the floor sing with the group.' It turned out to be
a young George Strait.''
   Dean said he still doesn't regret that decision, even though
Strait has gone on to garner numerous country music awards.
   Dean likes his music, but admits he would be fine without it.
   ``I'm just a cowboy at heart,'' he says. ``Give me a pair of
posthole diggers, some barb wire, a poor old horse and an old cow
to look after and I'm happy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, July 1-3</NOTE>
</DOC>
