<HEAD>Chicago Scientists' Instruments to Hitch Ride on Soviet Mars
Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When two Soviet spacecraft take off for Mars and
one of its moons in a couple weeks, soil analyzers designed by two
Chicago scientists will be aboard, even though the United States
isn't taking part in the project.
   The devices, in 6-inch, gold-plated boxes, are similar to those
Anthony L. Turkevich and Thanasis Economou developed in the 1960s
for three U.S. Surveyor missions that did the first chemical
analysis of the lunar surface.
   The Soviet probes will take off July 7 and July 12 for the
seven-month, 110-million-mile trip to Mars and Phobos. One will
orbit the planet; the other will drop a lander to analyze for the
first time the small, asteroid-like moon.
   Astronomers speculate Phobos may have been an asteroid captured
by Mars' gravity. The analyzer beams sub-atomic alpha particles
into the soil, and the rate and speed at which they bounce off
nuclei of atoms in the soil identifies its elements. High carbon
levels would indicate Phobos probably is a captured asteroid
containing traces of material left largely undisturbed since the
beginning of the solar system, Turkevich said.
   Soviet scientists asked Turkevich two years ago to build an
analyzer, but he couldn't get U.S. funding because of strained
superpower relations. Instead, he and Economou, a physicist, worked
with West Germans.
   The craft will include instruments from eight countries and the
European Space Agency. The Phobos probe will carry a plaque
commemorating the Martian moon's discovery in 1877 by American
astronomer Asaph Hall.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>High Cholesterol Among Children Often Undetected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANVILLE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High cholesterol often goes undetected in
children because doctors don't check family histories for early
heart attacks, and some pediatric cardiologists recommend
cholesterol tests for all 5-year-olds.
   ``We're really beginning to appreciate now this an inheritable
thing that gets passed on through the family,'' according to
Geisinger Medical Center head of pediatric cardiology Dr. John G.
Spangler. He said that doctors previoulsy believed diet and
lifestyle were the most important factors.
   Between 1 percent and 2 percent of all children have inherited
high cholesterol, said Dr. Jean A. Cortner, director of the
Lipid-Heart Research Center at Children's Hospital of Philadelphia.
Normal cholesterol for children measures about 150 miligrams per
100 cubic centimeters of blood. Children with inherited cholesterol
problems can have levels as high as 1,000, Spangler said.
   Cholesterol sticks to the lining of arteries, making it more
difficult for blood to flow to the heart. High cholesterol can
cause heart attacks in men as young as their 20s and women as young
as their 30s.
   Cholesterol levels often are associated with weight because one
source is fatty foods, but children with inherited high cholesterol
can be thin and appear healthy, Spangler said. In most cases, high
cholesterol can be controlled with diet, exercise and medication,
he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Skeleton Of Extinct Stag Moose Found In Illinois Cornfield</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TONICA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A museum crew looking for fossils along a
highway project found the bones of a stag moose that roamed the
United States 10,000 years ago and the logs of spruce trees that no
longer grow in the area.
   Only two other skeletons of the stag moose _ sort of a cross
between a moose and an elk that inhabited boggy areas until the
glaciers receded _ said Russell Graham, head of the Illinois State
Museum geology department. The other two skeletons, in New Jersey,
are from adults; the latest find is younger.
   ``This one will compare with the other two, which are adults,
and provide us with new information about how these animals
lived,'' Graham said. The logs will give information about the
environment in which the stag moose lived.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Doctors Urge Parents To Keep Ipecac As Poison Remedy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrup of ipecac can be used to induce vomiting in
small children who swallow some poisons, but two physicians found
that only a quarter of parents surveyed keep it and less than 10
percent of doctors dispense it.
   Those findings were reported in the June edition of the American
Journal of Diseases of Children by Dr. Michael H. Malloy and Dr.
George C. Rhoads of the National Institute of Child Health and
Human Development in Bethesda, Md.
   Pediatricians could increase home supplies by regularly
dispensing ipecac, wrote Malloy and Rhoads, but only 7 percent of
doctors they interviewed in the Washington, D.C., area did so.
   Dr. H. Juhling McClung of Children's Hospital in Columbus, Ohio,
warns in another article in the same AMA publication that easy
availability of ipecac has potential for child abuse and
self-induced vomiting.
</TEXT>
