<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Slightly Lower At Midday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: will be led with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were marginally lower in thin trading
at midday Monday amid concerns that interest rates were headed
higher.
   But prices got a slight lift following the late-morning release
of data showing that Britain's money supply and bank lending grew
at a slower rate in May than had been expected.
   At 1 p.m. local time, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was down 0.1 points, or 0.01 percent, at 1,850.0,
its best level for the day.
   The index hit a low of 6.9 points down when trading began.
   Volume was light at 155.2 million shares, compared with 289.8
million shares at the same time Friday.
   Dealers said that the money supply data, while better than
expected, did little to change the fundamental view that interest
rates were likely to rise, although perhaps not immediately.
</TEXT>
