<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0326</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks fell this morning in light trading, with
Wall Street brokers blaming the weakness on fears of
drought-spawned inflation and higher interest rates.
   The key Dow Jones industrial index lost 18.14 points by 11 a.m.
EDT to total 2,085.88.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues fell 0.98 to 151.86. On the
American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 0.89 to 304.81.
   Losing issues outnumbered gains by more than 2-to-1 on the NYSE,
with 794 down, 371 up and 495 unchanged. Volume totaled 38.75
million shares after the first 90 minutes of business.
   Anxiety over inflation and rising interest rates appeared to be
key elements in the weakness today, brokers said. Falling prices in
the bond market pushed the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond up to
9.15 percent by late morning, compared with 9.09 percent last
Friday and 8.81 percent last Tuesday.
   Fear of a prolonged drought in the Midwest wrenched up commodity
prices, another important inflation signal that contributed to the
uncertainty on Wall Street, persuading large institutional
investors to refrain from buying.
   ``The institutional business is nonexistent,'' said Philip C.
Puccio, senior vice president and manager of institutional trading
at Dillon Read & Co. in New York.
   Reports that leaders of the seven industrialized democracies
meeting in Toronto would tolerate higher interest rates added to
belief on Wall Street that tighter credit is looming.
   Johnson & Johnson was the Big Board's most active issue, down 1[
to 79~ on volume of more than 1.1 million shares. It was not
immediately clear what accounted for the stock activity.
   On the over-the-counter market, Farmers Group fell 4} to 57\ on
volume of nearly 1.2 million shares. Last Friday B.A.T. Industries
was denied regulatory approval to buy the company, an unexpected
setback.
