<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1448EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Soviet-Reforms     06-20 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Reforms,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Law on Cooperatives Criticized</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The manager of Moscow's first cooperative
restaurant said Monday a new law governing the businesses could
cause many to fold, rather than promote their growth.
   Andrei Fyodorov said the law, which goes into effect July 1,
contains ``unreasonable measures and could make the cooperative
movement null and void.''
   Fyodorov, who opened his Cafe Kropotkinskya No. 36 in March
1987, was one of several panelists at a briefing for journalists on
the new law.
   The Soviet parliament approved the law last month after Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev made clear he is depending on
development of cooperatives to provide consumer goods and services
the inefficient state-run economy cannot.
   But Fyodorov and another spokesman for cooperatives appeared
skeptical that the law will stimulate the businesses. The provision
most often attacked by cooperative managers sets a personal income
tax of 27 percent on a monthly income of 1,000 rubles (about
$1,600) and 53.5 percent on an income of 2,000 rubles (about
$3,200). The tax rate eventually reaches 90 percent.
   ``We view this as a blow against the cooperative movement,''
said Vladimir Sorokin, a cooperative spokesman who works for the
newspaper Literaturnaya Gazeta. ``It is very good theoretically,
but in practice it is bad.''
   Sorokin said the purpose of the cooperative is to increase
production, but taxation at the rate proposed will thwart ingenuity.
   ``Now we see they want to tax industrial attitude, or the
ability to organize our efforts and work more than eight hours a
day. If we develop our production in two or three years, but have
taxes, why should we do so?'' he asked.
   Soviet officials have made it clear the tax structure probably
will be reworked, sparking debate on how it should be changed.
   The disagreement is over whether to limit taxes at the central
government, whether to apply a uniform tax on cooperatives, or
whether to permit local authorities to set tax rates according to
local conditions.
   The Soviet Union has an estimated 20,000 cooperatives employing
300,000 people. They offer a range of services and products from
restaurants to agricultural goods.
   Yuri M. Lujkov of the Moscow City Soviet of People's Deputies
said the draft law would expand, rather than limit, the cooperative
movement.
   ``At the end of last year, we had 800 cooperatives in Moscow.
Less than six months have passed and we have more than 2,000. The
process is gaining momentum, especially with the adoption of the
draft law on cooperatives.''
   Lujkov said the main problems facing cooperatives are finding
staff and buildings.
   The law guarantees that cooperatives cannot be run out of
business by the state. It allows them to conduct business with
foreign companies and receive hard currency as payment, gives them
the right to own buildings and other property, and allows them to
appeal decisions by authorities not to license a cooperative.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
