<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     06-20 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0404</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market weakened today in light
trading, with Wall Street brokers blaming the decline largely on
fears of drought-spawned inflation and higher interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks lost 21.87 points
by 3 p.m. EDT to total 2,082.15.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues fell 0.97 to 151.87. On the
American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 0.93 to 304.77.
   Losing issues outnumbered gains by about a 9-to-5 margin on the
NYSE, with 888 down, 507 up and 524 unchanged. Volume totaled 98.94
million shares with an hour of business left.
   Anxiety over inflation and rising interest rates were key
elements in stock weakness today, brokers said.
   Fear of a prolonged drought in the Midwest wrenched up commodity
prices, an important inflation signal that contributed to the
uncertainty on Wall Street, persuading large institutional
investors to refrain from buying.
   ``The institutional business is nonexistent,'' said Philip C.
Puccio, senior vice president and manager of institutional trading
at Dillon Read & Co. in New York.
   Some traders concluded that leaders of the seven industrialized
democracies meeting in Toronto would tolerate higher interest
rates, adding to a belief on Wall Street that tighter credit is
looming.
   Robert O'Toole, manager of over-the-counter trading at Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York, said: ``Anytime somebody mentions
higher interest rates, that spooks us.''
   Most-active issues included Texaco, down | to 47] on volume
exceeding 2.1 million shares. The company's management has claimed
victory in a battle with takeover strategist Carl Icahn.
   American Cyanamid rose 2 to 52~ on rumors that the company may
be targeted in a takeover attempt. Kroger, another rumored takeover
target, fell } to 36.
   Johnson & Johnson fell 1 to 80 on volume exceeding 1 million
shares, an unusually busy volume. The company confirmed reports
that it bought a large block of stock as part of a share-repurchase
program.
   Among blue-chip stocks, Du Pont fell 1~ to 87}, McDonalds fell }
to 43~ and Bethlehem Steel fell | to 21].
   In the over-the-counter market, Farmers Group fell 4~ to 57[ on
volume exceeding 1.9 million shares. Last Friday B.A.T. Industries
was denied regulatory approval to buy the company, an unexpected
development.
</TEXT>
