<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-20 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board of Trade, Close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Except for wheat, all futures prices of grain and
soybeans shot up their daily limits at the opening Monday and
didn't budge all day in another drought-driven session on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Whenever a contract's price moves its daily limit, trading
ceases for that contract.
   The limit-up opening left only wheat futures open for trading,
which left most traders bored, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``I sat around and talked to people. I didn't do very much,'' he
said.
   Wheat futures are influenced less by the drought than corn,
oats, soybeans and soybean products because the winter wheat crop,
which accounts for 75 percent of U.S. production, is nearly
finished growing and is being harvested.
   Lespinasse said some private meteorologists had predicted light
rain for some parts of Illinois, Indiana and Ohio on Wednesday and
Thursday.
   ``But that's not for certain, of course, and judging by the way
the market reacted, it's going to stay hot and dry,'' he said.
   At the close, wheat was 10 cents to 19{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $4.01 a bushel; corn was 15 cents
higher across the board with July at $3.24{ a bushel; oats were 10
cents higher across the board with July at $3.08 a bushel; soybeans
were 30 cents higher across the board with July at $10.01{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
