<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0138</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market weakened today in light
trading, with Wall Street brokers blaming the decline largely on
fears of drought-spawned inflation and talk of higher interest
rates.
   ``Anytime somebody mentions higher interest rates, that spooks
us,'' said Robert O'Toole, manager of over-the-counter trading at
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   The slow trading volume suggested that large institutional
investors refrained from participating in the market. Brokers said
sharply higher commodity prices caused by fear of a prolonged
Midwest drought, combined with a belief that credit conditions will
tighten in coming months, were key reasons.
   ``All of that provides a classic backdrop for time-out,'' said
Joseph Barthel, a technical strategist with the Philadelphia
investment firm Butcher & Singer Inc.
</TEXT>
