<HEAD>Restaurant Chief At Pillsbury Resigns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 4 grafs to reflect Pillsbury's CORRECTION that
Campbell headed restaurant group for one year, sted five. Picks up
5th graf pvs, William H. Spoor ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. said Monday that the executive
who has headed its restaurant operations for just over a year has
resigned.
   The food giant said J. Jeffrey Campbell had resigned as chairman
and chief executive of Pillsbury's restaurant group, which includes
the fast-food chain Burger King.
   The company did not provide an explanation for Campbell's
resignation, and Campbell could not be reached immediately for
comment.
   He joined Burger King in 1971 and took over at Pillsbury's
restaurant group in May 1987.
   William H. Spoor, Pillsbury's chairman and chief executive, said
in a statement: ``We are grateful for Jeff's many contributions and
wish him every success in his new ventures.''
   One securities analyst said Campbell's resignation may have been
related to the performance of Pillsbury's restaurants, which he
said have lagged behind industry averages.
   ``I think they felt it was time to change the leadership to see
if that would be more instrumental in driving more positive
results,'' said Lawrence Adelman, an analyst with Dean Witter
Reynolds in New York.
   Pillsbury spokesman Larry Haeg said he would not comment on the
views of analysts. ``It was his decision and that's all I can
say,'' Haeg said.
</TEXT>
