<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-20 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0821</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Zoom Higher On Dry Weather</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices spurted sharply
higher Monday in another drought-driven session on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   On other markets, livestock and meat futures were mixed; oil
futures fell; precious metals were lower and stock-index futures
retreated.
   In another signal of rising prices, the Commodity Research
Bureau's index of 21 industrial and agricultural commodities rose
2.93 points to a four-year-high of 266.23.
   Except for wheat, all grain and soybean futures on the Chicago
Board of Trade shot up their daily allowable limits at the opening
bell and didn't budge all day.
   Whenever a futures contract's price moves its daily limit,
trading ceases in that contract. The limit-up opening left only
wheat futures open for trading, which in turn left most traders
``bored,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   ``I sat around and talked to people. I didn't do very much,'' he
said.
   Wheat futures were influenced less by the drought than corn,
oats and soybeans because the winter wheat crop, which accounts for
75 percent of U.S. production, is nearly finished growing and is
being harvested.
   Lespinasse said some private meteorologists had predicted light
rain for some parts of Illinois, Indiana and Ohio on Wednesday and
Thursday.
   ``But that's not for certain, of course, and judging by the way
the market reacted, it's going to stay hot and dry,'' he said.
``And as long as it's hot and dry, we'll keep going higher.''
   After the close, the National Weather Service issued a
six-to-10-day forecast predicting above-normal temperatures and
below-normal rainfall for the Grain Belt in the first five days of
next week.
   The near-month soybean contract, for July delivery, settled
above $10 a bushel, an 11-year high. Soybeans reached an all-time
high of $12.90 a bushel in June 1973.
   Wheat futures are at their highest level in nearly seven years.
Corn futures prices are at four-year highs.
   The Board of Trade said the daily limit on corn futures would
return to 10 cents a bushel on Tuesday. The limit was raised to 15
cents for three days, ending Monday, after all three corn contracts
for 1988 delivery finished up the limit on two consecutive days.
   Wheat settled 10 cents to 19} cents higher with the contract for
delivery in July at $4.01\ a bushel; corn was 15 cents higher
across the board with July at $3.24{ a bushel; oats were 10 cents
higher across the board with July at $3.08 a bushel; soybeans were
30 cents higher across the board with July at $10.01{ a bushel.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, traders used the phrase ``a
drought spread'' to describe Monday's pattern of widely mixed
prices for future delivery of livestock and meat.
   Most prices for summer and fall delivery moved lower in
anticipation of increased supplies as higher feed prices and
shrinking pasture land caused widespread slaughtering of animals,
analysts said.
   But prices for delivery in the winter and spring soared, some by
their permissable limits, on expectations that over the long term
the drought-related herd liquidation will result in a sharp drop in
supplies, said Thomas Morgan, president of Sterling Research Corp.
in Arlington Heights, Ill.
   Live cattle were .25 cents lower to 1.50 cents higher with June
at 70.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were 1.50 cents lower to 1.22
cents higher with August at 70.30 cents a pound; hogs were 1.27
cents lower to 1.50 cents higher with June at 50.45 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were 1.13 cents lower to 2 cents higher with
July at 41.97 cents a pound.
   Crude oil for near-month delivery on the New York Mercantile
Exchange fell to $16 a barrel for the first time since March 16 due
to an abundance of available crude oil, said John Azarow, an
analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 45 cents lower to 6
cents higher with July at $16 a barrel; heating oil was .25 cent to
.55 cent lower with July at 43.18 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .50 cent lower to .04 cent higher with July at 49.47 cents a
gallon.
   Gold and silver futures slipped lower on the Commodity Exchange
in New York in reaction to the drop in oil prices and the strength
of the dollar, analysts said.
   Gold settled $3.80 lower across the board with August at $454.50
a troy ounce; silver was 5.5 cents to 6 cents lower with July at
$7.195 a troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures dipped on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the contract for September delivery of the Standard & Poor's
500 index settled 1.25 points lower at 271.50.
</TEXT>
