<2ND_LINE>AM-Stuart Karl, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0198,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Video Wizard Pleads Innocent To Campaign Contribution Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New details thruout; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A video producer pleaded innocent
Monday to charges that he illegally donated nearly $200,000 to
several political candidates, including former Sen. Gary Hart.
   George Stuart Karl Jr., 34, of Newport Beach, who produced the
best-selling Jane Fonda ``Workout'' videos, pleaded innocent to six
counts of campaign financing law violations, one count of
conspiracy and five counts of filing false statements.
   He was ordered by U.S. Magistrate Ronald Rose to return for
trial on Aug. 23 before U.S. District Judge Alicemarie Stotler.
   Karl, who was indicted on June 9, posted $25,000 bail and
forfeited his passport.
   His attorneys and the prosecutor refused to comment on the case.
   If convicted of all charges, Karl faces a maximum sentence of 36
years in prison and $930,000 in fines.
   The indictment alleges that Karl asked former employees to
contribute up to $1,000 each to various candidates, then reimbursed
them in cash.
   The bulk of the donations, $159,500, went to Hart's 1984
presidential campaign, the indictment alleged.
   The indictment alleges about $38,000 in illegal contributions
were given to the 1986 Senate campaigns of John Kerry of
Massachusetts, Timothy Wirth of Colorado, Tom Daschle of South
Dakota, Bob Edgar of Pennsylvania, Patrick Leahy of Vermont and
Alan Cranston of California.
   The indictment also cites alleged donations to the unsuccessful
congressional campaign of Orange County Superior Court Judge David
O. Carter.
   In the indictment, Karl is accused of using his corporation,
Karl-Lorimar Home Video, to give an illegal $25,000 contribution to
a fund-raiser entitled ``An Evening With Barbra Streisand and Robin
Williams,'' which benefitted the various candidates.
   Karl founded the Karl Video Corp. in 1979, then sold it to
Lorimar in 1984 for an undisclosed amount. However, he became
president and chief executive of Karl-Lorimar Home Video division,
under contract until 1989.
   In March 1987, Karl resigned following conflict-of-interest
allegations. In November of that year, Lorimar-Telepictures filed
suit against Karl, alleging he violated terms of a financial
agreement when he resigned from Karl-Lorimar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
