<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Pillsbury-Campbell     06-20 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury-Campbell,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Restaurant Chief At Pillsbury Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. announced on Monday the
resignation of J. Jeffrey Campbell, who headed its restaurant
business for more than a year.
   Pillsbury also announced a series of other organizational
changes designed to implement its new strategic business plan and
streamline the structure of its senior management.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Pillsbury rose $1 a
share to $36.75.
   The company did not provide an explanation for the departure of
Campbell, who had responsibility since May 1987 for all of
Pillsbury's restaurant operations. He could not be reached for
comment.
   Campbell began his Pillsbury career in 1971 with Burger King,
the fast-food chain that is the centerpiece of the company's
restaurant business but whose future with Pillsbury has been the
subject of speculation in recent months.
   William H. Spoor, Pillsbury's chief executive, had said in March
that Burger King ``is central to Pillsbury'' and said the parent
company had no intention of selling the fast-food chain.
   In addition to Campbell's resignation as chairman and chief
executive of its restaurant group, Pillsbury announced the
following appointments:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Charles S. Olcott, 41, president of Burger King U.S.A., was
named president and chief operating officer of Burger King Corp.
with responsibility for U.S. and international operations.
   _Richard T. Crowder, 48, senior vice president and corporate
risk officer, was given the added responsibility of Distron, the
distribution and procurement division of Burger King.
   _Jerry W. Levin, 44, executive vice president for corporate
development, was given the added responsibility for S&A Restaurant
Corp., operators of Steak and Ale and Bennigan's restaurants.
   _John L. Morrison, 43, executive vice president and chairman of
Pillsbury U.S. Foods, was given added responsibility for The
Haagen-Dazs Co.
   Olcott, Crowder, Levin and Morrison will report directly to
Spoor, as will Russell J. Bragg, 52, vice president and group vice
president for industrial foods.
   ``We have streamlined our senior management structure to bring
added strength and focus to our most important growth
opportunities,'' Spoor said.
   Stephen Carnes, a securities analyst with Piper Jaffray &
Hopwood in Minneapolis, said Campbell's departure indicates a
desire to upgrade the restaurant group's performance but does not
signal a move away from the Burger King commitment.
   ``With his departure, it really says that Pillsbury is very
interested in building the restaurant business and restoring a
higher level of profitability,'' Carnes said.
   Carnes said the strategy laid out at Burger King ``had not
really been executed,'' and said he believes Campbell's resignation
at least indirectly resulted from Burger King's problems.
   Regarding the other changes, Carnes said the moves spreads out
responsibility and called newly organized team ``a good lineup.''
He said the men chosen for the new responsibilities fit well into
those jobs.
   Lawrence Adelman, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds in New
York, said Pillsbury ``felt it was time to change the leadership to
see if that would be more instrumental in driving more positive
results.
   ``I think they want to take a fresh approach to that business
unit,'' Adelman said. ``The future of Pillsbury is very closely
tied to Burger King.''
   Pillsbury spokesman Larry Haeg said he would not comment on the
views of analysts.
   ``It was his (Campbell's) decision and that's all I can say,''
Haeg said.
   Pillsbury's restaurant division accounted for about 45 percent
of the company's fiscal 1987 sales.
   Operating profits for the restaurant group for fiscal 1987 were
down 28 percent from fiscal 1986, but were ``essentially
unchanged'' from fiscal 1985, Haeg said. However, he was unable to
locate exact dollar figures late Monday. Adelman said average
dollar sales per Burger King unit have averaged about $1 million
for the past two years even though sales in the restaurant group
rose 4 percent to $2.03 billion in 1987 from $1.97 billion in 1986.
The increase was largely due to the addition of new stores, Haeg
said.
</TEXT>
