<1ST_LINE>u f AM-USX 1stLd-Writethru   06-20 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USX, 1st Ld-Writethru,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USX Sells Transportation Businesses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS five grafs at end with comment from Blackstone
spokesman.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. said Monday it plans to sell its
transportation businesses for more than $500 million to a joint
venture it is forming with Blackstone Capital Partners and managers
of the rail and water subsidiaries.
   Industry analysts called the planned sale a good move for the
oil and steel giant.
   The deal would raise the total of USX asset sales to $5.5
billion since David Roderick became chairman in 1979. It also would
pare USX's wholly owned transportation businesses to the petroleum
pipelines and ocean-going tankers of its Marathon Oil and Texas Oil
& Gas subsidiaries.
   Roderick has said USX intends to sell another $750 million in
assets over the next year and a half.
   The deal also would drain USX's Diversified Group of its largest
business segment, leaving realty, engineering and related
consulting and several other small businesses.
   ``It's a good approach,'' said George Gaspar, an analyst with
the investment firm Robert W. Baird and Co. Inc. in Milwaukee.
``The company wants to disengage from the direct, wholly-owned
operations that support its steel operations.''
   ``The cash they'll get will allow them more flexibility,''
Gaspar said, adding that USX might use the proceeds from the sale
to make an oil-relatd acquisition or repurchase its own stock.
   In consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading, USX shares
finished unchanged at $31.37{.
   Jeffrey Miller, an analyst with Duff & Phelps Inc. in Chicago,
said of the sale, ``It's good for them to concentrate on the energy
and the steel (segments).''
   Miller suggested USX use the cash from its asset sales to reduce
its debt.
   USX, based in Pittsburgh, signed a letter of intent with
Blackstone, leaving a definitive agreement to be negotiated and
regulatory approval, financing and USX board approval to be
obtained, USX said.
   The Blackstone Group was founded in 1985 by former Commerce
Secretary Peter G. Peterson and Stephen A. Schwarzman, former head
of mergers and acquisitions at Lehman Brothers Kuhn Loeb Inc.,
predecessor to Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The deal covers all USX's railroads: the Bessemer and Lake Erie;
Birmingham Southern; Duluth, Missabe and Iron Range; Elgin, Joliet
and Eastern; The Lake Terminal, and the Union Railroad.
   Warrior & Gulf Navigation Co., the Pittsburgh & Conneaut Dock
Co., and the USS Great Lakes Fleet Inc. also are included.
   The subsidiaries employ about 4,000 people who operate about 300
locomotives and 20,000 rail cars over more than 2,000 miles of
track as well as 14 lake vessels, 305 barges and 27 tugboats.
   The partners said they will assume labor contracts, recognize
employees' unions and pay comparable benefits to all employees.
They also anticipate no change in customer relations.
   Blackstone spokesman James Mossman said his firm believes the
units can expand their outside business. But he said the success of
the new company doesn't depend on that.
   The new company ``will be highly leveraged,'' Mossman
acknowledged.
   ``But the cash flows of these companies are quite strong and
even if there's a downturn we believe they'll still be able to
support the debt,'' he added.
   Mossman declined to disclose revenues and earnings of the
transportation units.
   But USX's published financial reports list their combined sales
at $353 million for 1987, a year in which they were likely hurt by
the effects of the company's six-month steel strike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
