<DOCNO> AP880620-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-88 1928EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Brunswick-Georgia-Pacific     06-20 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brunswick-Georgia-Pacific,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Georgia-Pacific to Buy Brunswick Pulp & Paper for $665 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp. announced Monday it has
agreed to buy Brunswick Pulp & Paper Co. for $665 million.
   Brunswick, which owns one of the world's largest bleached pulp
and paperboard mills at Brunswick, Ga., is a joint venture of Mead
Corp. and Scott Paper Co. The purchase includes that mill, three
sawmills and around 535,000 acres of timberland.
   The acquisition is subject to negotiation of a definitive
agreement, regulatory approvals and approvals by the companies'
boards of directors. Final approval is expected within two months,
according to an announcement from Georgia-Pacific.
   The Brunswick mill produces around 1,500 tons a day of bleached
softwood market pulp and 500 tons a day of bleached paperboard,
used to make products such as folding cartons, paper plates and
cups.
   ``This is an unusual opportunity to make a major acquisition of
strategic importance to our core business at an attractive price.
The Brunswick property provides world-class manufacturing capacity
with a strong fiber base,'' said T. Marshall Hahn Jr., chairman and
chief executive officer of Georgia-Pacific.
   Mead has been divesting itself of some basic commodity
operations so that it can invest in expansion of higher-value
coated paperboard.
   Philip E. Lippincott, Scott's chairman and chief executive
officer, said ``an increasingly greater proportion of Brunswick
Pulp & Paper Co.'s production is being directed to the worldwide
pulp market, a strategic direction which Scott is not emphasizing
for the future. At the same time, Scott is focusing its fiber
strategy on dedicated sources of strategic types of fiber, such as
eucalyptus, which Brunswick does not produce.''
   He said the sale is part of the company's plan to sell off parts
of its operation which do not fit its long-term strategy.
   Georgia-Pacific said the acquisition represents a significant
addition to its present position as a major producer of market
pulp, adding 525,000 tons a year to its current capacity of 700,00
tons.
   It also more than doubles Georgia-Pacific's bleached board
capacity, adding 175,000 tons to the 171,000-ton capacity of tis
facilty at Crossett, Ark.
   The 535,000 acres of timberland are located in areas where they
can be used by the Brunswick mill and other Georgia-Pacific
facilities in South Carolina, Georgia and Florida, the company said.
   The sawmills, located at Pearson and Sterling, Ga., and
McCormick, S.C., have a combined capacity of almost 200 million
board feet of Southern pine lumber products per year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
