<1ST_LINE>u f AM-LowRiver 1stLd-Writethru f0240 06-20 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Low River, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0240,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Creates More Problems For Mississippi River Shipping</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to add qualifier in 5th graf, change
predicted time of dredge arrival in 9th graf and UPDATE with stuck
barges freed, Coast Guard explaining why decision on closing
section of river has not been made yet. Picks up 11th graf pvs
``The low...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mississippi River's record low-water
levels caused by the drought in the Midwest and Plains threw more
roadblocks in the way of river barge shipping Monday.
   And authorities warned that sandbars exposed by the dropping
water are dangerous and claimed three lives over the weekend.
   ``A little rain at St. Louis is not what is needed,'' said Coast
Guard Lt. Phil Rhoades. ``A drenching of the entire Mississippi
drainage basin is needed, lots of water.''
   Towboats were freed during the weekend from backups caused by
shallow water and sandbars at Greenville, Miss., and on the Ohio
River after dredges cut fresh channels through the shallow river
bottoms.
   But Coast Guard Cmdr. Michael Donohoe said a low section of the
river six miles north of Memphis probably would be closed for
dredging and could stay closed for two days or more.
   And a barge ran aground early Monday in shallow water near
Gunnison, Miss., and engineers said it could take as long as three
days to dredge a deeper channel at that spot.
   The Mississippi at Memphis was more than 20 feet lower than this
time last year on Monday and 40 to 50 feet below its springtime
level, Donohoe said.
   The main channel was 9 feet deep, and perhaps a little less, for
about 1,000 feet at the low spot and the river's width there was
down from 500 feet to about 170 feet, he said.
   A Corps of Engineers dredge was expected to arrive Tuesday to
begin deepening the channel to 12 to 14 feet and widening it to 300
feet, Donohoe said.
   A decision on closing the river for the dredging or allowing
limited barge traffic while the work is under way would be made
Tuesday, said Lt. Tony Bauncore. ``If it can be done quicker with
it closed, we'll do that,'' Bauncore said.
   Four towboats with a total of about 35 barges were reported
grounded Monday at other low spots near Memphis, but Bauncore said
they all were eventually freed.
   Donohoe said towboats working in the Memphis area were being
limited to six barges each. The boats generally can handle 30 to 40
barges each, he said.
   The low water also exposed huge sandbars that were drawing
spectators dangerously close to the river.
   Three people drowned near Natchez, Miss., Sunday when a sandbar
they were walking on fell apart, said Rhoades.
   ``These sandbars have been under water and they're not stable,''
he said. ``If you've seen the side of a sandcastle just fall away,
that's basically what it can be if you're walking on a sandbar.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
